{"title_page": "ZZT", "text_new": "{{For|the German musical group|ZZT (duo)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = ZZT\n| image = ZZT_Title_screen.gif\n| caption = Title screen of Episode 1\n| developer = [[Potomac Computer Systems]]\n| publisher = Potomac Computer Systems\n| platforms = [[MS-DOS]]\n| released = {{Video game release|NA|October 1991}}\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]], [[Puzzle video game|puzzle]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| designer = [[Tim Sweeney (game developer)|Tim Sweeney]]\n}}\n\n'''''ZZT''''' is an [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[Puzzle video game|puzzle]] video game developed by [[Potomac Computer Systems]] and released for [[MS-DOS]] in October 1991. The game was designed by [[Tim Sweeney (game developer)|Tim Sweeney]] and took roughly nine months to develop, including the game's scripting language, ZZT-oop. The name was thought to be an acronym for \"Zoo of Zero Tolerance\", but Sweeney actually picked that name so it would be listed last alphabetically on the software catalog.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter2\">{{cite web|url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/265/page/2/epic-megagames-newsletter|title=Epic MegaGames Newsletter - Spring 1992|last=Sweeney|first=Tim|authorlink=Tim Sweeney (game developer)|date=1992|website=Museum of ZZT|publisher=Epic MegaGames|page=2|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> ''ZZT'' was followed by a sequel, ''Super ZZT'', in 1992.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe player character is controlled by the four cursor keys, and the shift key and a cursor key pressed will shoot a bullet (if the player has ammo). Items that can be picked up include: ammo (each magazine holds five rounds), gems (used for currency in most games), torches (used by pressing the T key in darkened rooms, lighting a small area around the player, that moves as the player does), and energizers that give the player temporary invincibility. Enemies include lions (randomly moving monsters that may follow the player), tigers (randomly moving monsters that fire bullets), ruffians (monsters that chase the player, then rest, then repeat), bears, slimes, centipedes, and spinning guns.\n\n== Development ==\n[[Video game programmer]] [[Tim Sweeney (game developer)|Tim Sweeney]], at the time attending the [[University of Maryland]], first developed ''ZZT'' as a [[text editor]] that ran in [[Pascal (programming language)|Pascal]].<ref name=\"ZZT-GU\">{{cite web |title=From The Past To The Future: Tim Sweeney Talks |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/132426/from_the_past_to_the_future_tim_.php |first=Benj |last=Edwards |website=[[Gamasutra]] |date=May 25, 2009 |accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> However, after experimenting with [[ASCII]] characters, Sweeney designed his first levels for what would become a video game.<ref name=\"ZZT-InterFanta\"/> The game took around nine months to develop,<ref name=\"ZZT-GU\"/> and was released in October 1991.<ref name=\"ZZT-InterFanta\">{{cite web |title=Hercules meets Tim Sweeney |url=http://if.digitalmzx.net/herculesmeets-timsweeney.shtml |author=Hercules |date=November 17, 2000 |website=[[DigitalMZX]] |accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nThird-party worlds created for ''ZZT'' were diverse, ranging from [[shoot 'em up]]s to complex [[role-playing video game|role-playing games]] to a ''[[Lemmings (video game)|Lemmings]]'' clone, ''Zem!''.<ref name=\"museum-Zem\">{{cite web |url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/170/closer-look-zem-and-zem-2 |title=Closer Look: Zem! and Zem! 2 |author=Dr. Dos| publisher=Museum of ZZT| date=24 August 2016}}</ref> Other games have been inspired by ''ZZT'', such as ''[[MegaZeux]]'', ''[[Frog Fractions 2]]'' and ''ZZT''{{'s}} sequel, ''[[Super ZZT]]'', the latter being widely criticized for lacking an easily accessible editor function, which was a mistake on Sweeney's part.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter2\"/> [[Computer Gaming World]] billed ''ZZT'' as the first major video game to use [[Object-oriented programming]].<ref name=\"ZZT-CGW\">{{cite magazine |author=Circle Reader Service #12 |date=July 1991 |title=Taking a Peek |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_84.pdf |magazine=Computer Gaming World |issue=84 |page=78 |issn=}}</ref>\n\nAlthough ''Super ZZT'' is in many ways a vast improvement over ''ZZT'', it never caught on with the ''ZZT'' community like the original ''ZZT'' did, and very few games were ever created for ''Super ZZT''.<ref name=\"ZZT-InterFanta\"/>\n\n=== Sales ===\nFollowing ''ZZT''{{'s}} release, the game sold about three to four copies daily, and as of 2009, had sold around 4,000 to 5,000 copies in total.<ref name=\"ZZT-GU\" /> After Sweeney moved out of his parents' house to establish proper corporate headquarters for Potomac Computer Systems, then renamed [[Epic MegaGames]], his father, Paul Sweeney, continued fulfilling mail orders to the original address under the \"Epic Classics\" label.<ref name=\"Polygon-Last\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/11/21/5128872/epic-classics-ships-last-copy-of-zzt |title=Epic Classics ships last copy of ZZT |first=Jenna |last=Pitcher |date=November 21, 2013 |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> The final copy of ''ZZT'' was shipped to game designer Zack Hiwiller in November 2013.<ref name=\"Polygon-Last\"/>\n\nAround 1992, after the custom world design contest, copies of the \"ZZT's Revenge\" collection was on sale with \"Best of ZZT\" shipped with it for free.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter3\">{{cite web|url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/265/page/3/epic-megagames-newsletter|title=Epic MegaGames Newsletter - Spring 1992|last=Sweeney|first=Tim|authorlink=Tim Sweeney (game developer)|date=1992|website=Museum of ZZT|publisher=Epic MegaGames|page=3|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Promotion ===\nShortly after the release of ZZT, Sweeney started a level designer contest for registered users to make their own worlds and submit them to him.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter\">{{cite web|url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/265/epic-megagames-newsletter|title=Epic MegaGames Newsletter - Spring 1992|last=Sweeney|first=Tim|authorlink=Tim Sweeney (game developer)|date=1992|website=Museum of ZZT|publisher=Epic MegaGames|page=1|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> Over 200 users submitted their custom worlds. The best collaboration games that won the contest were ''The Best of ZZT'' and ''ZZT's Revenge''. The winners of the contest received prizes of gift certificates. The six winning custom worlds that made up ZZT's Revenge earned the designers employment in Epic MegaGames. Other contestants got honorable mentions for good entries.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter3\"/>\n\nAround 1992, Sweeney started a contest titled \"ZZTaholics Challenge\" for players to play any of the ten volumes from ZZT, ZZT's Revenge and Super ZZT, then submit their high scores. The winners received discount coupons to get the next two releases from Epic MegaGames for free.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter2\"/>\n\n== Legacy ==\n=== Sequel ===\nSweeney collaborated with programmer Allen Pilgrim on creating a sequel to ''ZZT'' called ''Super ZZT'', which added more features and levels to ''ZZT''{{'s}} core gameplay. The game plays similarly to ''ZZT'', and incorporates floor textures, a different gameplay menu, prefabricated enemies and objects, and scrolling map screens, allowing for much larger worlds than in ''ZZT''.\n\n=== Third-party level editors ===\n<!-- editor note: [[KevEdit]] and [[ZZTAE]] redirect here -->\nIn addition to archive websites, several developers have released ZZT world editors such as KevEdit for Windows.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fz8lndvLhJQC&pg=PT441#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Retro Gaming Hacks: Tips & Tools for Playing the Classics|last=Kohler|first=Chris|publisher=O'Reilly|year=2006|isbn=9781449303907|edition=1st|location=Beijing|oclc=607589293}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/232/closer-look-modern-zzt-editing-with-kevedit|title=Closer Look: Modern ZZT Editing With KevEdit - Museum of ZZT|first=Dr.|last=Dos|date=|website=museumofzzt.com|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref> The external editors would have more features such as color coding objects, fade tools, and access to STK without downloading.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zzt.org/editors/|title=z2|first=|last=|date=|website=zzt.org|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref> DreamZZT was an emulator for the Dreamcast.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrqz84QUuSEC&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Gaming Hacks|last=Carless|first=Simon|publisher=O'Reilly|year=2004|isbn=9780596007140|edition=1st|location=Sebastopol, CA|pages=67|oclc=326649266}}</ref>\n\n=== Reconstructed source code ===\nTim Sweeney claims to have [[Digital obsolescence|lost]] the [[source code]] of ZZT in a [[Crash (computing)|crash]].<ref name=\"ZZT-GU\"/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/19991010013339/http://www.epicgames.com/zzt.htm zzt] on epicgames.com ''\"Please don't ask for the source; if I had it, I'd release it, but I lost it in a crash a long time ago.\"'' (archived in 1999)</ref> To compensate for this loss, a community developer [[reverse engineering|reconstructed]] the source code in 2020, with permission of Sweeney.<ref>[https://retronauts.com/article/1480/zzts-source-code-has-been-reconstructed ZZT's source code has been reconstructed - Reconstruction of ZZT is a game-changer for the ZZT community] on retronauts.com by Stuart Gipp (March 17, 2020)</ref> The reconstructed source code is binary accurate; when compiled with the originally used [[Turbo Pascal]] 5.5 [[compiler]] an identical [[.EXE]] file is generated. The source code is released under a [[permissive license|permissive]]<ref>[https://github.com/asiekierka/reconstruction-of-zzt/blob/master/LICENSE.TXT license.txt] on github.com/asiekierka/reconstruction-of-zzt</ref> [[software license]] on [[GitHub]].<ref>[https://github.com/asiekierka/reconstruction-of-zzt reconstruction-of-zzt] on [[github.com]]</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | authorlink=Anna Anthropy | first=Anna | last=Anthropy | title=ZZT | publisher=[[Boss Fight Books]] | year=2014 | isbn=978-1-940535-02-9}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Epic}}\n\n[[Category:1991 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:DOS-only games]]\n[[Category:Epic Games games]]\n[[Category:Video game development software]]\n[[Category:Video game engines]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the German musical group|ZZT (duo)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = ZZT\n| image = ZZT_Title_screen.gif\n| caption = Title screen of Episode 1\n| developer = [[Potomac Computer Systems]]\n| publisher = Potomac Computer Systems\n| platforms = [[MS-DOS]]\n| released = {{Video game release|NA|October 1991}}\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]], [[Puzzle video game|puzzle]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| designer = [[Tim Sweeney (game developer)|Tim Sweeney]]\n}}\n\n'''''ZZT''''' is an [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[Puzzle video game|puzzle]] video game developed by [[Potomac Computer Systems]] and released for [[MS-DOS]] in October 1991. The game was designed by [[Tim Sweeney (game developer)|Tim Sweeney]] and took roughly nine months to develop, including the game's scripting language, ZZT-oop. The name was thought to be an acronym for \"Zoo of Zero Tolerance\", but Sweeney actually picked that name so it would be listed last alphabetically on the software catalog.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter2\">{{cite web|url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/265/page/2/epic-megagames-newsletter|title=Epic MegaGames Newsletter - Spring 1992|last=Sweeney|first=Tim|authorlink=Tim Sweeney (game developer)|date=1992|website=Museum of ZZT|publisher=Epic MegaGames|page=2|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> ''ZZT'' was followed by a sequel, ''Super ZZT'', in 1992.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe player character is controlled by the four cursor keys, and the shift key and a cursor key pressed will shoot a bullet (if the player has ammo). Items that can be picked up include: ammo (each magazine holds five rounds), gems (used for currency in most games), torches (used by pressing the T key in darkened rooms, lighting a small area around the player, that moves as the player does), and energizers that give the player temporary invincibility. Enemies include lions (randomly moving monsters that may follow the player), tigers (randomly moving monsters that fire bullets), ruffians (monsters that chase the player, then rest, then repeat), bears, slimes, centipedes, and spinning guns.\n\n== Development ==\n[[Video game programmer]] [[Tim Sweeney (game developer)|Tim Sweeney]], at the time attending the [[University of Maryland]], first developed ''ZZT'' as a [[text editor]] that ran in [[Pascal (programming language)|Pascal]].<ref name=\"ZZT-GU\">{{cite web |title=From The Past To The Future: Tim Sweeney Talks |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/132426/from_the_past_to_the_future_tim_.php |first=Benj |last=Edwards |website=[[Gamasutra]] |date=May 25, 2009 |accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> However, after experimenting with [[ASCII]] characters, Sweeney designed his first levels for what would become a video game.<ref name=\"ZZT-InterFanta\"/> The game took around nine months to develop,<ref name=\"ZZT-GU\"/> and was released in October 1991.<ref name=\"ZZT-InterFanta\">{{cite web |title=Hercules meets Tim Sweeney |url=http://if.digitalmzx.net/herculesmeets-timsweeney.shtml |author=Hercules |date=November 17, 2000 |website=[[DigitalMZX]] |accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nThird-party worlds created for ''ZZT'' were diverse, ranging from [[shoot 'em up]]s to complex [[role-playing video game|role-playing games]] to a ''[[Lemmings (video game)|Lemmings]]'' clone, ''Zem!''.<ref name=\"museum-Zem\">{{cite web |url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/170/closer-look-zem-and-zem-2 |title=Closer Look: Zem! and Zem! 2 |author=Dr. Dos| publisher=Museum of ZZT| date=24 August 2016}}</ref> Other games have been inspired by ''ZZT'', such as ''[[MegaZeux]]'', ''[[Frog Fractions 2]]'' and ''ZZT''{{'s}} sequel, ''[[Super ZZT]]'', the latter being widely criticized for lacking an easily accessible editor function, which was a mistake on Sweeney's part.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter2\"/> [[Computer Gaming World]] billed ''ZZT'' as the first major video game to use [[Object-oriented programming]].<ref name=\"ZZT-CGW\">{{cite magazine |author=Circle Reader Service #12 |date=July 1991 |title=Taking a Peek |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_84.pdf |magazine=Computer Gaming World |issue=84 |page=78 |issn=}}</ref>\n\nAlthough ''Super ZZT'' is in many ways a vast improvement over ''ZZT'', it never caught on with the ''ZZT'' community like the original ''ZZT'' did, and very few games were ever created for ''Super ZZT''.<ref name=\"ZZT-InterFanta\"/>\n\n=== Sales ===\nFollowing ''ZZT''{{'s}} release, the game sold about three to four copies daily, and as of 2009, had sold around 4,000 to 5,000 copies in total.<ref name=\"ZZT-GU\" /> After Sweeney moved out of his parents' house to establish proper corporate headquarters for Potomac Computer Systems, then renamed [[Epic MegaGames]], his father, Paul Sweeney, continued fulfilling mail orders to the original address under the \"Epic Classics\" label.<ref name=\"Polygon-Last\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/11/21/5128872/epic-classics-ships-last-copy-of-zzt |title=Epic Classics ships last copy of ZZT |first=Jenna |last=Pitcher |date=November 21, 2013 |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> The final copy of ''ZZT'' was shipped to game designer Zack Hiwiller in November 2013.<ref name=\"Polygon-Last\"/>\n\nAround 1992, after the custom world design contest, copies of the \"ZZT's Revenge\" collection was on sale with \"Best of ZZT\" shipped with it for free.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter3\">{{cite web|url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/265/page/3/epic-megagames-newsletter|title=Epic MegaGames Newsletter - Spring 1992|last=Sweeney|first=Tim|authorlink=Tim Sweeney (game developer)|date=1992|website=Museum of ZZT|publisher=Epic MegaGames|page=3|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Promotion ===\nShortly after the release of ZZT, Sweeney started a level designer contest for registered users to make their own worlds and submit them to him.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter\">{{cite web|url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/265/epic-megagames-newsletter|title=Epic MegaGames Newsletter - Spring 1992|last=Sweeney|first=Tim|authorlink=Tim Sweeney (game developer)|date=1992|website=Museum of ZZT|publisher=Epic MegaGames|page=1|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> Over 200 users submitted their custom worlds. The best collaboration games that won the contest were ''The Best of ZZT'' and ''ZZT's Revenge''. The winners of the contest received prizes of gift certificates. The six winning custom worlds that made up ZZT's Revenge earned the designers employment in Epic MegaGames. Other contestants got honorable mentions for good entries.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter3\"/>\n\nAround 1992, Sweeney started a contest titled \"ZZTaholics Challenge\" for players to play any of the ten volumes from ZZT, ZZT's Revenge and Super ZZT, then submit their high scores. The winners received discount coupons to get the next two releases from Epic MegaGames for free.<ref name=\"EM-Newsletter2\"/>\n\n== Legacy ==\n=== Sequel ===\nSweeney collaborated with programmer Allen Pilgrim on creating a sequel to ''ZZT'' called ''Super ZZT'', which added more features and levels to ''ZZT''{{'s}} core gameplay. The game plays similarly to ''ZZT'', and incorporates floor textures, a different gameplay menu, prefabricated enemies and objects, and scrolling map screens, allowing for much larger worlds than in ''ZZT''.\n\n=== Third-party level editors ===\n<!-- editor note: [[KevEdit]] and [[ZZTAE]] redirect here -->\nIn addition to archive websites, several developers have released ZZT world editors such as KevEdit for Windows.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fz8lndvLhJQC&pg=PT441#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Retro Gaming Hacks: Tips & Tools for Playing the Classics|last=Kohler|first=Chris|publisher=O'Reilly|year=2006|isbn=9781449303907|edition=1st|location=Beijing|oclc=607589293}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://museumofzzt.com/article/232/closer-look-modern-zzt-editing-with-kevedit|title=Closer Look: Modern ZZT Editing With KevEdit - Museum of ZZT|first=Dr.|last=Dos|date=|website=museumofzzt.com|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref> The external editors would have more features such as color coding objects, fade tools, and access to STK without downloading.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zzt.org/editors/|title=z2|first=|last=|date=|website=zzt.org|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref> DreamZZT was an emulator for the Dreamcast.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrqz84QUuSEC&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Gaming Hacks|last=Carless|first=Simon|publisher=O'Reilly|year=2004|isbn=9780596007140|edition=1st|location=Sebastopol, CA|pages=67|oclc=326649266}}</ref>\n\n=== Reconstructed source code ===\nTim Sweeney claims to have [[Digital obsolescence|lost]] the [[source code]] of ZZT in a [[Crash (computing)|crash]].<ref name=\"ZZT-GU\"/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/19991010013339/http://www.epicgames.com/zzt.htm zzt] on epicgames.com ''\"Please don't ask for the source; if I had it, I'd release it, but I lost it in a crash a long time ago.\"'' (1997)</ref> To compensate for this loss, a community developer [[reverse engineering|reconstructed]] the source code in 2020, with permission of Sweeney.<ref>[https://retronauts.com/article/1480/zzts-source-code-has-been-reconstructed ZZT's source code has been reconstructed - Reconstruction of ZZT is a game-changer for the ZZT community] on retronauts.com by Stuart Gipp (March 17, 2020)</ref> The reconstructed source code is binary accurate; when compiled with the originally used [[Turbo Pascal]] 5.5 [[compiler]] an identical [[.EXE]] file is generated. The source code is released under a [[permissive license|permissive]]<ref>[https://github.com/asiekierka/reconstruction-of-zzt/blob/master/LICENSE.TXT license.txt] on github.com/asiekierka/reconstruction-of-zzt</ref> [[software license]] on [[GitHub]].<ref>[https://github.com/asiekierka/reconstruction-of-zzt reconstruction-of-zzt] on [[github.com]]</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | authorlink=Anna Anthropy | first=Anna | last=Anthropy | title=ZZT | publisher=[[Boss Fight Books]] | year=2014 | isbn=978-1-940535-02-9}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Epic}}\n\n[[Category:1991 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:DOS-only games]]\n[[Category:Epic Games games]]\n[[Category:Video game development software]]\n[[Category:Video game engines]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "name_user": "Hakken", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReconstructed source code", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZZT"}
{"title_page": "Simon Sch\u00fcrch", "text_new": "{{short description|Swiss rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Simon Sch\u00fcrch\n| image          = World Championships Corea.JPG\n| caption        = [[Mario Gyr]] and Sch\u00fcrch in 2013\n| nationality    = Swiss\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1990|12|2|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Rothrist]], Switzerland\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| country        = Switzerland\n| sport          = [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Rowing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|LM4\u2212]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Rowing Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 World Rowing Championships|2015 Aiguebelette]]|LM4\u2212}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2013 World Rowing Championships|2013 Chungjiu]]|LM2x}}\n}}\n'''Simon Sch\u00fcrch''' (born 2 December 1990) is a Swiss [[Rowing (sport)|rower]]. He won gold at the [[2016 Rio Olympics]] in the [[Rowing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|men's lightweight four]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/36687040 |title=Rio Olympics 2016: Switzerland edge Denmark to win lightweight four gold |date=11 August 2016 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref> with the team being coached by New Zealander [[Ian Wright (rower)|Ian Wright]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New Zealand's Ian Wright guides Switzerland to rowing gold at Rio Olympics |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/olympics/80130520/New-Zealands-Ian-Wright-guides-Switzerland-to-rowing-gold-at-Rio-Olympics |accessdate=30 September 2016 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=12 August 2016}}</ref> He has also competed in the [[Rowing at the 2012 Summer Olympics&nbsp;\u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|Men's lightweight coxless four]] event at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/sc/simon-schurch-1.html |title=Simon Sch\u00fcrch Olympic Results |accessdate=3 August 2012 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Olympic champions \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four}}\n{{World champions \u2013 Lightweight men's coxless four}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schurch, Simon}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Zofingen District]]\n[[Category:Swiss male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in rowing]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swiss rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Simon Sch\u00fcrch\n| image          = World Championships Corea.JPG\n| caption        = [[Mario Gyr]] and Sch\u00fcrch in 2013\n| nationality    = Swiss\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1990|12|2|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Rothrist]], Switzerland\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| country        = Switzerland\n| sport          = [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Rowing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|LM4\u2212]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Rowing Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 World Rowing Championships|2015 Aiguebelette]]|LM4\u2212}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2013 World Rowing Championships|2013 Chungjiu]]|LM2x}}\n}}\n'''Simon Sch\u00fcrch''' (born 2 December 1990) is a Swiss [[Rowing (sport)|rower]]. He won gold at the [[2016 Rio Olympics]] in the [[Rowing at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|men's lightweight four]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/36687040 |title=Rio Olympics 2016: Switzerland edge Denmark to win lightweight four gold |date=11 August 2016 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref> with the team being coached by New Zealander [[Ian Wright (rower)|Ian Wright]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New Zealand's Ian Wright guides Switzerland to rowing gold at Rio Olympics |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/olympics/80130520/New-Zealands-Ian-Wright-guides-Switzerland-to-rowing-gold-at-Rio-Olympics |accessdate=30 September 2016 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=12 August 2016}}</ref> He has also competed in the [[Rowing at the 2012 Summer Olympics&nbsp;\u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|Men's lightweight coxless four]] event at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/sc/simon-schurch-1.html |title=Simon Sch\u00fcrch Olympic Results |accessdate=3 August 2012 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Olympic champions \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four}}\n{{World champions \u2013 Lightweight men's coxless four}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schurch, Simon}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Zofingen District]]\n[[Category:Swiss male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in rowing]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Sch%C3%BCrch"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United Arab Emirates.svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in the United Arab Emirates (as of 10 February)<br />{{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}\n| map2            = \n| legend 2        = \n| map3            = \n| legend 3        = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Emirate of Dubai]]<br /> [[Emirate of Abu Dhabi]]\n| first_case      = [[Dubai]]\n| arrival_date    = 29 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=29|year 1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  = 588<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d>{{cite news |last=Sebugwaawo  |first=Ismail|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-reports-376-new-coronavirus-cases170-recoveries|title=Covid-19: UAE reports 376 new coronavirus cases, 170 recoveries|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=Khaleej Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 20<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| confirmed_cases = 3,736 (as of 11 April)<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| active_cases    = 3,128<ref name=\"stat.\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 CORONAVIRUS PANDEMIC |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |website=Worldometers |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| severe_cases    = 1<ref name=\"stat.\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| fatality_rate   = 0.007%\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://covid19.ncema.gov.ae/en}}\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[United Arab Emirates]] was announced on 29 January 2020. It was the first country in the [[Middle East]] to report a confirmed case.<ref>Turak, Natasha (29 January 2020). [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/29/first-middle-east-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-the-uae.html First Middle East cases of coronavirus confirmed in the UAE] ''CNBC.com.'' Retrieved 19 March 2020.</ref> The first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released on 9 February after recovering. The first two deaths were confirmed on March 20. On 22 March, [[Dubai]] started an 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus. Night curfew was imposed 4 days later while the country began disinfection. School closure was first announced on April 8 for 4 weeks. 3 weeks later, it was announced that school will be closed until the end of the academic year.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases chart}}\n\n===January 2020===\nOn 23 January, [[Abu Dhabi International Airport]] and [[Dubai International Airport]] announced that travelers arriving directly from China would have their temperatures screened.<ref name=\"Khaleej23Jan2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/uae/dubai/china-coronavirus-outbreak-dubai-to-screen-passengers|title=China coronavirus outbreak: Dubai to screen passengers|last=Reuters|date=23 January 2020|website=Khaleej Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/abu-dhabi-and-dubai-airports-to-screen-passengers-for-china-coronavirus-1.968492|title=Abu Dhabi and Dubai airports to screen passengers for China coronavirus|last=Kamel|first=Deena|date=23 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January, the first case in the UAE was confirmed to be a 73-year-old Chinese woman who came to the country on holiday with her family from Wuhan.<ref name=\"first case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hammond|first=Ashley|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-how-the-first-coronavirus-case-in-uae-was-cured-1.1581323524356|title=Watch: How the first coronavirus case in UAE was cured|date=10 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Chaudhary|first2=Suchitra Bajpai|last3=Hilotin|first3=Jay}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|title=Coronavirus in UAE: Four of a family infected|last=Nandkeolyar|first=Karishma|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129111625/https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The family of four, 36-year-old mother,<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" /> 38-year-old father,<ref name=\":0\" /> 10-year-old child,<ref name=\":0\" /> and the 73-year-old grandmother arrived in the Emirates on 16 January and took the grandmother to a doctor with flu-like symptoms on 23 January, where it was discovered that the family was infected.<ref name=\"Infected family UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|title=Coronavirus: UAE records first case|last=Duncan|first=Gillian|date=29 January 2020|work=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Gautam|first2=Shuchita|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129110532/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|archive-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> The announcement led to a sell out of face masks across the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|title=Coronavirus: face masks sell out across the UAE|last=Gautam|first=Shuchita|date=29 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129143403/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|title=Coronavirus: Most pharmacies in the UAE run out of face mask as residents rush to take protective measures|last=Ahmed|first=Ashfaq|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129140304/https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the fifth case of coronavirus in the UAE was confirmed, in someone who had travelled from Wuhan to Dubai.<ref name=\"fifth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|title=UAE announces new coronavirus case|website=The National|access-date=2020-02-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201185052/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref> The Dubai Health Authority (DHA) directed all DHA-licensed hospitals to consider all suspected and confirmed cases as emergencies and patients are to be treated free of charge, including those without insurance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|title=Coronavirus cases in UAE to be treated free of cost, insurance not necessary|first=Dhanusha|last=Gokulan|website=Khaleej Times|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206184719/https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|archive-date=2020-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 8 February, the sixth and seventh cases, of Chinese and a 43-year-old [[Filipino nationality|Filipino]], were confirmed.<ref name=\"sixth and seventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/2-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-1.1581134995319|title=2 new cases of coronavirus in UAE|date=8 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/chinese-filipino-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-in-uae-bringing-total-cases-to-7-1.1581142731007|title=Chinese, Filipino diagnosed with coronavirus in UAE, bringing total cases to 7|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|date=8 February 2020|website=Gulf News |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"seventh case UAE\">{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |title=Condition of Filipino coronavirus patient in UAE 'not improving', says diplomat |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/condition-of-filipino-coronavirus-patient-in-uae-not-improving-says-diplomat-1.69834108 |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February, the first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released after recovering.<ref name=\"first discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Abueish|first=Tamara|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/02/09/Woman-infected-with-coronavirus-cured-UAE-.html|title=Woman infected with coronavirus cured: UAE|date=9 February 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the eighth case was confirmed to be an Indian expatriate who had interacted with a recently diagnosed person.<ref name=\"eighth case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/indian-expat-in-uae-found-infected-by-coronavirus-1.1581392108339?slide=2|title=Indian expat in UAE found infected by coronavirus|date=11 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, two more patients recovered and were discharged from the hospital. The two patients were a 41-year-old Chinese father and his eight-year-old boy.<ref name=\"second discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/uae-announces-recovery-of-two-new-coronavirus-patients-1.1581704777547|title=UAE announces recovery of two new coronavirus patients|date=14 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, the ninth case was confirmed to be a 37-year old Chinese man.<ref name=\"ninth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-ninth-case-of-coronavirus-1.1581869353798|title=UAE announces ninth case of coronavirus|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, the tenth and eleventh case were confirmed to be a 34-year-old Filipino national and a 39-year-old Bangladeshi national who had contact with a Chinese national who had been diagnosed with the virus.<ref name=\"tenth and eleventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKBN20F28J|title=UAE records two new coronavirus cases, total number reaches 11|date=2020-02-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the government announced that two more people, a 70-year old Iranian visitor and his 64-year-old wife, have been diagnosed, taking the total to thirteen.<ref name=\"twelfth and thirteenth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/iranian-couple-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-uae-taking-number-of-cases-to-13-1.69875492|title=Iranian couple diagnosed with COVID-19 in UAE, taking number of cases to 13|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, six more new cases were announced, including four Iranians, one Bahraini and one Chinese national.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/six-new-cases-of-coronavirus-reported-in-uae-1.1582821151401|title=Six new cases of coronavirus reported in UAE|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that case 2, of the 36-year-old Chinese woman, and another 37-year-old Chinese person were discharged after recovering.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" />\n\nOn 28 February, two Italian technicians visiting the country to participate in the [[2020 UAE Tour|UAE Tour]], a top level cycling race, were tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-tour-cancelled-and-dozens-quarantined-as-two-participants-test-positive-1.985664|title=Coronavirus: UAE Tour cancelled and dozens quarantined as two participants test positive|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> 612 people involved in the UAE Tour were quarantined in the homes and the W Abu Dhabi hotel and the Crowne Plaza Abu Dhabi hotel, both in Yas Island, and the two hotels were put on lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aarons|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/27/chris-froome-facing-coronavirus-test-after-uae-tour-is-cancelled|title=Chris Froome facing coronavirus test after UAE Tour is cancelled|date=2020-02-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKCN20M1UW|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two Gulf hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en}}</ref> The 612 people were all screened and the results were negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/21-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-ministry|title=21 confirmed cases of coronavirus in UAE: Ministry|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/news/2020/02/28/cyclists-await-test-results-after-coronavirus-hits-uae-tour|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two UAE hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|website=www.gulf today.ae|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 1 March, six more people tested positive for the coronavirus in the UAE, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of infected persons to 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-six-more-cases-of-covid-19-1.987661|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces six more cases of Covid-19|website=thenational.ae}}</ref> The patients include two Russians, two Italians, a German and a Colombian citizen, who had been in contact with two Italian participants of the UAE Tour who tested positive for coronavirus at the weekend.\n\nOn 3 March, a 16-year-old female Indian student in Dubai tested positive for the coronavirus after  contracting it from her parent who came back after traveling abroad. The parent developed symptoms five days after returning to Dubai. Both the student and her family were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-dubai-school-pupil-tests-positive-for-covid-19-1.988293|title=Coronavirus: Dubai school pupil tests positive for Covid-19|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> On 5 March, the Ministry of Health and Prevention confirmed that a 17-year-old male Emirati student has tested positive for coronavirus and showed no symptoms of it. The student is now stable and is receiving necessary healthcare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-confirms-new-coronavirus-case-1.1583440148424|title=New 30th coronavirus case confirmed on student|website=Gulf News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, two Chinese patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the UAE to seven.<ref name=\"official numbers1\">{{cite news|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829181|title= UAE announces recovery of two cases of COVID-19|work=wam|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The two recoveries, a  38-year-old father and his 10-year-old child, were from the first family to contract the virus, and all members of the Chinese family are now virus-free.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/15-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-the-uae-2-chinese-patients-recover-1.1583547467978|title=15 new cases of coronavirus in the UAE, 2 Chinese patients recover|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that 15 cases of different nationalities have tested positive for the virus, taking to 45 the total infections in the country.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> 13 cases consisted of one individual each from Thailand, China, Morocco and India, two individuals each from Saudi Arabia, Ethiopia, Iran and three individuals from the UAE were detected through early reporting by individuals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khalid|first=Tuqa|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/07/UAE-confirms-15-new-coronavirus-cases-bringing-total-up-to-44.html|title=UAE confirms 15 new coronavirus cases bringing total up to 45|date=7 March 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> All these cases arrived from abroad.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> Two cases, each from the UAE and Egypt, have been diagnosed with the virus by active surveillance system for being in close contact with confirmed cases announced previously in connection with the UAE Tour.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" />\n\nOn 9 March, the UAE recorded 14 new cases, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of reported cases to 59. In a statement, the health ministry said the cases involve four Emiratis, three Italians, two Bangladeshis, two Nepalese, a Russian, an Indian and a Syrian national.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health ministry reports 14 new coronavirus cases |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829607 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-14-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1583753297673|title=14 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|access-date=9 March 2020 |work=Gulf News|date=9 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that two Emiratis, two Ethiopians and a Thai national recovered from the virus, bringing to 12 the total recovered cases in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Five more coronavirus patients recover in UAE: Health Ministry |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829635 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the UAE Ministry of Health and Prevention on Tuesday confirmed 15 new cases, bringing the total number of infected people in the country to 74. The 15 cases involve three Italians, two Emiratis, two from UK, two from Sri Lanka, two Indians, a German, a South African, a Tanzanian and an Iranian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-15-new-cases-announced|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 15 new cases announced|last=Wam|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that five cases recovered, consisting for three Emiratis, one Egyptian and one Moroccan.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ar:5 \u062d\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0634\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u0625\u0636\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u0635\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u062c\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 |url=https://www.wam.ae/ar/details/1395302829848 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=10 March 2020|language=ar|trans-title=Five additional recovery cases from the Coronavirus in the country}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, 11 new cases were announced, bring the total number of cases in the UAE to 85.<ref>{{cite news|last=Salman|first=Nour|url=https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830309|title=11 new COVID-19 cases in UAE: MoHAP|date=12 March 2020|work=Wam|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The individuals were placed under quarantine as suspected cases subsequent to their entry into the UAE and following required testing and monitoring, the individuals were confirmed to be positive. The 11 individuals diagnosed include two Italians, two Filipinos, one Montenegrin, one Canadian, one German, one Pakistani, one Emirati, one Russian and one British citizen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-uae-confirms-11-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 11 new cases of Covid-19|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that a Bangladeshi, a Chinese, and an Italian person recovered from the virus, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the country to 20.<ref name=\"recoveries2\">{{cite news |last=Alfaham |first= Tariq |title= Three more people recover from coronavirus in UAE |url= https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830394 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, 12 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 98. The patients are three Indians, and one each from the UAE, the Philippines, South Africa, Australia, China, Lebanon, the UK, Italy, and Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-confirms-12-new-cases-1.992864|title=12 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> \nOn the same day, 3 people have recovered from the virus bringing the total number to 26, the people are two Emiratis and an Indian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-three-more-recover-in-the-uae-1.992496|title= 3 new COVID-19 recoveries in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> On 18 March, 15 new cases were announced, with the total number of infected people to 113. Patients are from Kyrgyzstan, Serbia, Italy, Netherlands, Australia, Germany, USA, Greece, Russia, Ukraine, Bangladesh, Britain, and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-15-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.994024|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 15 new cases of Covid-19|website=The National}}</ref> On 19 March, UAE confirmed 27 new cases of the novel coronavirus on Thursday along with 30 recoveries in total.\nThe total number of COVID-19 cases in UAE stands at 140, Ministry of Health and Prevention said today in a press conference. Dr. Farida Al Hosani, Director of Communicable Diseases Department at the Health Department said the total number of cases have reached 140. She said five more cases have recovered including three Emiratis, one Syrian and one Sri Lankan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-27-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 27 new cases confirmed|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 20 March, the first two deaths were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-emirates-tally/uae-announces-first-two-deaths-from-coronavirus-wam-idUSKBN2173JU|title=UAE Announces First Two Deaths From Coronavirus: WAM|website=Reuters|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, The Ministry of Health and Prevention made the announcement. One of the two cases is 78-year old Arab national who came from Europe and tested positive for COVID-19 and died due to heart attack while the other is a 59-year-old Asian expat who was suffering from chronic diseases including heart disease and kidney failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/uae-announces-2-coronavirus-deaths-1.1584735850926|title=UAE announces 2 coronavirus deaths|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, there were seven recovery cases, but however, there were 13 new cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-13-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-1|title=Covid-19 in UAE: 13 new cases, seven recoveries confirmed|first=Web|last=Report|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] announced that it will be suspending all passenger flights effective March 25 in response to the coronavirus, but will continue to operate cargo flights for essential goods.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://apnews.com/10aa229f979a05241ede3c349f5e4d2d | title=Dubai's Emirates cuts passenger flights to 13 destinations| date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[UAE]] announces 45 new coronavirus cases. Total cases reported in the country are now 198.<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-45-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1584969735068|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 45 new coronavirus cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government urged people to stay in their homes and only leave home for an emergency or for work, said Ministry of Interior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-urges-people-to-stay-in-their-homes-1.1584916668613|title=Coronavirus: UAE urges people to stay in their homes|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government shut malls for two weeks. Fish, meat and vegetable markets also closed for a renewable period of two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-shuts-malls-for-two-weeks-1.1584914600541|title=Coronavirus: UAE shuts malls for two weeks|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government also suspended all passenger and transit flights. The suspension of flights will commence at 23:59 (UAE local time) on Wednesday 25 March and will last for an initial 14 days, subject to further directives by the relevant authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/aviation/coronavirus-uae-suspends-all-passenger-and-transit-flights-1.1584917287850|title=Coronavirus: UAE suspends all passenger and transit flights|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Telecommunications Regulatory Authority (UAE)|TRA]] unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid the coronavirus outbreak. The TRA explained that residents will now be able to use Microsoft Teams, Zoom and Blackboard, which are available on all networks in the country. Microsoft Skype for Business and Google Hangouts are compatible with fixed Internet networks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-tra-unblocks-skype-for-business-google-hangouts-amid-covid-19-outbreak-1.1585047632245|title=UAE: TRA unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid COVID-19 outbreak|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> Four new recovery cases and 50 new cases were confirmed. These new cases were among individuals who had close contact with cases announced previously, as well as people who returned from abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-50-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 50 new cases confirmed|website= www.khaleejtimes.com/}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, UAE announces 85 new cases, the total number of infections in the country reaches 333, with seven recoveries reported on Wednesday, March 25. The announcement was made during a regular media briefing held Wednesday, March 25 by Farida Al Hosani, official spokesperson of the UAE health sector. Seven people were recovered making the total recoveries in the UAE 52.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-announces-85-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585141534235|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 85 new COVID-19 cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, 64 people were arrested for breaking home quarantine after they came in direct contact with people infected with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/crime/coronavirus-uae-arrests-64-for-breaking-home-quarantine-law-1.1585155529277|title=Coronavirus: UAE arrests 64 for breaking home quarantine law|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, UAE 72 new cases and three recoveries were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-reports-72-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585331041900|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 72 new corona virus cases|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, UAE on Saturday announced 63 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total of confirmed cases to 468.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-63-new-cases-of-covid-19-on-saturday-1.1585401355346 |title = Coronavirus: UAE: 63 new cases of COVID-19 on Saturday}}</ref> On 29 March, UAE the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 102 new cases, taking the total cases in the country to 570. The 102 new cases patients consisted of one person from New Zealand, Slovakia, Morocco, Greece, China, France, Germany, Algeria, Iraq, Colombia, Venezuela, and Poland. Two people from Brazil, Sweden, Australia, Ethiopia, Canada, Lebanon, Sudan, Saudi Arabia, and Portugal. Three people from Italy and Ireland. Six people from Egypt. Seven people from the UAE and the Philippines. 16 people from Britain. 30 people from India. On the same day, the three new recoveries were announced takes the total tally of recoveries to 58, and another person died from the virus, taking the toll to three in UAE, until March 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-102-new-cases-announced-3-recoveries|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 102 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, UAE announced 41 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total number of confirmed cases in the country to 611. All are in stable condition except two, who are in critical condition. Two more deaths have been announced as well. The total death toll is now five. Three recoveries have also been announced - two Indians and one Filipino.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-41-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1585573506275|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 41 new corona virus cases|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 31 March, UAE The Ministry of Health and Prevention in the UAE has announced 53 new confirmed cases of the coronavirus and one death. The total cases reported in the country is now 664. One death has also been announced, taking the total toll to six. The new cases include one each from Algeria, Lebanon, Pakistan, Iran, Kuwait, Switzerland, Turkey, the Philippines, Italy, France, America and two people from Egypt, Nepal, three people from Britain, four people from the UAE, and as many as 31 people from India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-reports-53-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1585660904284|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 53 new corona virus cases|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Moreover, Al Ras area, one of the city's densely populated areas that's home to the gold souk and museums, was placed under lock down for two weeks starting 31 March preventing all residents from leaving or entering the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/dubai-locks-down-historic-neighborhood-to-prevent-virus-spread|title=Dubai Locks Down Historic Neighborhood to Prevent Virus Spread|last=Elbahrawy|first=Farah|date=31 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 150 new coronavirus cases for a total of 814, with a total number of eight deaths from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-150-new-cases-1|title=COVID-19: UAE confirms 150 new cases, two deaths|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 210 new cases for a total number of cases to 1,024, with 96 recoveries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302834594|title=COVID-19: Ministry of Health announces 210 new cases of COVID-19, 35 recoveries among various nationalities|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, 240 new cases were announced for a total of 1,264, with 108 having fully recovered, and one patient having died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-confirms-240-new-cases-on-friday |title= Covid-19: One expat dead, 240 new cases in UAE |website= Khaleej Times \\accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported another 241 new coronavirus cases, bringing the total number of COVID-19 patients to 1,505.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/covid-19-241-new-coronavirus-cases-reported-in-uae-on-saturday-1.1586001691620 |title=COVID-19: 1 death, 241 new coronavirus cases reported in UAE on Saturday  |website=gulfnews.com |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported 294 new cases of the COVID-19 coronavirus, taking the total number of cases in the country to 1,799. MoHAP also announced 19 new recoveries, taking the total number of recoveries to 144.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-294-new-cases-of-covid-19 |title= Coronavirus: UAE confirms 294 new cases, 19 recoveries |website=Khaleej Times |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported another 277 new coronavirus cases of different nationalities, bringing the total number of cases of infection to 2076, with 11 deaths from the virus, and a total of 167 recovered patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-277-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1586170041645 |title=COVID-19: UAE announces 277 new coronavirus cases, one death |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, The Ministry of Health and Community Protection announced it was monitoring 283 new cases of coronavirus, bringing the number of diagnosed cases to 2359. The Ministry also announced the total of the cases of recovery to 186, with a total number of 12 deaths due to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-283-new-cases-april-7-1- | title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 283 new cases of COVID-19 |website=Khaleej Times |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 300 new cases and 53 new recoveries were announced, with the total number of cases standing at 2,659, with 239 recoveries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-announces-300-new-cases-of-coronavirus |title=Covid-19: UAE announces 300 new cases of coronavirus - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, there were 331 new coronavirus cases and two deaths, with a total of 14 deaths.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/Covid-19-in-UAE-331-new-cases-29-recoveries-announced|title=Covid-19: The UAE reported 331 new coronavirus cases - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, there were 370 new confirmed cases, for a total of 3,360. 150 patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases to 418. There were two deaths from the virus, for a total of 16.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-370-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1586541879415|title=Covid-19: UAE announces 370 new coronavirus cases, two deaths - News |publisher=Gulf News|date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, there were 376 new cases of coronavirus, for a total of 3,736. The total number of recoveries rose to 588. Four patients died of the virus, bringing the total number of deaths to 20.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-reports-376-new-coronavirus-cases170-recoveries|title=Covid-19: UAE reports 376 new coronavirus cases, 170 recoveries - News |publisher=Khaleej Times|date= |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nOn 22 March, [[Dubai]] started a 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |last2=Nasrallah |first2=Tawfiq |title=Watch: Dubai starts massive coronavirus sterilisation drive |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-dubai-starts-massive-coronavirus-sterilisation-drive-1.70524415 |access-date=2020-03-20 |work=Gulf News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, the country imposed night curfew as disinfection in the country began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-uae-imposes-overnight-curfew-disinfection-campaign|title=Coronavirus: UAE imposes night curfew as it carries out disinfection campaign|website=Middle East Eye|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, Dubai lifted their ban on trucks weighting 2.5 tonnes.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://gulfnews.com/amp/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubai-temporarily-lifts-ban-on-movement-of-trucks-1.70618893 |title=Coronavirus: Dubai temporarily lifts ban on movement of trucks |publisher=Gulfnews.com |date=2020-03-25 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 28 March, the country announced that curfews and disinfection would be extended until April 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/443885-uae-extends-sterilisation-programme-until-april-5|title=UAE extends nationwide coronavirus disinfection programme, curfews until April 5|website=ArabianBusiness.com|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Abu Dhabi]] crown prince [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan|Mohammed bin Zayed]] announced that a new testing site has opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/28/UAE-launches-mobile-drive-through-coronavirus-test-center |title=UAE launches mobile drive-through coronavirus test center |publisher=Al Arabiya English |date=2020-03-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 29 March, the [[Dubai Metro]] and [[Dubai Tram]] were suspended until April 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubais-rta-extends-8pm-to-6am-public-transport-suspension-until-april-5-1.70694418 |title=Coronavirus: Dubai's RTA extends 8pm to 6am public transport suspension until April 5 &#124; Transport \u2013 Gulf News |publisher=Gulfnews.com |date=2020-03-29 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 31 March, [[Abu Dhabi]] installed a disinfection gate at one of its bus stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/31/abu-dhabi-sets-up-smart-disinfection-gate-at-main-bus-terminal/|title=Abu Dhabi sets up smart disinfection gate at main bus terminal\u00a0|website=The Filipino Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, [[Emirates SkyCargo]] suspended operations at the [[Al Maktoum International Airport]] and moved them to the [[Dubai International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alexander Cornwell |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/aviation/emirates-to-temporarily-shift-all-cargo-operations-to-dubai-airport |title=Emirates to temporarily shift all cargo operations to Dubai airport - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe following table does not include details on the categorization of tests, cases, and fatalities/deaths by state/territory/emirate.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Category:COVID-19 pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n**{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/uae |title=Coronavirus UAE updates and news |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in the UAE. |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian}}\n**[https://www.doh.gov.ae/covid-19 Department of Health UAE](in English, Arabic).\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|United Arab Emirates|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|United Arab Emirates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United Arab Emirates.svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in the United Arab Emirates (as of 10 February)<br />{{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}\n| map2            = \n| legend 2        = \n| map3            = \n| legend 3        = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Emirate of Dubai]]<br /> [[Emirate of Abu Dhabi]]\n| first_case      = [[Dubai]]\n| arrival_date    = 29 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=29|year 1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  = 588<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d>{{cite news |last=Sebugwaawo  |first=Ismail|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-reports-376-new-coronavirus-cases170-recoveries|title=Covid-19: UAE reports 376 new coronavirus cases, 170 recoveries|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=Khaleej Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 20<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| confirmed_cases = 3,736 (as of 11 April)<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| active_cases    = 3,128<ref name=\"stat.\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 CORONAVIRUS PANDEMIC |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |website=Worldometers |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| severe_cases    = 1<ref name=\"stat.\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| fatality_rate   = 0.007%\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://covid19.ncema.gov.ae/en}}\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[United Arab Emirates]] was announced on 29 January 2020. It was the first country in the [[Middle East]] to report a confirmed case.<ref>Turak, Natasha (29 January 2020). [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/29/first-middle-east-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-the-uae.html First Middle East cases of coronavirus confirmed in the UAE] ''CNBC.com.'' Retrieved 19 March 2020.</ref> The first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released on 9 February after recovering. The first two deaths were confirmed on March 20. On 22 March, [[Dubai]] started an 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus. Night curfew was imposed 4 days later while the country began disinfection. School closure was first announced on April 8 for 4 weeks. 3 weeks later, it was announced that school will be closed until the end of the academic year.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases chart}}\n\n===January 2020===\nOn 23 January, [[Abu Dhabi International Airport]] and [[Dubai International Airport]] announced that travelers arriving directly from China would have their temperatures screened.<ref name=\"Khaleej23Jan2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/uae/dubai/china-coronavirus-outbreak-dubai-to-screen-passengers|title=China coronavirus outbreak: Dubai to screen passengers|last=Reuters|date=23 January 2020|website=Khaleej Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/abu-dhabi-and-dubai-airports-to-screen-passengers-for-china-coronavirus-1.968492|title=Abu Dhabi and Dubai airports to screen passengers for China coronavirus|last=Kamel|first=Deena|date=23 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January, the first case in the UAE was confirmed to be a 73-year-old Chinese woman who came to the country on holiday with her family from Wuhan.<ref name=\"first case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hammond|first=Ashley|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-how-the-first-coronavirus-case-in-uae-was-cured-1.1581323524356|title=Watch: How the first coronavirus case in UAE was cured|date=10 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Chaudhary|first2=Suchitra Bajpai|last3=Hilotin|first3=Jay}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|title=Coronavirus in UAE: Four of a family infected|last=Nandkeolyar|first=Karishma|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129111625/https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The family of four, 36-year-old mother,<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" /> 38-year-old father,<ref name=\":0\" /> 10-year-old child,<ref name=\":0\" /> and the 73-year-old grandmother arrived in the Emirates on 16 January and took the grandmother to a doctor with flu-like symptoms on 23 January, where it was discovered that the family was infected.<ref name=\"Infected family UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|title=Coronavirus: UAE records first case|last=Duncan|first=Gillian|date=29 January 2020|work=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Gautam|first2=Shuchita|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129110532/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|archive-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> The announcement led to a sell out of face masks across the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|title=Coronavirus: face masks sell out across the UAE|last=Gautam|first=Shuchita|date=29 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129143403/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|title=Coronavirus: Most pharmacies in the UAE run out of face mask as residents rush to take protective measures|last=Ahmed|first=Ashfaq|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129140304/https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the fifth case of coronavirus in the UAE was confirmed, in someone who had travelled from Wuhan to Dubai.<ref name=\"fifth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|title=UAE announces new coronavirus case|website=The National|access-date=2020-02-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201185052/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref> The Dubai Health Authority (DHA) directed all DHA-licensed hospitals to consider all suspected and confirmed cases as emergencies and patients are to be treated free of charge, including those without insurance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|title=Coronavirus cases in UAE to be treated free of cost, insurance not necessary|first=Dhanusha|last=Gokulan|website=Khaleej Times|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206184719/https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|archive-date=2020-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 8 February, the sixth and seventh cases, of Chinese and a 43-year-old [[Filipino nationality|Filipino]], were confirmed.<ref name=\"sixth and seventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/2-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-1.1581134995319|title=2 new cases of coronavirus in UAE|date=8 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/chinese-filipino-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-in-uae-bringing-total-cases-to-7-1.1581142731007|title=Chinese, Filipino diagnosed with coronavirus in UAE, bringing total cases to 7|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|date=8 February 2020|website=Gulf News |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"seventh case UAE\">{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |title=Condition of Filipino coronavirus patient in UAE 'not improving', says diplomat |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/condition-of-filipino-coronavirus-patient-in-uae-not-improving-says-diplomat-1.69834108 |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February, the first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released after recovering.<ref name=\"first discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Abueish|first=Tamara|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/02/09/Woman-infected-with-coronavirus-cured-UAE-.html|title=Woman infected with coronavirus cured: UAE|date=9 February 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the eighth case was confirmed to be an Indian expatriate who had interacted with a recently diagnosed person.<ref name=\"eighth case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/indian-expat-in-uae-found-infected-by-coronavirus-1.1581392108339?slide=2|title=Indian expat in UAE found infected by coronavirus|date=11 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, two more patients recovered and were discharged from the hospital. The two patients were a 41-year-old Chinese father and his eight-year-old boy.<ref name=\"second discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/uae-announces-recovery-of-two-new-coronavirus-patients-1.1581704777547|title=UAE announces recovery of two new coronavirus patients|date=14 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, the ninth case was confirmed to be a 37-year old Chinese man.<ref name=\"ninth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-ninth-case-of-coronavirus-1.1581869353798|title=UAE announces ninth case of coronavirus|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, the tenth and eleventh case were confirmed to be a 34-year-old Filipino national and a 39-year-old Bangladeshi national who had contact with a Chinese national who had been diagnosed with the virus.<ref name=\"tenth and eleventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKBN20F28J|title=UAE records two new coronavirus cases, total number reaches 11|date=2020-02-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the government announced that two more people, a 70-year old Iranian visitor and his 64-year-old wife, have been diagnosed, taking the total to thirteen.<ref name=\"twelfth and thirteenth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/iranian-couple-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-uae-taking-number-of-cases-to-13-1.69875492|title=Iranian couple diagnosed with COVID-19 in UAE, taking number of cases to 13|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, six more new cases were announced, including four Iranians, one Bahraini and one Chinese national.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/six-new-cases-of-coronavirus-reported-in-uae-1.1582821151401|title=Six new cases of coronavirus reported in UAE|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that case 2, of the 36-year-old Chinese woman, and another 37-year-old Chinese person were discharged after recovering.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" />\n\nOn 28 February, two Italian technicians visiting the country to participate in the [[2020 UAE Tour|UAE Tour]], a top level cycling race, were tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-tour-cancelled-and-dozens-quarantined-as-two-participants-test-positive-1.985664|title=Coronavirus: UAE Tour cancelled and dozens quarantined as two participants test positive|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> 612 people involved in the UAE Tour were quarantined in the homes and the W Abu Dhabi hotel and the Crowne Plaza Abu Dhabi hotel, both in Yas Island, and the two hotels were put on lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aarons|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/27/chris-froome-facing-coronavirus-test-after-uae-tour-is-cancelled|title=Chris Froome facing coronavirus test after UAE Tour is cancelled|date=2020-02-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKCN20M1UW|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two Gulf hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en}}</ref> The 612 people were all screened and the results were negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/21-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-ministry|title=21 confirmed cases of coronavirus in UAE: Ministry|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/news/2020/02/28/cyclists-await-test-results-after-coronavirus-hits-uae-tour|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two UAE hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|website=www.gulf today.ae|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 1 March, six more people tested positive for the coronavirus in the UAE, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of infected persons to 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-six-more-cases-of-covid-19-1.987661|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces six more cases of Covid-19|website=thenational.ae}}</ref> The patients include two Russians, two Italians, a German and a Colombian citizen, who had been in contact with two Italian participants of the UAE Tour who tested positive for coronavirus at the weekend.\n\nOn 3 March, a 16-year-old female Indian student in Dubai tested positive for the coronavirus after  contracting it from her parent who came back after traveling abroad. The parent developed symptoms five days after returning to Dubai. Both the student and her family were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-dubai-school-pupil-tests-positive-for-covid-19-1.988293|title=Coronavirus: Dubai school pupil tests positive for Covid-19|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> On 5 March, the Ministry of Health and Prevention confirmed that a 17-year-old male Emirati student has tested positive for coronavirus and showed no symptoms of it. The student is now stable and is receiving necessary healthcare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-confirms-new-coronavirus-case-1.1583440148424|title=New 30th coronavirus case confirmed on student|website=Gulf News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, two Chinese patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the UAE to seven.<ref name=\"official numbers1\">{{cite news|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829181|title= UAE announces recovery of two cases of COVID-19|work=wam|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The two recoveries, a  38-year-old father and his 10-year-old child, were from the first family to contract the virus, and all members of the Chinese family are now virus-free.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/15-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-the-uae-2-chinese-patients-recover-1.1583547467978|title=15 new cases of coronavirus in the UAE, 2 Chinese patients recover|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that 15 cases of different nationalities have tested positive for the virus, taking to 45 the total infections in the country.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> 13 cases consisted of one individual each from Thailand, China, Morocco and India, two individuals each from Saudi Arabia, Ethiopia, Iran and three individuals from the UAE were detected through early reporting by individuals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khalid|first=Tuqa|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/07/UAE-confirms-15-new-coronavirus-cases-bringing-total-up-to-44.html|title=UAE confirms 15 new coronavirus cases bringing total up to 45|date=7 March 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> All these cases arrived from abroad.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> Two cases, each from the UAE and Egypt, have been diagnosed with the virus by active surveillance system for being in close contact with confirmed cases announced previously in connection with the UAE Tour.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" />\n\nOn 9 March, the UAE recorded 14 new cases, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of reported cases to 59. In a statement, the health ministry said the cases involve four Emiratis, three Italians, two Bangladeshis, two Nepalese, a Russian, an Indian and a Syrian national.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health ministry reports 14 new coronavirus cases |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829607 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-14-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1583753297673|title=14 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|access-date=9 March 2020 |work=Gulf News|date=9 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that two Emiratis, two Ethiopians and a Thai national recovered from the virus, bringing to 12 the total recovered cases in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Five more coronavirus patients recover in UAE: Health Ministry |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829635 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the UAE Ministry of Health and Prevention on Tuesday confirmed 15 new cases, bringing the total number of infected people in the country to 74. The 15 cases involve three Italians, two Emiratis, two from UK, two from Sri Lanka, two Indians, a German, a South African, a Tanzanian and an Iranian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-15-new-cases-announced|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 15 new cases announced|last=Wam|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that five cases recovered, consisting for three Emiratis, one Egyptian and one Moroccan.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ar:5 \u062d\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0634\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u0625\u0636\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u0635\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u062c\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 |url=https://www.wam.ae/ar/details/1395302829848 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=10 March 2020|language=ar|trans-title=Five additional recovery cases from the Coronavirus in the country}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, 11 new cases were announced, bring the total number of cases in the UAE to 85.<ref>{{cite news|last=Salman|first=Nour|url=https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830309|title=11 new COVID-19 cases in UAE: MoHAP|date=12 March 2020|work=Wam|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The individuals were placed under quarantine as suspected cases subsequent to their entry into the UAE and following required testing and monitoring, the individuals were confirmed to be positive. The 11 individuals diagnosed include two Italians, two Filipinos, one Montenegrin, one Canadian, one German, one Pakistani, one Emirati, one Russian and one British citizen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-uae-confirms-11-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 11 new cases of Covid-19|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that a Bangladeshi, a Chinese, and an Italian person recovered from the virus, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the country to 20.<ref name=\"recoveries2\">{{cite news |last=Alfaham |first= Tariq |title= Three more people recover from coronavirus in UAE |url= https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830394 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, 12 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 98. The patients are three Indians, and one each from the UAE, the Philippines, South Africa, Australia, China, Lebanon, the UK, Italy, and Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-confirms-12-new-cases-1.992864|title=12 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> \nOn the same day, 3 people have recovered from the virus bringing the total number to 26, the people are two Emiratis and an Indian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-three-more-recover-in-the-uae-1.992496|title= 3 new COVID-19 recoveries in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> On 18 March, 15 new cases were announced, with the total number of infected people to 113. Patients are from Kyrgyzstan, Serbia, Italy, Netherlands, Australia, Germany, USA, Greece, Russia, Ukraine, Bangladesh, Britain, and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-15-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.994024|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 15 new cases of Covid-19|website=The National}}</ref> On 19 March, UAE confirmed 27 new cases of the novel coronavirus on Thursday along with 30 recoveries in total.\nThe total number of COVID-19 cases in UAE stands at 140, Ministry of Health and Prevention said today in a press conference. Dr. Farida Al Hosani, Director of Communicable Diseases Department at the Health Department said the total number of cases have reached 140. She said five more cases have recovered including three Emiratis, one Syrian and one Sri Lankan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-27-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 27 new cases confirmed|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 20 March, the first two deaths were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-emirates-tally/uae-announces-first-two-deaths-from-coronavirus-wam-idUSKBN2173JU|title=UAE Announces First Two Deaths From Coronavirus: WAM|website=Reuters|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, The Ministry of Health and Prevention made the announcement. One of the two cases is 78-year old Arab national who came from Europe and tested positive for COVID-19 and died due to heart attack while the other is a 59-year-old Asian expat who was suffering from chronic diseases including heart disease and kidney failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/uae-announces-2-coronavirus-deaths-1.1584735850926|title=UAE announces 2 coronavirus deaths|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, there were seven recovery cases, but however, there were 13 new cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-13-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-1|title=Covid-19 in UAE: 13 new cases, seven recoveries confirmed|first=Web|last=Report|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] announced that it will be suspending all passenger flights effective March 25 in response to the coronavirus, but will continue to operate cargo flights for essential goods.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://apnews.com/10aa229f979a05241ede3c349f5e4d2d | title=Dubai's Emirates cuts passenger flights to 13 destinations| date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[UAE]] announces 45 new coronavirus cases. Total cases reported in the country are now 198.<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-45-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1584969735068|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 45 new coronavirus cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government urged people to stay in their homes and only leave home for an emergency or for work, said Ministry of Interior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-urges-people-to-stay-in-their-homes-1.1584916668613|title=Coronavirus: UAE urges people to stay in their homes|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government shut malls for two weeks. Fish, meat and vegetable markets also closed for a renewable period of two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-shuts-malls-for-two-weeks-1.1584914600541|title=Coronavirus: UAE shuts malls for two weeks|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government also suspended all passenger and transit flights. The suspension of flights will commence at 23:59 (UAE local time) on Wednesday 25 March and will last for an initial 14 days, subject to further directives by the relevant authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/aviation/coronavirus-uae-suspends-all-passenger-and-transit-flights-1.1584917287850|title=Coronavirus: UAE suspends all passenger and transit flights|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Telecommunications Regulatory Authority (UAE)|TRA]] unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid the coronavirus outbreak. The TRA explained that residents will now be able to use Microsoft Teams, Zoom and Blackboard, which are available on all networks in the country. Microsoft Skype for Business and Google Hangouts are compatible with fixed Internet networks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-tra-unblocks-skype-for-business-google-hangouts-amid-covid-19-outbreak-1.1585047632245|title=UAE: TRA unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid COVID-19 outbreak|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> Four new recovery cases and 50 new cases were confirmed. These new cases were among individuals who had close contact with cases announced previously, as well as people who returned from abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-50-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 50 new cases confirmed|website= www.khaleejtimes.com/}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, UAE announces 85 new cases, the total number of infections in the country reaches 333, with seven recoveries reported on Wednesday, March 25. The announcement was made during a regular media briefing held Wednesday, March 25 by Farida Al Hosani, official spokesperson of the UAE health sector. Seven people were recovered making the total recoveries in the UAE 52.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-announces-85-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585141534235|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 85 new COVID-19 cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, 64 people were arrested for breaking home quarantine after they came in direct contact with people infected with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/crime/coronavirus-uae-arrests-64-for-breaking-home-quarantine-law-1.1585155529277|title=Coronavirus: UAE arrests 64 for breaking home quarantine law|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, UAE 72 new cases and three recoveries were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-reports-72-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585331041900|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 72 new corona virus cases|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, UAE on Saturday announced 63 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total of confirmed cases to 468.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-63-new-cases-of-covid-19-on-saturday-1.1585401355346 |title = Coronavirus: UAE: 63 new cases of COVID-19 on Saturday}}</ref> On 29 March, UAE the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 102 new cases, taking the total cases in the country to 570. The 102 new cases patients consisted of one person from New Zealand, Slovakia, Morocco, Greece, China, France, Germany, Algeria, Iraq, Colombia, Venezuela, and Poland. Two people from Brazil, Sweden, Australia, Ethiopia, Canada, Lebanon, Sudan, Saudi Arabia, and Portugal. Three people from Italy and Ireland. Six people from Egypt. Seven people from the UAE and the Philippines. 16 people from Britain. 30 people from India. On the same day, the three new recoveries were announced takes the total tally of recoveries to 58, and another person died from the virus, taking the toll to three in UAE, until March 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-102-new-cases-announced-3-recoveries|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 102 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, UAE announced 41 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total number of confirmed cases in the country to 611. All are in stable condition except two, who are in critical condition. Two more deaths have been announced as well. The total death toll is now five. Three recoveries have also been announced - two Indians and one Filipino.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-41-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1585573506275|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 41 new corona virus cases|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 31 March, UAE The Ministry of Health and Prevention in the UAE has announced 53 new confirmed cases of the coronavirus and one death. The total cases reported in the country is now 664. One death has also been announced, taking the total toll to six. The new cases include one each from Algeria, Lebanon, Pakistan, Iran, Kuwait, Switzerland, Turkey, the Philippines, Italy, France, America and two people from Egypt, Nepal, three people from Britain, four people from the UAE, and as many as 31 people from India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-reports-53-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1585660904284|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 53 new corona virus cases|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Moreover, Al Ras area, one of the city's densely populated areas that's home to the gold souk and museums, was placed under lock down for two weeks starting 31 March preventing all residents from leaving or entering the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/dubai-locks-down-historic-neighborhood-to-prevent-virus-spread|title=Dubai Locks Down Historic Neighborhood to Prevent Virus Spread|last=Elbahrawy|first=Farah|date=31 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 150 new coronavirus cases for a total of 814, with a total number of eight deaths from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-150-new-cases-1|title=COVID-19: UAE confirms 150 new cases, two deaths|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 210 new cases for a total number of cases to 1,024, with 96 recoveries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302834594|title=COVID-19: Ministry of Health announces 210 new cases of COVID-19, 35 recoveries among various nationalities|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, 240 new cases were announced for a total of 1,264, with 108 having fully recovered, and one patient having died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-confirms-240-new-cases-on-friday |title= Covid-19: One expat dead, 240 new cases in UAE |website= Khaleej Times \\accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported another 241 new coronavirus cases, bringing the total number of COVID-19 patients to 1,505.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/covid-19-241-new-coronavirus-cases-reported-in-uae-on-saturday-1.1586001691620 |title=COVID-19: 1 death, 241 new coronavirus cases reported in UAE on Saturday  |website=gulfnews.com |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported 294 new cases of the COVID-19 coronavirus, taking the total number of cases in the country to 1,799. MoHAP also announced 19 new recoveries, taking the total number of recoveries to 144.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-294-new-cases-of-covid-19 |title= Coronavirus: UAE confirms 294 new cases, 19 recoveries |website=Khaleej Times |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported another 277 new coronavirus cases of different nationalities, bringing the total number of cases of infection to 2076, with 11 deaths from the virus, and a total of 167 recovered patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-277-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1586170041645 |title=COVID-19: UAE announces 277 new coronavirus cases, one death |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, The Ministry of Health and Community Protection announced it was monitoring 283 new cases of coronavirus, bringing the number of diagnosed cases to 2359. The Ministry also announced the total of the cases of recovery to 186, with a total number of 12 deaths due to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-283-new-cases-april-7-1- | title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 283 new cases of COVID-19 |website=Khaleej Times |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 300 new cases and 53 new recoveries were announced, with the total number of cases standing at 2,659, with 239 recoveries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-announces-300-new-cases-of-coronavirus |title=Covid-19: UAE announces 300 new cases of coronavirus - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, there were 331 new coronavirus cases and two deaths, with a total of 14 deaths.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/Covid-19-in-UAE-331-new-cases-29-recoveries-announced|title=Covid-19: The UAE reported 331 new coronavirus cases - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, there were 370 new confirmed cases, for a total of 3,360. 150 patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases to 418. There were two deaths from the virus, for a total of 16.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-370-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1586541879415|title=Covid-19: UAE announces 370 new coronavirus cases, two deaths - News |publisher=Gulf News|date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, there were 376 new cases of coronavirus, for a total of 3,736. The total number of recoveries rose to 588. Four patients died of the virus, bringing the total number of deaths to 20.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-reports-376-new-coronavirus-cases170-recoveries|title=Covid-19: UAE reports 376 new coronavirus cases, 170 recoveries - News |publisher=Khaleej Times|date= |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nOn 22 March, [[Dubai]] started a 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |last2=Nasrallah |first2=Tawfiq |title=Watch: Dubai starts massive coronavirus sterilisation drive |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-dubai-starts-massive-coronavirus-sterilisation-drive-1.70524415 |access-date=2020-03-20 |work=Gulf News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, the country imposed night curfew as disinfection in the country began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-uae-imposes-overnight-curfew-disinfection-campaign|title=Coronavirus: UAE imposes night curfew as it carries out disinfection campaign|website=Middle East Eye|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, Dubai lifted their ban on trucks weighting 2.5 tonnes.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://gulfnews.com/amp/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubai-temporarily-lifts-ban-on-movement-of-trucks-1.70618893 |title=Coronavirus: Dubai temporarily lifts ban on movement of trucks |publisher=Gulfnews.com |date=2020-03-25 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 28 March, the country announced that curfews and disinfection would be extended until April 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/443885-uae-extends-sterilisation-programme-until-april-5|title=UAE extends nationwide coronavirus disinfection programme, curfews until April 5|website=ArabianBusiness.com|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Abu Dhabi]] crown prince [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan|Mohammed bin Zayed]] announced that a new testing site has opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/28/UAE-launches-mobile-drive-through-coronavirus-test-center |title=UAE launches mobile drive-through coronavirus test center |publisher=Al Arabiya English |date=2020-03-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 29 March, the [[Dubai Metro]] and [[Dubai Tram]] were suspended until April 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubais-rta-extends-8pm-to-6am-public-transport-suspension-until-april-5-1.70694418 |title=Coronavirus: Dubai's RTA extends 8pm to 6am public transport suspension until April 5 &#124; Transport \u2013 Gulf News |publisher=Gulfnews.com |date=2020-03-29 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 31 March, [[Abu Dhabi]] installed a disinfection gate at one of its bus stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/31/abu-dhabi-sets-up-smart-disinfection-gate-at-main-bus-terminal/|title=Abu Dhabi sets up smart disinfection gate at main bus terminal\u00a0|website=The Filipino Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, [[Emirates SkyCargo]] suspended operations at the [[Al Maktoum International Airport]] and moved them to the [[Dubai International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alexander Cornwell |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/aviation/emirates-to-temporarily-shift-all-cargo-operations-to-dubai-airport |title=Emirates to temporarily shift all cargo operations to Dubai airport - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Category:COVID-19 pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n**{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/uae |title=Coronavirus UAE updates and news |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in the UAE. |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian}}\n**[https://www.doh.gov.ae/covid-19 Department of Health UAE](in English, Arabic).\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|United Arab Emirates|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|United Arab Emirates]]\n", "name_user": "217.164.12.107", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_Arab_Emirates"}
{"title_page": "Thullum Kaalam", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Thullum Kaalam\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = A. Sarana\n| producer       = Lakshmi\n| writer         = A. Sarana\n| starring       = {{ubl|Shankar|Heera|Megha}}\n| music          = S. P. Boopathy\n| cinematography = P. Sundarraj\n| editing        = P. A. Balamurugan\n| distributor    =\n| studio         = Lakshmi Shankar Movies\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2005|07|29}}\n| runtime        = 145 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Thullum Kaalam''''' is a [[Tamil films of 2005|2005]] Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[drama film]] directed and written by A. Sarana, making his directorial debut. The film features newcomers Shankar, Heera and Megha in lead roles, with [[Vineetha]], [[Rajeev (Tamil actor)|Rajeev]], [[Sriman (actor)|Sriman]], [[Pallavi (actress)|Pallavi]], Rajini Nivetha and [[Kumarimuthu]] playing supporting roles. The film had musical score by S. P. Boopathy and was released on 29 July 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woodsdeck.com/movies/3303-thullum-kaalam-2005|title=Thullum Kaalam Tamil Movie|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=woodsdeck.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointscene.com:80/movies/Kollywood/Thullum_Kaalam_/1883|title=Find Tamil Movie Thullum Kaalam|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813175456/http://www.jointscene.com/movies/Kollywood/Thullum_Kaalam_/1883|archive-date=13 August 2010|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=jointscene.com|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/inside-story/article2581046.ece|title=Inside story |author=S. R. Ashok Kumar|date=23 June 2012|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/audio-beat-sokkali/article3562727.ece|title=Audio Beat: Sokkali|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/news/tamil/sokkali-a-playboy-story-with-no-vulgarity/53251/story.htm|title='Sokkali'&nbsp;- a playboy story with no 'vulgarity'|date=27 June 2012|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=nowrunning.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nSindhuraj alias Sindhu (Shankar) is a carefree [[twelfth grade|plus two]] student who lives in [[Polur]] with his elder sister Porkodi ([[Vineetha]]), the village teacher whereas his elder brother Santhosh (Murugan) is an upright military officer. Porkodi lives only for her brothers and would do anything for her brothers. Sindhu always hangs out with his friends and enjoys teasing the villagers. Tamizhselvi (Heera) is a hard-working and haughty plus two student who hates her cousin Sindhu. After successfully passing the exam, Sindhu and his friends decide to pursue a [[Bachelor of Science|bachelor's degree in science]] and apply to one of the colleges in the city.\n\nAt the college, his college mate Divya (Megha) fall in love with him, she is from a rich background. At the annual inter-college competition, Sindhu sings a song and won the first prize making the college proud. Later, Santhosh, on the holiday, returns to his village from the military camp. Her sister wants her brother Santhosh to marry her cousin Thamizhselvi but Thamizhselvi refuses to marry him for not getting enough money and humiliates them. When Divya wanted to introduce her lover Sindhu to her parents, Sindhu stood them up for various reasons. The first time, he got an opportunity to sing in a concert, so Divya's parents were understanding. While the second time, it was the last of college, therefore, his friends and he celebrated and got drunk, Divya and her parents were disappointed that he did not come. Worried about Sindhu, Divya goes to his college dorm and she sees the drunk Sindhu talks ill about her. The next day, Sindhu realizes his mistake and apologizes to Divya. Divya, who sincerely loved him, tells him that he was too reckless and immature to be her life partner. Divya and her parents are about to leave the country to settle down to the [[United States|USA]] and before leaving, she tells Sindhu that he has missed an opportunity to make it big in life.\n\nThereafter, all his friends decide to pursue a [[Master of Science|master's degree in science]] while Sindhu has to clear all his arrears to complete his bachelor degree. Sindhu finds himself alone, isolated and mocked by the villagers. In the meantime, Thamizhselvi, who refused to marry grooms for not being rich enough, finally agrees to marry a doctor when she discovers that her mother (Rajini Nivetha) has [[cardiovascular disease]]. The day of the wedding, the groom demands a huge dowry but Thamizhselvi's mother tells them that she has not that much money and the wedding is cancelled. The carefree Sindhu and arrogant Thamizhselvi who both fail in life decide to marry. Sindhu then gets an opportunity to sing in a feature film. The film ends with Sindhu and Thamizhselvi living happily.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n*Shankar as Sindhuraj alias Sindhu\n*Heera as Thamizhselvi\n*Megha as Divya\n*[[Vineetha]] as Porkodi\n*[[Rajeev (Tamil actor)|Rajeev]] as Divya's father\n*[[Sriman (actor)|Sriman]] as Meter Govind\n*[[Pallavi (actress)|Pallavi]] as Divya's mother\n*Rajini Nivetha as Thamizhselvi's mother\n*[[Kumarimuthu]] as Ekambaram\n*[[Kadhal Sukumar]] as Sindhu's friend\n*Kottachi as Sindhu's friend\n*Bayilvan Ranganathan\n*Manager Cheena\n*Murugan as Santhosh\n*Mimicry Senthil as Ganesh,  Sindhu's friend\n*[[Tharika]] as an item number\n*[[Viveka (lyricist)|Viveka]] in a cameo appearance\n{{colend}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Thullum Kaalam\n| type       = [[soundtrack]]\n| artist     = S. P. Boopathy\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 2005\n| recorded   = 2005\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 26:51\n| label      =\n| producer   = S. P. Boopathy\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe film score and the soundtrack were composed by [[film composer]] S. P. Boopathy. The soundtrack, released in 2005, features 5 tracks with lyrics written by [[Viveka (lyricist)|Viveka]], Victor Doss and Dr. Kiruthaya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mio.to/album/Thullum+Kaalam+(2005)|title=Thullum Kaalam (2005)&nbsp;- Bhoopathy SP|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=mio.to}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/thullum-kaalam-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-ep/1126700101|title=Thullum Kaalam (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=itunes.apple.com}}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Track !! Song !! Singer(s) !! Duration\n|-\n|1 || 'Thullum Kaalam' || [[Tippu (singer)|Tippu]] || 4:45\n|-\n|2 || '60 Vayathil' || Prasanna Rao || 5:13\n|-\n|3 || 'Thai Piranthathu' || Prabhu, Priya || 5:40\n|-\n|4 || 'Chembaruthi' || [[Harish Raghavendra]] || 6:06\n|-\n|5 || 'Ekkalira' || [[Srilekha Parthasarathy]] || 5:07\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2005 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:2005 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Thullum Kaalam\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = A. Sarana\n| producer       = Lakshmi\n| writer         = A. Sarana\n| starring       = {{ubl|Shankar|Heera|Megha}}\n| music          = S. P. Boopathy\n| cinematography = P. Sundarraj\n| editing        = P. A. Balamurugan\n| distributor    =\n| studio         = Lakshmi Shankar Movies\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2005|07|29}}\n| runtime        = 145 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Thullum Kaalam''''' is a [[Tamil films of 2005|2005]] Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[drama film]] directed and written by A. Sarana, making his directorial debut. The film features newcomers Shankar, Heera and Megha in lead roles, with [[Vineetha]], [[Rajeev (Tamil actor)|Rajeev]], [[Sriman (actor)|Sriman]], [[Pallavi (actress)|Pallavi]], Rajini Nivetha and [[Kumarimuthu]] playing supporting roles. The film had musical score by S. P. Boopathy and was released on 29 July 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woodsdeck.com/movies/3303-thullum-kaalam-2005|title=Thullum Kaalam Tamil Movie|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=woodsdeck.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointscene.com:80/movies/Kollywood/Thullum_Kaalam_/1883|title=Find Tamil Movie Thullum Kaalam|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813175456/http://www.jointscene.com/movies/Kollywood/Thullum_Kaalam_/1883|archive-date=13 August 2010|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=jointscene.com|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/inside-story/article2581046.ece|title=Inside story |author=S. R. Ashok Kumar|date=23 June 2012|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/audio-beat-sokkali/article3562727.ece|title=Audio Beat: Sokkali|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/news/tamil/sokkali-a-playboy-story-with-no-vulgarity/53251/story.htm|title='Sokkali'&nbsp;- a playboy story with no 'vulgarity'|date=27 June 2012|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=nowrunning.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nSindhuraj alias Sindhu (Shankar) is a carefree [[twelfth grade|plus two]] student who lives in [[Polur]] with his elder sister Porkodi ([[Vineetha]]), the village teacher whereas his elder brother Santhosh (Murugan) is an upright military officer. Porkodi lives only for her brothers and would do anything for her brothers. Sindhu always hangs out with his friends and enjoys teasing the villagers. Tamizhselvi (Heera) is a hard-working and haughty plus two student who hates her cousin Sindhu. After successfully passing the exam, Sindhu and his friends decide to pursue a [[Bachelor of Science|bachelor's degree in science]] and apply to one of the colleges in the city.\n\nAt the college, his college mate Divya (Megha) fall in love with him, she is from a rich background. At the annual inter-college competition, Sindhu sings a song and won the first prize making the college proud. Later, Santhosh, on the holiday, returns to his village from the military camp. Her sister wants her brother Santhosh to get married to her cousin Thamizhselvi but Thamizhselvi refuses to marry him for not getting enough money and humiliates them. When Divya wanted to introduce her lover Sindhu to her parents, Sindhu stood them up for various reasons. The first time, he got an opportunity to sing in a concert, so Divya's parents were understanding. While the second time, it was the last of college, therefore, his friends and he celebrated and got drunk, Divya and her parents were disappointed that he did not come. Worried about Sindhu, Divya goes to his college dorm and she sees the drunk Sindhu talks ill about her. The next day, Sindhu realizes his mistake and apologizes to Divya. Divya, who sincerely loved him, tells him that he was too reckless and immature to be her life partner. Divya and her parents are about to leave the country to settle down to the [[United States|USA]] and before leaving, she tells Sindhu that he has missed an opportunity to make it big in life.\n\nThereafter, all his friends decide to pursue a [[Master of Science|master's degree in science]] while Sindhu has to clear all his arrears to complete his bachelor degree. Sindhu finds himself alone, isolated and mocked by the villagers. In the meantime, Thamizhselvi, who refused to marry grooms for not being rich enough, finally accepts to get married to a doctor when she discovers that her mother (Rajini Nivetha) has [[cardiovascular disease]]. The day of the wedding, the groom demands a huge dowry but Thamizhselvi's mother tells them that she has not that much money and the wedding is cancelled. The carefree Sindhu and arrogant Thamizhselvi who both fail themselves in life decide to get married. Sindhu then gets an opportunity to sing in a feature film. The film ends with Sindhu and Thamizhselvi living happily.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n*Shankar as Sindhuraj alias Sindhu\n*Heera as Thamizhselvi\n*Megha as Divya\n*[[Vineetha]] as Porkodi\n*[[Rajeev (Tamil actor)|Rajeev]] as Divya's father\n*[[Sriman (actor)|Sriman]] as Meter Govind\n*[[Pallavi (actress)|Pallavi]] as Divya's mother\n*Rajini Nivetha as Thamizhselvi's mother\n*[[Kumarimuthu]] as Ekambaram\n*[[Kadhal Sukumar]] as Sindhu's friend\n*Kottachi as Sindhu's friend\n*Bayilvan Ranganathan\n*Manager Cheena\n*Murugan as Santhosh\n*Mimicry Senthil as Ganesh,  Sindhu's friend\n*[[Tharika]] as an item number\n*[[Viveka (lyricist)|Viveka]] in a cameo appearance\n{{colend}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Thullum Kaalam\n| type       = [[soundtrack]]\n| artist     = S. P. Boopathy\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 2005\n| recorded   = 2005\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 26:51\n| label      =\n| producer   = S. P. Boopathy\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe film score and the soundtrack were composed by [[film composer]] S. P. Boopathy. The soundtrack, released in 2005, features 5 tracks with lyrics written by [[Viveka (lyricist)|Viveka]], Victor Doss and Dr. Kiruthaya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mio.to/album/Thullum+Kaalam+(2005)|title=Thullum Kaalam (2005)&nbsp;- Bhoopathy SP|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=mio.to}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/thullum-kaalam-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-ep/1126700101|title=Thullum Kaalam (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)|accessdate=1 May 2018|publisher=itunes.apple.com}}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Track !! Song !! Singer(s) !! Duration\n|-\n|1 || 'Thullum Kaalam' || [[Tippu (singer)|Tippu]] || 4:45\n|-\n|2 || '60 Vayathil' || Prasanna Rao || 5:13\n|-\n|3 || 'Thai Piranthathu' || Prabhu, Priya || 5:40\n|-\n|4 || 'Chembaruthi' || [[Harish Raghavendra]] || 6:06\n|-\n|5 || 'Ekkalira' || [[Srilekha Parthasarathy]] || 5:07\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2005 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:2005 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thullum_Kaalam"}
{"title_page": "David Robertson (broadcaster)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n'''David Robertson''' (born 1965 in [[Dundee]]) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] former journalist and newsreader for [[Reporting Scotland]] from 2000-2008.\n\n== Career == \nRobertson's career began at Dundee radio station [[Radio Tay]]. He joined the BBC in the late 1980s, as a [[BBC]] reporter and correspondent, covering the Bosnian War from [[Sarajevo]] and reporting from the USA, Germany and Spain. He was also a presenter in the early days of [[BBC News 24]] on the Breakfast show. \n2000-2008, Robertson worked as a presenter on ''[[Reporting Scotland]]'', joining established presenters Jackie Bird and Sally Magnusson. Briefly during this period he also had a news quiz show on [[BBC Radio Scotland]].\nOn Friday 19 September 2008, he announced that he had been with the BBC for twenty years, presenting ''[[Reporting Scotland]]'' for eight, was honoured to have done so, and that this was his last appearance.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/7626441.stm</ref>\n\nIt emerged that the BBC had ended his employment.<ref>http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/entertainment-news/2008/09/24/bbc-newsreader-david-robertson-in-pay-off-row-after-reporting-scotland-exit-86908-20750188/</ref> Press reports claimed he sought a compensatory pay-off from [[BBC Scotland]] on the grounds that he was sacked by the corporation, rather than resigning.<ref>http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/62715/Sacked-newsreader-in-fight-for-100-000</ref>\n\nRobertson was Head of Public Affairs for the Wise Group, a social enterprise aiming to provide work focused solutions to social exclusion through employment, regeneration and sustainable development. He has recently worked for the Cell Therapy Catapult as Head of Communications and Marketing, and is currently Head of Public Relations, EMEA for the US biotech company, Illumina.\n\n== Popular culture ==\n\nIn January 2008, David Robertson's apparently regular on-air pen trick during Reporting Scotland was spotted and highlighted in the media <ref>http://www.sundaymail.co.uk/tv-showbiz-news/entertainment-news/2008/01/27/bbc-newsman-s-disappearing-act-78057-20300140/</ref> and on [[YouTube]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R24fyrs6ofo</ref> by Scottish comedian [[Limmy]].\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robertson, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Dundee]]\n[[Category:British reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Grove Academy]]\n\n\n{{scotland-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n'''David Robertson''' (born 1965 in [[Dundee]]) is a former [[Scottish people|Scottish]] journalist and newsreader for [[Reporting Scotland]] from 2000-2008.\n\n== Career == \nRobertson's career began at Dundee radio station [[Radio Tay]]. He joined the BBC in the late 1980s, as a [[BBC]] reporter and correspondent, covering the Bosnian War from [[Sarajevo]] and reporting from the USA, Germany and Spain. He was also a presenter in the early days of [[BBC News 24]] on the Breakfast show. \n2000-2008, Robertson worked as a presenter on ''[[Reporting Scotland]]'', joining established presenters Jackie Bird and Sally Magnusson. Briefly during this period he also had a news quiz show on [[BBC Radio Scotland]].\nOn Friday 19 September 2008, he announced that he had been with the BBC for twenty years, presenting ''[[Reporting Scotland]]'' for eight, was honoured to have done so, and that this was his last appearance.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/7626441.stm</ref>\n\nIt emerged that the BBC had ended his employment.<ref>http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/entertainment-news/2008/09/24/bbc-newsreader-david-robertson-in-pay-off-row-after-reporting-scotland-exit-86908-20750188/</ref> Press reports claimed he sought a compensatory pay-off from [[BBC Scotland]] on the grounds that he was sacked by the corporation, rather than resigning.<ref>http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/62715/Sacked-newsreader-in-fight-for-100-000</ref>\n\nRobertson was Head of Public Affairs for the Wise Group, a social enterprise aiming to provide work focused solutions to social exclusion through employment, regeneration and sustainable development. He has recently worked for the Cell Therapy Catapult as Head of Communications and Marketing, and is currently Head of Public Relations, EMEA for the US biotech company, Illumina.\n\n== Popular culture ==\n\nIn January 2008, David Robertson's apparently regular on-air pen trick during Reporting Scotland was spotted and highlighted in the media <ref>http://www.sundaymail.co.uk/tv-showbiz-news/entertainment-news/2008/01/27/bbc-newsman-s-disappearing-act-78057-20300140/</ref> and on [[YouTube]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R24fyrs6ofo</ref> by Scottish comedian [[Limmy]].\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robertson, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Dundee]]\n[[Category:British reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Grove Academy]]\n\n\n{{scotland-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Narky Blert", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Robertson_(broadcaster)"}
{"title_page": "Comet Humason", "text_new": ":''There is another long-period comet named Humason: [[C/1960 M1]] (a.k.a. 1959 X, 1960e).''\n\n{{Infobox Comet\n| name=C/1961 R1 (Humason)\n| image= Comet Humason (Palomar) September 4, 1962.jpg\n| caption= Comet Humason on Septebmer 4, 1962, by [[Palomar Observatory]]\n| discoverer=[[Milton L. Humason]]\n| discovery_date=1961-Sep-01\n| epoch=1962-Dec-02\n| obs_arc = 4.15 yr\n| perihelion=2.1334 AU (q)\n| aphelion=406.91 [[Astronomical unit|AU]]\n| eccentricity=0.98956\n| period=2883 years (barycentric inbound)<br/> 2516 years (barycentric outbound)\n| inclination=153.27\u00b0\n| last_p=1962-Dec-10<ref name=jpldata/>\n| dimensions = 30\u221241 km<ref name=Irish1964/>\n}}\n\n----\n'''Comet Humason''', [[Astronomical naming conventions#Comets|formally designated]] '''C/1961 R1''' (a.k.a. '''1962 VIII''' and '''1961e'''), was a [[List of non-periodic comets|non-periodic]] [[comet]] discovered by [[Milton L. Humason]] on September 1, 1961. Its [[perihelion]] was well beyond the orbit of [[Mars]], at 2.133 [[Astronomical unit|AU]]. The outbound orbital period is about 2516 years. The diameter of its [[comet nucleus]] is estimated at around 30\u221241 km.<ref name=Irish1964/>\n\nIt was a 'giant' comet, much more active than a normal comet for its distance to the [[Sun]], with an [[Absolute magnitude#Cometary magnitudes|absolute magnitude]] of 1.5\u22123.5, it could have been up to a hundred times brighter than an average new comet. It had an unusually disrupted or 'turbulent' appearance.<ref name=brandt>Brandt & Chapman, ''Introduction to Comets'', Cambridge University Press, 2004, p.156</ref> It was also unusual in that the spectrum of its tail showed a strong predominance of the ion CO+, a result previously seen unambiguously only in [[Comet Morehouse]] (C/1908 R1).<ref name=heubner>Huebner, W. ''Physics and chemistry of comets'', Springer-Verlag, 1990, p.246</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs =\n\n<ref name=jpldata>{{cite web\n  |type=last observation: 1965-11-01\n  |title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser: C/1961 R1 (Humason)\n  |url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=1961R1\n  |publisher=[[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n  |accessdate=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Irish1964>{{cite journal\n  |title=Comets : Comet Humason 1961e\n  |journal=[[Irish Astronomical Journal]]\n  |volume=6 |pages=191 |year=1964\n  |bibcode=1964IrAJ....6Q.191.}}</ref>\n\n}} <!-- end of reflist -->\n\n{{Comets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Humason, 1961 R1}}\n[[Category:Non-periodic comets]]\n[[Category:1961 in science]]\n\n\n{{comet-stub}}\n", "text_old": ":''There is another long-period comet named Humason: [[C/1960 M1]] (a.k.a. 1959 X, 1960e).''\n\n{{Infobox Comet\n| name=C/1961 R1 (Humason)\n| image= Comet Humason (Palomar) Septebmer 1, 1962.jpg\n| caption= Comet Humason on Septebmer 1, 1962, by [[Palomar Observatory]]\n| discoverer=[[Milton L. Humason]]\n| discovery_date=1961-Sep-01\n| epoch=1962-Dec-02\n| obs_arc = 4.15 yr\n| perihelion=2.1334 AU (q)\n| aphelion=406.91 [[Astronomical unit|AU]]\n| eccentricity=0.98956\n| period=2883 years (barycentric inbound)<br/> 2516 years (barycentric outbound)\n| inclination=153.27\u00b0\n| last_p=1962-Dec-10<ref name=jpldata/>\n| dimensions = 30\u221241 km<ref name=Irish1964/>\n}}\n\n----\n'''Comet Humason''', [[Astronomical naming conventions#Comets|formally designated]] '''C/1961 R1''' (a.k.a. '''1962 VIII''' and '''1961e'''), was a [[List of non-periodic comets|non-periodic]] [[comet]] discovered by [[Milton L. Humason]] on September 1, 1961. Its [[perihelion]] was well beyond the orbit of [[Mars]], at 2.133 [[Astronomical unit|AU]]. The outbound orbital period is about 2516 years. The diameter of its [[comet nucleus]] is estimated at around 30\u221241 km.<ref name=Irish1964/>\n\nIt was a 'giant' comet, much more active than a normal comet for its distance to the [[Sun]], with an [[Absolute magnitude#Cometary magnitudes|absolute magnitude]] of 1.5\u22123.5, it could have been up to a hundred times brighter than an average new comet. It had an unusually disrupted or 'turbulent' appearance.<ref name=brandt>Brandt & Chapman, ''Introduction to Comets'', Cambridge University Press, 2004, p.156</ref> It was also unusual in that the spectrum of its tail showed a strong predominance of the ion CO+, a result previously seen unambiguously only in [[Comet Morehouse]] (C/1908 R1).<ref name=heubner>Huebner, W. ''Physics and chemistry of comets'', Springer-Verlag, 1990, p.246</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs =\n\n<ref name=jpldata>{{cite web\n  |type=last observation: 1965-11-01\n  |title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser: C/1961 R1 (Humason)\n  |url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=1961R1\n  |publisher=[[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n  |accessdate=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Irish1964>{{cite journal\n  |title=Comets : Comet Humason 1961e\n  |journal=[[Irish Astronomical Journal]]\n  |volume=6 |pages=191 |year=1964\n  |bibcode=1964IrAJ....6Q.191.}}</ref>\n\n}} <!-- end of reflist -->\n\n{{Comets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Humason, 1961 R1}}\n[[Category:Non-periodic comets]]\n[[Category:1961 in science]]\n\n\n{{comet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "C messier", "label": "safe", "comment": "I think this one is better", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comet_Humason"}
{"title_page": "Vietnam mouse-deer", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Small hoofed mammal 'lost' until November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name          = Vietnam mouse-deer\n| image         =\n| status        = DD\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref    =<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Timmins, R.J.|author2=Duckworth, J.W.|author3=Meijaard, E.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2008|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/136360/0|title=''Tragulus versicolor''|access-date=29 March 2009|ref=harv}} Database entry includes a brief justification of why this species is of data deficient.</ref>\n| genus         = Tragulus\n| species       = versicolor\n| authority     = [[Oldfield Thomas|Thomas]], 1910\n| synonyms      = \n| range_map = Tragulus versicolor.png\n| range_map_caption = Range of the Vietnam mouse deer (2008)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Vietnam mouse-deer''' (''Tragulus versicolor''), also known as the '''silver-backed chevrotain''', is a species of [[even-toed ungulate]] in the family [[Tragulidae]] known only from [[Vietnam]]. It was first [[Scientific description|described]] by British zoologist [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1910. Little is known about the distribution and ecology of this mouse-deer; it has been sighted only thrice in the wild and is listed as [[Data Deficient]] on the [[IUCN Red List]]. After the first sighting in 1910 in Nha Trang ([[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]]), specimens were reported next in 1990 near Dak Rong and Buon Luoi in the [[Gia Lai Province]]. With increasing hunting pressure, habitat loss due to deforestation and no more reports of the species in the wild, the mouse-deer was feared to have gone extinct. In 2019, a study procured camera trap evidence confirming the existence of the Vietnam mouse-deer in dry low-lying forests of Nha Trang. This mouse-deer is characterised by a rough coat with a strange double-tone coloration unseen in other [[chevrotain]]s; the front part of the body is reddish brown and contrasts strongly with the greyish posterior. It has big reddish brown ears, white and dark reddish brown marks on the throat.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIn 1910, British zoologist [[Oldfield Thomas]] [[Scientific description|described]] four chevrotains from Nha Trang in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]] (Vietnam), giving them the name ''Tragulus versicolor''.<ref name=thomas>{{cite journal |last=Thomas |first=Oldfield |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1910 |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=5 |page=535 |issue=25\u201330 |title=''Tragulus versicolor'' |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54587#page/571/mode/1up}}</ref><ref name=msw3>{{MSW3|page=650|id=14200183}}</ref> In the past this mouse-deer was generally treated as a [[subspecies]] of the [[greater mouse-deer]] (''T.&nbsp;napu''), though it more closely resembles the [[lesser mouse-deer]] (''T.&nbsp;kanchil''). In a 2004 taxonomic revision, the Vietnam mouse-deer was identified as an independent species in ''Tragulus''.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Erik |last1=Meijaard |first2=C.P. |last2=Groves |year=2004 |url=http://zmmu.msu.ru/rjt/articles/ther3_1%2009_13%20Kuznez_Borisenko.pdf |title=A taxonomic revision of the ''Tragulus'' mouse-deer (Artiodactyla) |journal=Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=140 |issue=1 |pages=63\u2013102 |doi=10.1111/j.1096-3642.2004.00091.x}}</ref>\n\n==Status and sightings==\nInformation on the distribution and ecology of the mouse-deer is scarce; it is [[endemic]] to Vietnam. The specimens obtained by Thomas were from Nha Trang ({{Coord|12|15|N|109|10|E}}) in Annam on the southern coast of Vietnam; this need not be the original location for the species, as the specimens could have been traded.<ref name=iucn/> The mouse-deer was not seen in the wild for another 80 years until a Vietnamese-Russian expedition procured an adult male specimen from local hunters near Dak Rong and Buon Luoi in the [[Gia Lai Province]]. This specimen, initially assumed to be a [[Java mouse-deer]] (''T. javanicus''), was deposited in the [[Zoological Museum of Moscow University]]. A reexamination in 2004 identified the specimen as a Vietnam mouse-deer, noting its strange coloration compared to other chevrotains.<ref name=new2004>{{cite journal |last1=Kuznetsov |first1=G. V. |last2=Borissenko |first2=A. V. |title=A new record of ''Tragulus versicolor'' (Artiodactyla, Tragulidae) from Vietnam, and its sympatric occurrence with ''T. kanchil'' |journal=Russian Journal of Theriology |date=2004 |issue=3 |pages=9-13 |doi=10.15298/rusjtheriol.3.1.03}}</ref> Follow-up surveys indicated that heavy deforestation and hunting pressure in the area had emerged as major threats to chevrotains in the area, but no significant measures were taken to assess the status of the Vietnam mouse-deer. With severe risks to its survival and no new specimens found, scientists feared the Vietnam mouse-deer might have gone extinct.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meijaard |first1=E. |last2=Groves |first2=C.P. |title=Recent study identifies the possible existence of a forgotten species |journal=Oryx |date=2004 |volume=38 |pages=132-133}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meijaard |first1=E. |last2=Borissenko |first2=A.V. |last3=Kuznetsov |first3=G.V. |title=Rediscovery of ''Tragulus versicolor'', the silver-backed chevrotain |journal=Oryx |date=2004 |volume=38 |pages=254-255}}</ref><ref name=\"ng\">{{cite news |last1=Leahy |first1=S. |title=Fanged mouse-deer identified after vanishing for a generation |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2019/11/silver-backed-chevrotain-mouse-deer-reappears-vietnam/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=National Geographic |date=11 November 2019}}</ref> The [[IUCN]], in lack of survey data or ecological cues from which the status and population trend could be reliably assessed, listed the species as \"Data Deficient\" in 2008.<ref name=iucn/> The Vietnam mouse-deer was listed among the 25&nbsp;\"most wanted lost\" species that are the focus of Global Wildlife Conservation's Search for Lost Species initiative.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lostspecies.org |title=The Search for Lost Species |date= |website=Global Wildlife Conservation |access-date=10 July 2017}}</ref> \n\nAfter nearly 30 years, a 2019 study published by researchers in association with the Global Wildlife Conservation confirmed the presence of Vietnam mouse-deer in the Nha Trang area. The researchers had begun with interviews of local people, some of whom suggested the presence of two types of chevrotain in the area; all interviewees agreed that chevrotain populations had declined over the years in the region due to hunting. [[Camera trap]]s were set up in areas from where grey chevrotain had been reported; the researchers were successful in capturing images of silver-backed chevrotain, easily identifiable by their characteristic double-tone coloration and throat markings. The researchers aim to further study the size and stability of the populations.<ref name=nguyen>{{cite journal |last1=Nguyen |first1=A. |last2=Tran |first2=V.B. |last3=Hoang |first3=D.M. |last4=Nguyen |first4=T.A.M. |last5=Nguyen |first5=D.T. |last6=Tran |first6=V.T. |last7=Long |first7=B. |last8=Meijaard |first8=E. |last9=Holland |first9=J. |last10=Wilting |first10=A. |last11=Tilker |first11=A. |title=Camera-trap evidence that the silver-backed chevrotain Tragulus versicolor remains in the wild in Vietnam |journal=Nature Ecology & Evolution |date=2019 |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=1650\u20131654 |doi=10.1038/s41559-019-1027-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Iati |first1=M. |title=A tiny \u2018deer\u2019 was feared extinct. Scientists just photographed it for the first time in a generation. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2019/11/12/tiny-deer-was-feared-extinct-scientists-just-photographed-it-first-time-generation/ |date=12 November 2019 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=E. |title=This elusive creature wasn't seen for nearly 30 years. Then it appeared on camera. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/11/science/vietnam-silver-backed-chevrotain.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nCamera trap evidence obtained by researchers in the 2019 study suggests that Vietnam mouse-deer are diurnal (active mainly during the day), and stay solitary or form pairs.<ref name=nguyen/> The locality where the 1990 specimen was obtained was a low-lying area of [[semi-deciduous]] tropical forest; several lesser mouse-deer specimens were found in the same area, suggesting [[sympatry]].<ref name=new2004/> The 2019 study observed the Vietnam mouse-deer in dry lowland forest near the southern coast of Vietnam.<ref name=nguyen/>\n\n==Physical description==\nIn his 1910 account, Thomas described this mouse-deer as having a rough coat, big reddish brown ears, white and dark reddish brown marks on the throat. He noted the sharp contrast between the reddish brown colour of the front part of the body up to the shoulders, and the grey posterior separated by a line of buff from the white underparts\u2014such stark variation is not observed in other chevrotains. The tail, grey in the upper part and white below, becomes more reddish brown toward the tip, which is white. Per his measurements, the head-and-body length is around {{convert|48|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the tail is {{convert|5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=thomas/> Examiners of the specimen procured in 1990 noted its [[shabrack]]-like coat with dense fur on the back and white hair tips. A prominent silver line runs down its back, hence the name \"silver-backed\". The neck and shoulders were more brown with less dense fur; unlike the lesser mouse-deer the fur on the neck is coarser and less prickly. This mouse-deer lacks the dark markings along the flanks and the middle portion of the underparts visible in the lesser mouse-deer.<ref name=new2004/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Saplakoglu |first1=Y. |title=A Tiny Species That Looks Part-Deer, Part-Mouse Was Missing for Nearly 30 Years. Scientists Just Found It. |url=https://www.livescience.com/lost-silver-backed-chevrotain-captured-photos.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Live Science |date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Mammals}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Artiodactyla|R.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q966649}}\n\n[[Category:Tragulus]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1910]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Small hoofed mammal 'lost' until November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name          = Vietnam mouse-deer\n| image         =\n| status        = DD\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref    =<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Timmins, R.J.|author2=Duckworth, J.W.|author3=Meijaard, E.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2008|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/136360/0|title=''Tragulus versicolor''|access-date=29 March 2009|ref=harv}} Database entry includes a brief justification of why this species is of data deficient.</ref>\n| genus         = Tragulus\n| species       = versicolor\n| authority     = [[Oldfield Thomas|Thomas]], 1910\n| synonyms      = \n| range_map = Tragulus versicolor.png\n| range_map_caption = Range of the Vietnam mouse deer (2008)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Vietnam mouse-deer''' (''Tragulus versicolor''), also known as the '''silver-backed chevrotain''', is a species of [[even-toed ungulate]] in the family [[Tragulidae]] known only from [[Vietnam]]. It was first [[Scientific description|described]] by British zoologist [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1910. Little is known about the distribution and ecology of this mouse-deer; it has been sighted only thrice in the wild and is listed as [[Data Deficient]] on the [[IUCN Red List]]. After the first sighting in 1910 in Nha Trang ([[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]]), specimens were reported next in 1990 near Dak Rong and Buon Luoi in the [[Gia Lai Province]]. With increasing hunting pressure, habitat loss due to deforestation and no more reports of the species in the wild, the mouse-deer was feared to have gone extinct. In 2019, a study procured camera trap evidence confirming the existence of the Vietnam mouse-deer in dry low-lying forests of Nha Trang. This mouse-deer is characterised by a rough coat with a strange double-tone coloration unseen in other [[chevrotain]]s; the front part of the body is reddish brown and contrasts strongly with the greyish posterior. It has big reddish brown ears, white and dark reddish brown marks on the throat.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIn 1910, British zoologist [[Oldfield Thomas]] [[Scientific description|described]] four chevrotains from Nha Trang in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]] (Vietnam), giving them the name ''Tragulus versicolor''.<ref name=thomas>{{cite journal |last=Thomas |first=Oldfield |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1910 |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=5 |page=535 |issue=25\u201330 |title=''Tragulus versicolor'' |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54587#page/571/mode/1up}}</ref><ref name=msw3>{{MSW3|page=650|id=14200183}}</ref> In the past this mouse-deer was generally treated as a [[subspecies]] of the [[greater mouse-deer]] (''T.&nbsp;napu''), though it more closely resembles the [[lesser mouse-deer]] (''T.&nbsp;kanchil''). In a 2004 taxonomic revision, the Vietnam mouse-deer was identified as an independent species in ''Tragulus''.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Erik |last1=Meijaard |first2=C.P. |last2=Groves |year=2004 |url=http://zmmu.msu.ru/rjt/articles/ther3_1%2009_13%20Kuznez_Borisenko.pdf |title=A taxonomic revision of the ''Tragulus'' mouse-deer (Artiodactyla) |journal=Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=140 |issue=1 |pages=63\u2013102 |doi=10.1111/j.1096-3642.2004.00091.x}}</ref>\n\n==Status and sightings==\nInformation on the distribution and ecology of the mouse-deer is scarce; it is [[endemic]] to Vietnam. The specimens obtained by Thomas were from Nha Trang ({{Coord|12|15|N|109|10|E}}) in Annam on the southern coast of Vietnam; this need not be the original location for the species, as the specimens could have been traded.<ref name=iucn/> The mouse-deer was not seen in the wild for another 80 years until a Vietnamese-Russian expedition procured an adult male specimen from local hunters near Dak Rong and Buon Luoi in the [[Gia Lai Province]]. This specimen, initially assumed to be a [[Java mouse-deer]] (''T. javanicus''), was deposited in the [[Zoological Museum of Moscow University]]. A reexamination in 2004 identified the specimen as a Vietnam mouse-deer, noting its strange coloration compared to other chevrotains.<ref name=new2004>{{cite journal |last1=Kuznetsov |first1=G. V. |last2=Borissenko |first2=A. V. |title=A new record of ''Tragulus versicolor'' (Artiodactyla, Tragulidae) from Vietnam, and its sympatric occurrence with ''T. kanchil'' |journal=Russian Journal of Theriology |date=2004 |issue=3 |pages=9-13 |doi=10.15298/rusjtheriol.3.1.03}}</ref> Follow-up surveys indicated that heavy deforestation and hunting pressure in the area had emerged as major threats to chevrotains in the area, but no significant measures were taken to assess the status of the Vietnam mouse-deer. With severe risks to its survival and no new specimens found, scientists feared the Vietnam mouse-deer might have gone extinct.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meijaard |first1=E. |last2=Groves |first2=C.P. |title=Recent study identifies the possible existence of a forgotten species |journal=Oryx |date=2004 |volume=38 |pages=132-133}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meijaard |first1=E. |last2=Borissenko |first2=A.V. |last3=Kuznetsov |first3=G.V. |title=Rediscovery of ''Tragulus versicolor'', the silver-backed chevrotain |journal=Oryx |date=2004 |volume=38 |pages=254-255}}</ref><ref name=\"ng\">{{cite news |last1=Leahy |first1=S. |title=Fanged mouse-deer identified after vanishing for a generation |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2019/11/silver-backed-chevrotain-mouse-deer-reappears-vietnam/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=National Geographic |date=11 November 2019}}</ref> The [[IUCN]], in lack of survey data or ecological cues from which the status and population trend could be reliably assessed, listed the species as \"Data Deficient\" in 2008.<ref name=iucn/> The Vietnam mouse-deer was listed among the 25&nbsp;\"most wanted lost\" species that are the focus of Global Wildlife Conservation's Search for Lost Species initiative.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lostspecies.org |title=The Search for Lost Species |date= |website=Global Wildlife Conservation |access-date=10 July 2017}}</ref> \n\nAfter nearly 30 years, a 2019 study published by researchers in association with the Global Wildlife Conservation confirmed the presence of Vietnam mouse-deer in the Nha Trang area. The researchers had begun with interviews of local people, some of whom suggested the presence of two types of chevrotain in the area; all interviewees agreed that chevrotain populations had declined over the years in the region due to hunting. [[Camera trap]]s were set up in areas from where grey chevrotain had been reported; the researchers were successful in capturing images of silver-backed chevrotain, easily identifiable by their characteristic double-tone coloration and throat markings. The researchers aim to further study the size and stability of the populations.<ref name=nguyen>{{cite journal |last1=Nguyen |first1=A. |last2=Tran |first2=V.B. |last3=Hoang |first3=D.M. |last4=Nguyen |first4=T.A.M. |last5=Nguyen |first5=D.T. |last6=Tran |first6=V.T. |last7=Long |first7=B. |last8=Meijaard |first8=E. |last9=Holland |first9=J. |last10=Wilting |first10=A. |last11=Tilker |first11=A. |title=Camera-trap evidence that the silver-backed chevrotain Tragulus versicolor remains in the wild in Vietnam |journal=Nature Ecology & Evolution |date=2019 |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=1650\u20131654 |doi=10.1038/s41559-019-1027-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Iati |first1=M. |title=A tiny \u2018deer\u2019 was feared extinct. Scientists just photographed it for the first time in a generation. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2019/11/12/tiny-deer-was-feared-extinct-scientists-just-photographed-it-first-time-generation/ |date=12 November 2019 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=E. |title=This elusive creature wasn't seen for nearly 30 years. Then it appeared on camera. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/11/science/vietnam-silver-backed-chevrotain.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nCamera trap evidence obtained by researchers in the 2019 study suggests that Vietnam mouse-deer are diurnal (active mainly during the day), and stay solitary or form pairs.<ref name=nguyen/> The locality where the 1990 specimen was obtained was a low-lying area of [[semi-deciduous]] tropical forest; several lesser mouse-deer specimens were found in the same area, suggesting [[sympatry]].<ref name=new2004/> The 2019 study observed the Vietnam mouse-deer in dry lowland forest near the southern coast of Vietnam.<ref name=nguyen/>\n\n==Physical description==\nIn his 1910 account, Thomas described this mouse-deer as having a rough coat, big reddish brown ears, white and dark reddish brown marks on the throat. He noted the sharp contrast between the reddish brown color of the front part of the body up to the shoulders, and the grey posterior separated by a line of buff from the white underparts\u2014such stark variation is not observed in other chevrotains. The tail, grey in the upper part and white below, becomes more reddish brown toward the tip, which is white. Per his measurements, the head-and-body length is around {{convert|48|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the tail is {{convert|5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=thomas/> Examiners of the specimen procured in 1990 noted its [[shabrack]]-like coat with dense fur on the back and white hair tips. A prominent silver line runs down its back, hence the name \"silver-backed\". The neck and shoulders were more brown with less dense fur; unlike the lesser mouse-deer the fur on the neck is coarser and less prickly. This mouse-deer lacks the dark markings along the flanks and the middle portion of the underparts visible in the lesser mouse-deer.<ref name=new2004/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Saplakoglu |first1=Y. |title=A Tiny Species That Looks Part-Deer, Part-Mouse Was Missing for Nearly 30 Years. Scientists Just Found It. |url=https://www.livescience.com/lost-silver-backed-chevrotain-captured-photos.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Live Science |date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Mammals}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Artiodactyla|R.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q966649}}\n\n[[Category:Tragulus]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1910]]\n", "name_user": "Sainsf", "label": "safe", "comment": "EngvarB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vietnam_mouse-deer"}
{"title_page": "Nevers faience", "text_new": "[[File:Ewer MET DT214721 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Mustard and blue solid-body wares, 1650-80, with Turkish-inspired birds and flowers.<ref>McNab, 18-20; [https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194289 Ewer page at Metropolitan Museum]</ref>]] \n[[File:Maiolica di nevers, trionfo di cesare in roma, 1600-1630 circa.JPG|thumb|Nevers dish in the ''istoriato'' style, with the ''Triumph of Julius Caesar'', very loosely [[Triumphs of Caesar (Mantegna)|after Mantegna]], 1600\u20131630]]\nThe city of [[Nevers]], [[Ni\u00e8vre]], now in the [[Bourgogne-Franche-Comt\u00e9]] [[Regions of France|region]] in central France, was a centre for manufacturing [[faience]], or [[Tin-glazed pottery|tin-glazed earthenware]] pottery, between around 1580 and the early 19th century, production then gradually dying down to a single factory, before a revival in the 1880s.  In 2017, there were still two potteries making it in the city, after a third had closed.<ref>[https://www.lejdc.fr/nevers/economie/commerce-artisanat/2017/04/01/desormais-nevers-ne-compte-plus-que-deux-faienceries_12346253.html \"D\u00e9sormais, Nevers ne compte plus que deux fa\u00efenceries\"], Lara Payet, 1 April 2017, ''Le Journal du Centre'' (in French); [http://faiencedenevers.fr/les-faienciers-actuels/ \"les faienciers actuels\"], faiencedenevers.fr - still the case in 2020</ref>  However the quality and prestige of the wares has gradually declined, from a fashionable luxury product for the court, to a traditional regional speciality using styles derived from the past.\n[[File:Faience Nevers 6868.jpg|thumb|17th-century plate with genteel party in a European-style landscape. The border has birds, flowers and a rabbit, all at the same size.<ref>Estienne, 52-54</ref>]]\n\nNevers faience was one of the centres where the ''istoriato'' style of [[Italian maiolica]] was transplanted in the 16th century, and flourished for rather longer than in Italy itself.  In the 17th century Nevers was then a pioneer in imitating Asian ceramic styles in Europe, within some decades followed by all producers of fine wares.  The second half of the 17th century was Nevers' finest period, with several styles being made at the same time, including a grandiose Italianate Court style.<ref>McNab, 20-21; [http://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O1156287/jardiniere-unknown/ V&A, Nevers] [[Jardiniere]]</ref>   \n\nBy the time of the [[French Revolution]] Nevers wares had ceased to be fashionable and expensive,<ref>Garnier, 274\u2013275</ref> but the relatively crudely painted ''faiences patriotiques'' wares commenting on political events have great interest and charm.<ref>Though not to Garnier, 275, who is very rude about them</ref>  A late 19th-century revival concentrated on high-quality revivalist wares recreating past glories.    \n \n==History==\nThe tradition owes its origin to [[Louis Gonzaga, Duke of Nevers]] (1539\u20131595), a half-French and half Italian politician and courtier who married the heiress of the [[Duke of Nevers|Duchy of Nevers]], which then still gave him great powers in the [[County and Duchy of Nevers]].  He had been born in [[Mantua]], near several centres for Italian [[maiolica]], which had already spread to [[Rouen]] and [[Lyons]], and encouraged some Italian potters to move to the city.  Giulio Gambin was already in Lyons and the Conrade brothers (Corrado in Italy) came from [[Albisola]], who would found the dynasty that dominated Nevers production for a century.<ref>Coutts, 28; Moon; McNab, 12; Britannica</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=[[Birmingham Museum of Art]]|title=Birmingham Museum of Art : guide to the collection|year=2010|publisher=Birmingham Museum of Art|location=[Birmingham, Ala]|isbn=978-1-904832-77-5|pages=173}}</ref>   \n\nNevers already had a local unglazed pottery industry, and was a very suitable location for making faience. The city was near deposits of excellent pottery clay, an exceptionally good type of sand for making [[ceramic glaze]], forests for wood for the kilns, and was on the major [[Loire]] river.  The earliest dated piece by the Italians is from 1587.<ref>Estienne, 46</ref> \n\nIn 1603 the brothers received a monopoly from [[Henry IV of France|Henri IV]] for the making of wares in the style of [[Faenza]], whether painted polychrome or with white grounds, and a generation later Antoine Conrade, son of Dominique, was made ''faiencier ordinaire'' to the young [[Louis XIV]] in 1644.<ref>Coutts, 27\u201328</ref>  This was repeated in the next generation for another Dominique Conrade, given his ''brevet'' in 1672.<ref>Garnier, 270</ref>\n[[File:Nevers7.JPG|thumb|''faience patriotique'' of the [[French Revolution]]. An aristocrat and bishop: \"Unhappiness re-unites us\", 1791.]]\n\nThe Conrade monopoly was not effective for long, with a second factory starting in 1632, and by 1652 there were four different potteries in Nevers, including one founded by Pierre Custode, whose family became the other main Nevers dynasty of potters.<ref>Garnier, 270; Chaffers, 148</ref>  \n\nThe French faience industry received a huge boost when, late in his reign in 1709, [[Louis XIV]] pressured the wealthy to donate their silver plate, previously what they normally used to dine, to his treasury to help pay for his wars.  They was an \"overnight frenzy\" as the elite rushed to get faience replacements of the best quality.  Nevers garden vases in blue and white were prominently used in the gardens of the [[Chateau de Versailles]].<ref>Moon; McNab, 30</ref>\n\nThe success of the wares led to several other factories opening in the early 18th century, and in 1743 the government limited the number to eleven, to prevent flooding the market.  In 1760 a twelfth was permitted.  By this period Nevers wares had been largely replaced at the top end of the market by other makers, but were producing large quantities of less expensive wares for a broader market.  They did not attempt to compete with the elegant [[Rococo]] style of the French porcelain factories, which was attempted rather successfully by some makers of faience, for example the [[Veuve Perrin]] factory in [[Marseilles]].  All twelve Nevers factories (still including the Conrade and Custode ateliers) were still in operation in 1790, but a commercial treaty with Great Britain in 1786 led to the French market being flooded by cheaper and better English [[creamware]]s, leading to crisis for all French manufacturers of faience, and by 1797 six had ceased operations, with the other six having reduced their workforce by half.<ref>Chaffers, 148\u2013149, who lists all 12; Badillet, 4; Osborne, 133; Britannica</ref>  \n\nBy this time European [[porcelain]] was becoming cheaper and more reliable, and making life difficult for producers of high-quality earthenware across Europe.<ref>Osborne, 133; Moon</ref>  The Nevers response was to produce topical ''faiences patriotiques'' with which the English were unlikely to compete (although they had done excellent business supplying the new American republic with patriotic wares).<ref>Britannica</ref>\n[[File:Manufacture du bout du monde, Sainte C\u00e9cile.jpg|thumb|Montagon plate with [[Saint Cecilia]], 1888]]\n\nIn 1838 700 workers were reported to be employed,<ref>de Saint-Fargeau, Girault, ''Guide pittoresque du voyageur en France: contenant la statistique ...'', Volume 2, 11, 1838, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6yQxAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA7 google books]</ref> but by 1846 only six factories remained, and by 1850 five.<ref>Badillet, 4</ref>  A [[porcelain]] manufactury in Nevers was also mentioned in 1844 by [[Alexandre Brongniart]], but little is known about it.<ref name=\"Litchfield\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=QsbMKOjvWiAC&pg=PA219 ''Pottery and Porcelain: A Guide to Collectors'' by Frederick Litchfield p.219]</ref>\n\nThe ''manufacture du Bout du monde'' (\"End of the World\" factory) was founded in 1648, and followed the general pattern of the Nevers factories.  By 1875 its fortunes had reached a low ebb, and it was bought by Antoine Montagnon, who had ambitious plans to relaunch it to supply the market for revivalist wares imitating 17th-century pieces, often large and complex pieces.<ref>Badillet, 4</ref><ref name=\"centre\">Dominique Romeyer, [http://www.lejdc.fr/nevers/loisirs/art-litterature/2015/05/19/vingt-cinq-dirigeants-se-sont-succede-a-la-tete-de-la-faiencerie-montagnon-en-367-ans_11445739.html \"Vingt-cinq dirigeants se sont succ\u00e9d\u00e9 \u00e0 la t\u00eate de la fa\u00efencerie Montagnon en 367 ans\"], ''Le Journal du Centre'' 19 May 2015</ref>  By 1881 it was the only factory left in Nevers.  The Montagnon factoriy (fa\u00efencerie) was successful for over a century, with 50 employees around 1900, and its wares exhibited at international exhibitions,<ref>Badillet, 4</ref> but the factory, by then the oldest in France, finally closed in 2015.<ref>Mont</ref>  In 2020, two factories remained in production, both mainly making traditional styles.<ref>[http://faiencedenevers.fr/les-faienciers-actuels/ \"les faienciers actuels\"], faiencedenevers.fr</ref>\n\n==Styles==\nThe list of stylistic periods devised by the French authority du Broc de Segange in his 1863 book on Nevers faience is still often repeated,<ref>Chaffers, 150</ref> though perhaps needing some adjustment. It shows several styles in use at particular dates, which is certainly the case:\n* 1600\u20131660: Italian style\n* 1650\u20131750: Chinese and Japanese style\n* 1630\u20131700: Persian style\n* 1640\u20131789: Franco-Nivernais style\n* 1700\u20131789: [[Rouen manufactory]] style\n* 1730\u20131789: ''Tradition de Moustiers'', imitating the faience of [[Moustiers-Sainte-Marie]] in the [[Alpes-de-Haute-Provence]]\n* 1770\u20131789: ''Gout de Saxe'', ie [[Meissen porcelain|Meissen]] style\n* 1789 on : Decadence.<ref>Chaffers, 150</ref>\n\nFran\u00e7oise Estienne, in the 1980s, divided Nevers production in the 17th century (extended slightly at both ends) into eleven \"families\" based on the decoration of a study group of 1874 pieces, mainly in French museums, looking at both subjects and styles.<ref>Estienne, 45 and throughout.  The locations of the group are described in note 6 on p. 47 - examples outside France appear to have been ignored completely.</ref>  \n\n===Italian style===\nThe Italian immigrants continued at Nevers the ''istoriato'' (narrative) style that was already in decline in Italy, until at least 1660. As was usual in Italy by 1580, designs were mostly adapted from [[old master print|prints]],<ref>Coutts, 27\u201328; McNab, 12</ref> and the outline set out on the pot by a ''ponci'' or [[stencil]], pushing charcoal dust through pin-pricks in a paper drawing or tracing from a print.<ref>McNab, 12</ref>  \n\nThe early pieces did not generally use distinctive marks or inscriptions, though sometimes painting \"Nevers\" on the base of important pieces, perhaps with a date \u2013 the earliest of these is 1589, on a dish in the [[Louvre]].<ref>Coutts, 28</ref>  As with painted [[Limoges enamel]] of the previous century, with which Nevers decoration has some similaritites, a high proportion of religious subjects illustrate [[Old Testament]] subjects.  As with Italian pieces, the subjects, especially those from the Old Testament or [[classical mythology]], tended to be named on the base, sometimes even with the bible chapter noted.<ref>Wilson, 202 for an Italian example; [https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194297 Metropolitan Museum page] for the \"Joseph and his brothers\" plate illustrated here.</ref>  \n\nThere is a good deal of uncertainty in the attribution of pieces between the Nevers workshops, and between Nevers pieces and those of other centres.<ref>Chaffers, 149, 151\u2013153 has an illustrated list of marks</ref>  The large dish with ''The Gathering of Manna'' illustrated below, a well-known piece, had been assumed to be Italian, and 16th century, until recently.  Though there are still uncertainties, it is now though to be moulded from an Italian dish (now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London), then painted as a matching pair of that.<ref>Wilson, 334\u2013337</ref>   A curious aspect of Nevers faience is that it never succeeded in producing a good red colour, unlike Rouen and other centres, the absence of which often enables Nevers pieces to be distinguished.<ref>Garnier, 275</ref>  \n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Sacrifice of Noah MET DP214750 (cropped).jpg|''Sacrifice of Noah'', 1580\u20131610, Nevers or Lyons\nFile:Dish with Joseph and His Brothers MET DP318841 (cropped).jpg|Dish with Joseph and His Brothers, 1630-45, after print by [[Bernard Salomon]]; Conrade workshop? \"Inscribed on back in blue: LES FRERE' DE JIOSEPH / VENUS A LUY EN EGIPTE / AU GENESE XLII (trans.: The brothers of Joseph came to him in Egypt in Genesis 42)\".<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194297 Metropolitan Museum page]</ref> \nFile:Basin or dish with The Gathering of Manna MET DP329029 (cropped).jpg|Basin or dish with ''The Gathering of Manna'', 1620-45, probably made as a pair to an Italian dish of the 1560s.<ref>Wilson, 334-337</ref> \nFile:Atelier d\u2019Antoine Conrade ou de Nicolas Estienne - Plat La Pluie de cailles dans le d\u00e9sert.jpg|The [[manna]] in the desert, attributed to Antoine Conrade or Nicolas Estienne \nFile:Plate with two lovers MET DP326528 (cropped).jpg|Plate with two lovers, dated 1644, \"perhaps\" Antoine Conrade.<ref>Wilson, 338; [https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194294 Metropolitan Museum page]</ref>\n\n</gallery>\n\n===Asian styles===\n[[File:Plat d'apparat \u00e0 d\u00e9cor de chinoiseries - Large ceremonial basin with chinoiseries - Nevers - 1660-1680 - Louvre - Inv OA 12546.JPG|thumb|Large dish (49.5 cm) with Chinese-style musicians in a landscape, unusually using two colours, flanked by two \"Persian style\" bowls with European-style painting]]\n\nWithin Estienne's study group of 1874 pieces, the \"Persian\" family were the most numerous, with 547, then the Chinese with 374, so 921 pieces in Asian styles in total, almost half.<ref>Estienne, 57-58</ref>  Nevers made the first Chinese-style [[blue and white porcelain|blue and white wares]] in France, with production running between about 1650 and 1700. Chinese styles would then be taken up by factories in [[Normandy]], especially following the foundation of the [[French East India Company]] in 1664.<ref name=\"Ward\"/><ref>Britannica</ref> \n\nA technique unique to Nevers in French faience, used on some pieces from about 1650 for a few decades, was to stain all the clay from which the body was made either in ''bleu de Nevers'' or (much more rarely) a mustard yellow ([[Wedgwood]] did the same for their [[jasperware]] a century later).  This was then painted in white or other colours, using various styles.  This style is traditionally known as \"Persian\", as decoration in white on a rich blue ground is often seen in [[Persian pottery]] of the period.  However the bird and flower painted decoration seen in most examples of the \"Persian\" style in fact derives more from Turkish [[Iznik pottery]], which  was reaching Europe through Italy.<ref>McNab, 18-20, 30 no 12; Estienne, 57</ref>   \n\nNevers adopted Chinese vase shapes early in the 17th century, earlier than Dutch [[Delftware]].<ref>McNab, 18</ref>  Some Nevers pieces clearly copy [[Chinese export porcelain]] in terms of their painted decoration, both the cheaper [[Kraak ware]] and better quality blue and white wares, whereas others have decoration based on Turkish, Persian or other Islamic Middle Eastern styles. These often have the blue background, which is unusual on Chinese export porcelain, where blue figures on a white ground are the norm in blue and white wares.<ref>McNab, 18\u201320; Estienne, 57-59</ref><ref name=\"Ward\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=mkJfbdTS--UC&pg=PA38 ''The Grove encyclopedia of materials and techniques in art'' Gerald W. R. Ward p.38]</ref>  \n\nMuch of the painting on pieces with a white ground copies that of Chinese blue and white [[Transitional porcelain]] (roughly 1625-90), a good deal of which was exported.  [[Chinese literati]] figures contemplating nature in a lush garden or landscape is a common subject in both countries, though the French treatments have some differences.<ref>Estienne, 58-59</ref> \n\nUnlike other French potteries, especially the porcelain factories of the early 18th century, influence from [[Japanese export porcelain]] styles such as [[Kakiemon]] is not found in Nevers wares.<ref>Estienne's long account makes no mention of Japan.</ref>  Estienne sees the ''decoration \u00e0 la bougie'', with white imitating splashes of candle-wax on a blue ground (see below), as of Chinese inspiration.  They compare with some much earlier [[Song dynasty]] wares, in particular the \"oil-spot\" glazes of [[Jian ware]] (around the 12th or 13th centuries), though Estienne is unable to explain how awareness of these could have reached France in the 17th century.<ref>Estienne, 60</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Assiette Nevers Conrade S\u00e8vres.jpg|Conrade plate, 1630s, imitating Chinese [[Kraak ware]]. \nFile:GardenVaseNevers-BMA (cropped).jpg|Garden vase, 1660-80; Chinese-style decor in white on a blue ground; the shape is entirely European. \nFile:Ariana museum - islamic pottery imitation - Plat - Nevers (France) - 1670 - 1680 - Inventaire AR 12748-2.jpg|\"Persian\"-style with ''bleu de Nevers'' ground, 1670s\nFile:Faience with Chinese scenes Nevers Manufactory 1680 1700.jpg|Chinese style, 1680-1700, blue on a white ground.\nFile:Nevers faience vases circa 1700.jpg|Chinese-style vases, c. 1700  \n\n</gallery>\n\n===Louis XIV Court style===\nAfter about 1650, Nevers adapted the new French Court style to faience, borrowing from metalwork and other decorative arts, and using prints after the new generation of court painters such as [[Simon Vouet]] and [[Charles Lebrun]] for the images.  The pieces were often extremely large and ornate, and apart from garden vases and wine-coolers, no doubt decorative rather than practical.<ref>McNab, 20-21; Moon; [http://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O1156287/jardiniere-unknown/ V&A, Nevers] [[Jardiniere]]</ref> \n\n<gallery widths=\"220px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Grand plat rond - L'enl\u00e8vement d'Europe - The Abduction of Europa - Nevers - 1675-1690 - Louvre - OA 1896.jpg|Central dish is 58 cm across, the main scene the ''Rape of Europa'', after an illustration of [[Ovid]] by [[Fran\u00e7ois Chauveau]], published in 1674 \nFile:Bassin \u00e0 rafraichir - L'Ivresse de Bacchus - Cooling Basin - The Drunkenness of Bacchus - Nevers - vers 1680 - Louvre - OA 11315 (cropped).jpg|Wine-cooler with ''The Drunkenness of Bacchus'', c. 1680\nFile:Wine jug (one of a pair) MET DT8115 (cropped).jpg|Pair of wine jugs, c. 1685, 56 cm high. [[Fran\u00e7ois Chauveau]]'s ''Rape of Europa'' is again used (left).\nFile:Vase avec sc\u00e8nes de bacchanales (Louvre, INV 5013).jpg|Large ewer with dancing bacchantes and satyrs, 1685\nFile:Lessines NDame a la Rose PM 093090 (cropped).jpg|Three Montagnon pieces in the style, after 1900\n\n</gallery>\n\n===European styles===\n[[File:Plat Nevers d\u00e9cor p\u00eacheur.JPG|thumb|Fisherman on the Loire near Nevers]]\nWares were also produced in a wide variety of styles drawing on European sources, and these came to dominate production in the 18th century, as the quality of Nevers wares declined.  After about 1750 the European porcelain factories largely replaced Asian exports as the dominant wares at the top of the market, but by this time Nevers faience was usually cruder, cheaper, and more \"popular\" in taste.  Some [[armorial porcelain|armorial wares]] were produced.<ref>McNab, 16</ref>  Nevers is on the [[Loire]] and many pieces have painted images of the local style of river boats, and the long arched bridge over the river.<ref>Badillet, Chapter 4 onwards</ref>\n\nIn the 17th century a favourite source for scenes with figures was the immensely long pastoral novel or romance ''[[L'Astr\u00e9e]]'' by [[Honor\u00e9 d'Urf\u00e9]], published between 1607 and 1627, and possibly the single most influential work of 17th century French literature.  The main characters, Astr\u00e9e and Celadon, spend time disguised as a shepherd and shepherdess, and this is the most popular depiction; very wide hats tend to indicate the pastoral life.  These scenes do not seem to take their compositions from prints, even approximately, nor relate to any specific moment in the story.  They seem to begin around 1640.<ref>Estienne, 54-55</ref>\n\nOther scenes show hunting and fishing, often drawing on Flemish prints,<ref>Estienne, 50, 55</ref> and a few specific historical moments. There is a dish with the signing of the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]] in 1659, with portraits of [[Cardinal Mazarin]] and [[Luis de Haro]], his Spanish counterpart.<ref>Estienne, 55-56</ref>  Many pieces, and many more borders, mix a range of elements: figures, birds and animals, flowers, and ornamental motifs, typically all at roughly the same size, for example a flower, rabbit, bird and man.<ref>Estienne, 52-54</ref>  \n\n<gallery widths=\"170px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Collections du Mus\u00e9e national de c\u00e9ramique de S\u00e8vres 17 (cropped).jpg|Rare Nevers \"Rustic ware\" dish, in the style of [[Bernard Palissy]], 1599, by Agostino Conrade\nFile:Mus\u00e9e national de C\u00e9ramique, saint S\u00e9bastien, Nevers 01 (cropped).jpg|Rare statue of [[Saint Sebastian]], about half life-size, c. 1630\nFile:Faience grand feu de Nevers 06859.jpg|Figure [[sconce (light fixture)|sconce]] (candleholder)\nFile:Vase - mus\u00e9e HCL - Charit\u00e9 (2) (cropped).jpg|Vase, 1650-1700\nFile:Plate MET ES633 (cropped).jpg|Characters from ''[[L'Astr\u00e9e]]'' in the \"Persian\" white on blue, c. 1675\nFile:Plate MET SF17 190 1779 img1 (cropped).jpg|Armorial dish, with characters from ''[[L'Astr\u00e9e]]'', 1650\u201375 \nFile:Nevers Vase with decoration \u00e0 la bougie.jpg|\"Candle\" style (''decoration \u00e0 la bougie''), imitating splashes of candle wax,<ref>McNab, 38 no. 12; Estienne, 60</ref> late 17th century\nFile:Nevers Factory - Large Plate - 1966.221 - Cleveland Museum of Art (cropped).tif|Astrological plate, 44 cm, perhaps with birthchart for \"Moderata Durant\", late 17th century.<ref>Estienne, 56</ref> \nFile:Gourde - mus\u00e9e HCL - c\u00e9ramique civile - 2007.0.3069.M (cropped).jpg|decorative pilgrim flask, 1700-1725\nFile:Bouteille - mus\u00e9e HCL - c\u00e9ramique civile - 2007.0.3074.M (cropped).jpg|Bottle, c. 1809\n</gallery>\n\n===''faiences parlantes''===\nThe ''faiences patriotiques'' of the Revolutionary period typically have one or two figures in the central section, rather crudely painted in a few colours, with a pro-revolutionary slogan or comment below in black cursive script. The earliest examples included pro-monarchist pieces.<ref>Chaffers, 149\u2013150 gives a number of examples; Britannica, F; [[:File:Carnavalet - pichet coeur ardent.jpg|Monarchist jug, c. 1789]]</ref>  The same style had been in use before the Revolution, and continued after it, the wider grouping being called ''faiences parlantes'' (\"talking faience\").  These were more comic or satirical than political.<ref>Britannica, N, F</ref>  Another type of pieces in this popular style, called ''faience patronymique'', showed the patron saint of the recipient, and were common as christening or birthday gifts.  These types were made in other centres, but Nevers was the leading producer.<ref>Britannica, F</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Bastilleteller.jpg|''[[Storming the Bastille]]'', c 1789\nFile:Serment clerg\u00e9 assiette.jpg|A priest swears \"with all my power\" to maintain the Constitution; the clergy were made to so swear (\"je jure de maintenir de tout mon pouvoir la constitution\") in November 1790 \nFile:Droits de l'homme assiette.jpg|\"Rights of Man\", c 1790\nFile:Plat au motif du train de bateaux (cropped).jpg|The Loire, with boats and the Nevers bridge, 1800\nFile:Arbre d'amour assiette.jpg|''Tree of Love'', a complex comic subject, 1803; the men are trying to hide from the women, a popular 18th century subject \n</gallery>\n\n==Collections==\nEstienne's group of 17th-century pieces included 227 in the Nevers museum, 179 at [[S\u00e8vres \u2013 Cit\u00e9 de la c\u00e9ramique|S\u00e8vres]], and 116 in the [[Chateau de Saumur]]. The [[Louvre]] had 49 pieces, but of the highest quality.<ref>Estienne, 47 note 6. At least today, many pieces at Nevers are loans from the Louvre.</ref>  [[J. P. Morgan]] collected Nevers wares, and left many to the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York (accessioned in 1917), including a number illustrated here.<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194289 including the mustard ewer at the start of the article]</ref>  Most other major ceramic collections have examples, for example the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London has over 60.<ref>[http://collections.vam.ac.uk/search/?offset=0&limit=45&narrow=1&extrasearch=&q=Nevers+Tin-glazed+earthenware&commit=Search&quality=0&objectnamesearch=&placesearch=&after=&before=&namesearch=&materialsearch=&mnsearch=&locationsearch= a search on \"Nevers Tin-glazed earthenware\"] returns 80 results, but some are imitations, old attributions, photos etc.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat|Faience of Nevers}}\n\n* [[Orientalism in early modern France]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Badillet, Guy, ''Fa\u00efences de Nevers et Marine de Loire'' (in French), Chapter 3, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ptug6b11XrgC&pg=PP13 google books]\n*\"Britannica N\", [https://www.britannica.com/art/Nevers-faience \"Nevers faience\"], [[Encyclopedia Britannica]] online\n*\"Britannica F\", [https://www.britannica.com/art/faience-parlante#ref273139 \"Faience parlante\"], [[Encyclopedia Britannica]] online\n*[[William Chaffers|Chaffers, William]], ''Marks and Monograms on Pottery and Porcelain'', 1863, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-ikGAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA147 google books]\n*Coutts, Howard, ''The Art of Ceramics: European Ceramic Design, 1500\u20131830'', 2001, Yale University Press, {{ISBN|0300083874}}, 9780300083873, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fRfIfV3Eq_sC&pg=PA28 google books]\n*Estienne, Fran\u00e7oise, \"\u00c0 propos d'une \u00e9tude sur un centre de production de fa\u00efence en France: Nevers\", ''Histoire, \u00e9conomie & soci\u00e9t\u00e9'', 1989 8-1 pp. 45-60, [https://www.persee.fr/doc/hes_0752-5702_1989_num_8_1_1545 online] (in French, abstract in English)\n*Garnier, \u00c9douard, ''Histoire de la c\u00e9ramique, poteries, fa\u00efences et porcelaines chez tous les peuples depuis les temps anciens jusqu'\u00e0 nos jours'', 1882 reprinted 2012, Editorial MAXTOR, {{ISBN|9791020800183}}, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7nELBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA269 google books]\n*McNab, Jessie, ''Seventeenth-Century French Ceramic Art'', 1987, Metropolitan Museum of Art, {{ISBN|0870994905}}, 9780870994906, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tAnKFvwSmhwC&pg=PA12 google books]\n*\"Mont\": [http://faiencedenevers.fr/au-xixieme-et-xxieme-siecle/faiencerie-montagnon/ \"Faiencerie Montagnon\"], faiencedenevers.fr\n*Moon, Iris, \"French Faience\", in Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History, 2016, New York: The [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], [http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/ffai/hd_ffai.htm online]\n*Osborne, Harold (ed), ''The Oxford Companion to the Decorative Arts'', 1975, OUP, {{ISBN|0198661134}}\n*Wilson, Timothy, ''Maiolica: Italian Renaissance Ceramics in the Metropolitan Museum of Art'', 2016, Metropolitan Museum of Art, {{ISBN|1588395618}}, 9781588395610, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2i_ADAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover google books]\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Champfleury]] (pseudonym of Jules Fran\u00e7ois Felix Fleury-Husson), ''Histoire des fa\u00efences patriotiques sous la r\u00e9volution'', 1875 (3rd edn), E. Dentu, Paris, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=v6oNAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover fully online] (in French)\n*Reginster-Le Clanche, Fran\u00e7oise, ''Fa\u00efences de Nevers'', 2003, (in French)\n*Rosen, Jean, ''Faience de Nevers, 1585\u20131900'', 4 volumes, (in French)\n\n[[Category:Ceramics manufacturers of France|Nevers]]\n[[Category:1588 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Nevers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bourgogne-Franche-Comt\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Faience of France]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ewer MET DT214721 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Mustard and blue solid-body wares, 1650-80, with Turkish-inspired birds and flowers.<ref>McNab, 18-20; [https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194289 Ewer page at Metropolitan Museum]</ref>]] \n[[File:Maiolica di nevers, trionfo di cesare in roma, 1600-1630 circa.JPG|thumb|Nevers dish in the ''istoriato'' style, with the ''Triumph of Julius Caesar'', very loosely [[Triumphs of Caesar (Mantegna)|after Mantegna]], 1600\u20131630]]\nThe city of [[Nevers]], [[Ni\u00e8vre]], now in the [[Bourgogne-Franche-Comt\u00e9]] [[Regions of France|region]] in central France, was a centre for manufacturing [[faience]], or [[Tin-glazed pottery|tin-glazed earthenware]] pottery, between around 1580 and the early 19th century, production then gradually dying down to a single factory, before a revival in the 1880s.  In 2017, there were still two potteries making it in the city, after a third had closed.<ref>[https://www.lejdc.fr/nevers/economie/commerce-artisanat/2017/04/01/desormais-nevers-ne-compte-plus-que-deux-faienceries_12346253.html \"D\u00e9sormais, Nevers ne compte plus que deux fa\u00efenceries\"], Lara Payet, 1 April 2017, ''Le Journal du Centre'' (in French); [http://faiencedenevers.fr/les-faienciers-actuels/ \"les faienciers actuels\"], faiencedenevers.fr - still the case in 2020</ref>  However the quality and prestige of the wares has gradually declined, from a fashionable luxury product for the court, to a traditional regional speciality using styles derived from the past.\n[[File:Faience Nevers 6868.jpg|thumb|17th-century plate with genteel party in a European-style landscape. The border has birds, flowers and a rabbit, all at the same size.<ref>Estienne, 52-54</ref>]]\n\nNevers faience was one of the centres where the ''istoriato'' style of [[Italian maiolica]] was transplanted in the 16th century, and flourished for rather longer than in Italy itself.  In the 17th century Nevers was then a pioneer in imitating Asian ceramic styles in Europe, within some decades followed by all producers of fine wares.  The second half of the 17th century was Nevers' finest period, with several styles being made at the same time, including a grandiose Italianate Court style.<ref>McNab, 20-21; [http://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O1156287/jardiniere-unknown/ V&A, Nevers] [[Jardiniere]]</ref>   \n\nBy the time of the [[French Revolution]] Nevers wares had ceased to be fashionable and expensive,<ref>Garnier, 274\u2013275</ref> but the relatively crudely painted ''faiences patriotiques'' wares commenting on political events have great interest and charm.<ref>Though not to Garnier, 275, who is very rude about them</ref>  A late 19th-century revival concentrated on high-quality revivalist wares recreating past glories.    \n \n==History==\nThe tradition owes its origin to [[Louis Gonzaga, Duke of Nevers]] (1539\u20131595), a half-French and half Italian politician and courtier who married the heiress of the [[Duke of Nevers|Duchy of Nevers]], which then still gave him great powers in the [[County and Duchy of Nevers]].  He had been born in [[Mantua]], near several centres for Italian [[maiolica]], which had already spread to [[Rouen]] and [[Lyons]], and encouraged some Italian potters to move to the city.  Giulio Gambin was already in Lyons and the Conrade brothers (Corrado in Italy) came from [[Albisola]], who would found the dynasty that dominated Nevers production for a century.<ref>Coutts, 28; Moon; McNab, 12; Britannica</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=[[Birmingham Museum of Art]]|title=Birmingham Museum of Art : guide to the collection|year=2010|publisher=Birmingham Museum of Art|location=[Birmingham, Ala]|isbn=978-1-904832-77-5|pages=173}}</ref>   \n\nNevers already had a local unglazed pottery industry, and was a very suitable location for making faience. The city was near deposits of excellent pottery clay, an exceptionally good type of sand for making [[ceramic glaze]], forests for wood for the kilns, and was on the major [[Loire]] river.  The earliest dated piece by the Italians is from 1587.<ref>Estienne, 46</ref> \n\nIn 1603 the brothers received a monopoly from [[Henry IV of France|Henri IV]] for the making of wares in the style of [[Faenza]], whether painted polychrome or with white grounds, and a generation later Antoine Conrade, son of Dominique, was made ''faiencier ordinaire'' to the young [[Louis XIV]] in 1644.<ref>Coutts, 27\u201328</ref>  This was repeated in the next generation for another Dominique Conrade, given his ''brevet'' in 1672.<ref>Garnier, 270</ref>\n[[File:Nevers7.JPG|thumb|''faience patriotique'' of the [[French Revolution]]. An aristocrat and bishop: \"Unhappiness re-unites us\", 1791.]]\n\nThe Conrade monopoly was not effective for long, with a second factory starting in 1632, and by 1652 there were four different potteries in Nevers, including one founded by Pierre Custode, whose family became the other main Nevers dynasty of potters.<ref>Garnier, 270; Chaffers, 148</ref>  \n\nThe French faience industry received a huge boost when, late in his reign in 1709, [[Louis XIV]] pressured the wealthy to donate their silver plate, previously what they normally used to dine, to his treasury to help pay for his wars.  They was an \"overnight frenzy\" as the elite rushed to get faience replacements of the best quality.  Nevers garden vases in blue and white were prominently used in the gardens of the [[Chateau de Versailles]].<ref>Moon; McNab, 30</ref>\n\nThe success of the wares led to several other factories opening in the early 18th century, and in 1743 the government limited the number to eleven, to prevent flooding the market.  In 1760 a twelfth was permitted.  By this period Nevers wares had been largely replaced at the top end of the market by other makers, but were producing large quantities of less expensive wares for a broader market.  They did not attempt to compete with the elegant [[Rococo]] style of the French porcelain factories, which was attempted rather successfully by some makers of faience, for example the [[Veuve Perrin]] factory in [[Marseilles]].  All twelve Nevers factories (still including the Conrade and Custode ateliers) were still in operation in 1790, but a commercial treaty with Great Britain in 1786 led to the French market being flooded by cheaper and better English [[creamware]]s, leading to crisis for all French manufacturers of faience, and by 1797 six had ceased operations, with the other six having reduced their workforce by half.<ref>Chaffers, 148\u2013149, who lists all 12; Badillet, 4; Osborne, 133; Britannica</ref>  \n\nBy this time European [[porcelain]] was becoming cheaper and more reliable, and making life difficult for producers of high-quality earthenware across Europe.<ref>Osborne, 133; Moon</ref>  The Nevers response was to produce topical ''faiences patriotiques'' with which the English were unlikely to compete (although they had done excellent business supplying the new American republic with patriotic wares).<ref>Britannica</ref>\n[[File:Manufacture du bout du monde, Sainte C\u00e9cile.jpg|thumb|Montagon plate with [[Saint Cecilia]], 1888]]\n\nIn 1838 700 workers were reported to be employed,<ref>de Saint-Fargeau, Girault, ''Guide pittoresque du voyageur en France: contenant la statistique ...'', Volume 2, 11, 1838, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6yQxAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA7 google books]</ref> but by 1846 only six factories remained, and by 1850 five.<ref>Badillet, 4</ref>  A [[porcelain]] manufactury in Nevers was also mentioned in 1844 by [[Alexandre Brongniart]], but little is known about it.<ref name=\"Litchfield\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=QsbMKOjvWiAC&pg=PA219 ''Pottery and Porcelain: A Guide to Collectors'' by Frederick Litchfield p.219]</ref>\n\nThe ''manufacture du Bout du monde'' (\"End of the World\" factory) was founded in 1648, and followed the general pattern of the Nevers factories.  By 1875 its fortunes had reached a low ebb, and it was bought by Antoine Montagnon, who had ambitious plans to relaunch it to supply the market for revivalist wares imitating 17th-century pieces, often large and complex pieces.<ref>Badillet, 4</ref><ref name=\"centre\">Dominique Romeyer, [http://www.lejdc.fr/nevers/loisirs/art-litterature/2015/05/19/vingt-cinq-dirigeants-se-sont-succede-a-la-tete-de-la-faiencerie-montagnon-en-367-ans_11445739.html \"Vingt-cinq dirigeants se sont succ\u00e9d\u00e9 \u00e0 la t\u00eate de la fa\u00efencerie Montagnon en 367 ans\"], ''Le Journal du Centre'' 19 May 2015</ref>  By 1881 it was the only factory left in Nevers.  The Montagnon factoriy (fa\u00efencerie) was successful for over a century, with 50 employees around 1900, and its wares exhibited at international exhibitions,<ref>Badillet, 4</ref> but the factory, by then the oldest in France, finally closed in 2015.<ref>Mont</ref>  In 2020, two factories remained in production, both mainly making traditional styles.<ref>[http://faiencedenevers.fr/les-faienciers-actuels/ \"les faienciers actuels\"], faiencedenevers.fr</ref>\n\n==Styles==\nThe list of stylistic periods devised by the French authority du Broc de Segange in his 1863 book on Nevers faience is still often repeated,<ref>Chaffers, 150</ref> though perhaps needing some adjustment. It shows several styles in use at particular dates, which is certainly the case:\n* 1600\u20131660: Italian style\n* 1650\u20131750: Chinese and Japanese style\n* 1630\u20131700: Persian style\n* 1640\u20131789: Franco-Nivernais style\n* 1700\u20131789: [[Rouen manufactory]] style\n* 1730\u20131789: ''Tradition de Moustiers'', imitating the faience of [[Moustiers-Sainte-Marie]] in the [[Alpes-de-Haute-Provence]]\n* 1770\u20131789: ''Gout de Saxe'', ie [[Meissen porcelain|Meissen]] style\n* 1789 on : Decadence.<ref>Chaffers, 150</ref>\n\nFran\u00e7oise Estienne, in the 1980s, divided Nevers production in the 17th century (extended slightly at both ends) into eleven \"families\" based on the decoration of a study group of 1874 pieces, mainly in French museums, looking at both subjects and styles.<ref>Estienne, 45 and throughout.  The locations of the group are described in note 6 on p. 47 - examples outside France appear to have been ignored completely.</ref>  \n\n===Italian style===\nThe Italian immigrants continued at Nevers the ''istoriato'' (narrative) style that was already in decline in Italy, until at least 1660. As was usual in Italy by 1580, designs were mostly adapted from [[old master print|prints]],<ref>Coutts, 27\u201328; McNab, 12</ref> and the outline set out on the pot by a ''ponci'' or [[stencil]], pushing charcoal dust through pin-pricks in a paper drawing or tracing from a print.<ref>McNab, 12</ref>  \n\nThe early pieces did not generally use distinctive marks or inscriptions, though sometimes painting \"Nevers\" on the base of important pieces, perhaps with a date \u2013 the earliest of these is 1589, on a dish in the [[Louvre]].<ref>Coutts, 28</ref>  As with painted [[Limoges enamel]] of the previous century, with which Nevers decoration has some similaritites, a high proportion of religious subjects illustrate [[Old Testament]] subjects.  As with Italian pieces, the subjects, especially those from the Old Testament or [[classical mythology]], tended to be named on the base, sometimes even with the bible chapter noted.<ref>Wilson, 202 for an Italian example; [https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194297 Metropolitan Museum page] for the \"Joseph and his brothers\" plate illustrated here.</ref>  \n\nThere is a good deal of uncertainty in the attribution of pieces between the Nevers workshops, and between Nevers pieces and those of other centres.<ref>Chaffers, 149, 151\u2013153 has an illustrated list of marks</ref>  The large dish with ''The Gathering of Manna'' illustrated below, a well-known piece, had been assumed to be Italian, and 16th century, until recently.  Though there are still uncertainties, it is now though to be moulded from an Italian dish (now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London), then painted as a matching pair of that.<ref>Wilson, 334\u2013337</ref>   A curious aspect of Nevers faience is that it never succeeded in producing a good red colour, unlike Rouen and other centres, the absence of which often enables Nevers pieces to be distinguished.<ref>Garnier, 275</ref>  \n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Sacrifice of Noah MET DP214750 (cropped).jpg|''Sacrifice of Noah'', 1580\u20131610, Nevers or Lyons\nFile:Dish with Joseph and His Brothers MET DP318841 (cropped).jpg|Dish with Joseph and His Brothers, 1630-45, after print by [[Bernard Salomon]]; Conrade workshop? \"Inscribed on back in blue: LES FRERE' DE JIOSEPH / VENUS A LUY EN EGIPTE / AU GENESE XLII (trans.: The brothers of Joseph came to him in Egypt in Genesis 42)\".<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194297 Metropolitan Museum page]</ref> \nFile:Basin or dish with The Gathering of Manna MET DP329029 (cropped).jpg|Basin or dish with ''The Gathering of Manna'', 1620-45, probably made as a pair to an Italian dish of the 1560s.<ref>Wilson, 334-337</ref> \nFile:Atelier d\u2019Antoine Conrade ou de Nicolas Estienne - Plat La Pluie de cailles dans le d\u00e9sert.jpg|The [[manna]] in the desert, attributed to Antoine Conrade or Nicolas Estienne \nFile:Plate with two lovers MET DP326528 (cropped).jpg|Plate with two lovers, dated 1644, \"perhaps\" Antoine Conrade.<ref>Wilson, 338; [https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194294 Metropolitan Museum page]</ref>\n\n</gallery>\n\n===Asian styles===\n[[File:Plat d'apparat \u00e0 d\u00e9cor de chinoiseries - Large ceremonial basin with chinoiseries - Nevers - 1660-1680 - Louvre - Inv OA 12546.JPG|thumb|Large dish (49.5 cm) with Chinese-style musicians in a landscape, unusually using two colours, flanked by two \"Persian style\" bowls with European-style painting]]\n\nWithin Estienne's study group of 1874 pieces, the \"Persian\" family were the most numerous, with 547, then the Chinese with 374, so 921 pieces in Asian styles in total, almost half.<ref>Estienne, 57-58</ref>  Nevers made the first Chinese-style [[blue and white porcelain|blue and white wares]] in France, with production running between about 1650 and 1700. Chinese styles would then be taken up by factories in [[Normandy]], especially following the foundation of the [[French East India Company]] in 1664.<ref name=\"Ward\"/><ref>Britannica</ref> \n\nA technique unique to Nevers in French faience, used on some pieces from about 1650 for a few decades, was to stain all the clay from which the body was made either in ''bleu de Nevers'' or (much more rarely) a mustard yellow ([[Wedgwood]] did the same for their [[jasperware]] a century later).  This was then painted in white or other colours, using various styles.  This style is traditionally known as \"Persian\", as decoration in white on a rich blue ground is often seen in [[Persian pottery]] of the period.  However the bird and flower painted decoration seen in most examples of the \"Persian\" style in fact derives more from Turkish [[Iznik pottery]], which  was reaching Europe through Italy.<ref>McNab, 18-20, 30 no 12; Estienne, 57</ref>   \n\nNevers adopted Chinese vase shapes early in the 17th century, earlier than Dutch [[Delftware]].<ref>McNab, 18</ref>  Some Nevers pieces clearly copy [[Chinese export porcelain]] in terms of their painted decoration, both the cheaper [[Kraak ware]] and better quality blue and white wares, whereas others have decoration based on Turkish, Persian or other Islamic Middle Eastern styles. These often have the blue background, which is unusual on Chinese export porcelain, where blue figures on a white ground are the norm in blue and white wares.<ref>McNab, 18\u201320; Estienne, 57-59</ref><ref name=\"Ward\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=mkJfbdTS--UC&pg=PA38 ''The Grove encyclopedia of materials and techniques in art'' Gerald W. R. Ward p.38]</ref>  \n\nMuch of the painting on pieces with a white ground copies that of Chinese blue and white [[Transitional porcelain]] (roughly 1625-90), a good deal of which was exported.  [[Chinese literati]] figures contemplating nature in a lush garden or landscape is a common subject in both countries, though the French treatments have some differences.<ref>Estienne, 58-59</ref> \n\nUnlike other French potteries, especially the porcelain factories of the early 18th century, influence from [[Japanese export porcelain]] styles such as [[Kakiemon]] is not found in Nevers wares.<ref>Estienne's long account makes no mention of Japan.</ref>  Estienne sees the ''decoration \u00e0 la bougie'', with white imitating splashes of candle-wax on a blue ground (see below), as of Chinese inspiration.  They compare with some much earlier [[Song dynasty]] wares, in particular the \"oil-spot\" glazes of [[Jian ware]] (around the 12th or 13th centuries), though Estienne is unable to explain how awareness of these could have reached France in the 17th century.<ref>Estienne, 60</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Assiette Nevers Conrade S\u00e8vres.jpg|Conrade plate, 1630s, imitating Chinese [[Kraak ware]]. \nFile:GardenVaseNevers-BMA (cropped).jpg|Garden vase, 1660-80; Chinese-style decor in white on a blue ground; the shape is entirely European. \nFile:Ariana museum - islamic pottery imitation - Plat - Nevers (France) - 1670 - 1680 - Inventaire AR 12748-2.jpg|\"Persian\"-style with ''bleu de Nevers'' ground, 1670s\nFile:Faience with Chinese scenes Nevers Manufactory 1680 1700.jpg|Chinese style, 1680-1700, blue on a white ground.\nFile:Nevers faience vases circa 1700.jpg|Chinese-style vases, c. 1700  \n\n</gallery>\n\n===Louis XIV Court style===\nAfter about 1650, Nevers adapted the new French Court style to faience, borrowing from metalwork and other decorative arts, and using prints after the new generation of court painters such as [[Simon Vouet]] and [[Charles Lebrun]] for the images.  The pieces were often extremely large and ornate, and apart from garden vases and wine-coolers, no doubt decorative rather than practical.<ref>McNab, 20-21; Moon; [http://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O1156287/jardiniere-unknown/ V&A, Nevers] [[Jardiniere]]</ref> \n\n<gallery widths=\"220px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Grand plat rond - L'enl\u00e8vement d'Europe - The Abduction of Europa - Nevers - 1675-1690 - Louvre - OA 1896.jpg|Central dish is 58 cm across, the main scene the ''Rape of Europa'', after an illustration of [[Ovid]] by [[Fran\u00e7ois Chauveau]], published in 1674 \nFile:Bassin \u00e0 rafraichir - L'Ivresse de Bacchus - Cooling Basin - The Drunkenness of Bacchus - Nevers - vers 1680 - Louvre - OA 11315 (cropped).jpg|Wine-cooler with ''The Drunkenness of Bacchus'', c. 1680\nFile:Wine jug (one of a pair) MET DT8115 (cropped).jpg|Pair of wine jugs, c. 1685, 56 cm high. [[Fran\u00e7ois Chauveau]]'s ''Rape of Europa'' is again used (left).\nFile:Vase avec sc\u00e8nes de bacchanales (Louvre, INV 5013).jpg|Large ewer with dancing bacchantes and satyrs, 1685\nFile:Lessines NDame a la Rose PM 093090 (cropped).jpg|Three Montagnon pieces in the style, after 1900\n\n</gallery>\n\n===European styles===\n[[File:Plat Nevers d\u00e9cor p\u00eacheur.JPG|thumb|Fisherman on the Loire near Nevers]]\nWares were also produced in a wide variety of styles drawing on European sources, and these came to dominate production in the 18th century, as the quality of Nevers wares declined.  After about 1750 the European porcelain factories largely replaced Asian exports as the dominant wares at the top of the market, but by this time Nevers faience was usually cruder, cheaper, and more \"popular\" in taste.  Some [[armorial porcelain|armorial wares]] were produced.<ref>McNab, 16</ref>  Nevers is on the [[Loire]] and many pieces have painted images of the local style of river boats, and the long arched bridge over the river.<ref>Badillet, Chapter 4 onwards</ref>\n\nIn the 17th century a favourite source for scenes with figures was the immensely long pastoral novel or romance ''[[L'Astr\u00e9e]]'' by [[Honor\u00e9 d'Urf\u00e9]], published between 1607 and 1627, and possibly the single most influential work of 17th century French literature.  The main characters, Astr\u00e9e and Celadon, spend time disguised as a shepherd and shepherdess, and this is the most popular depiction; very wide hats tend to indicate the pastoral life.  These scenes do not seem to take their compositions from prints, even approximately, nor relate to any specific moment in the story.  They seem to begin around 1640.<ref>Estienne, 54-55</ref>\n\nOther scenes show hunting and fishing, often drawing on Flemish prints,<ref>Estienne, 50, 55</ref> and a few specific historical moments. There is a dish with the signing of the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]] in 1659, with portraits of [[Cardinal Mazarin]] and [[Luis de Haro]], his Spanish counterpart.<ref>Estienne, 55-56</ref>  Many pieces, and many more borders, mix a range of elements: figures, birds and animals, flowers, and ornamental motifs, typically all at roughly the same size, for example a flower, rabbit, bird and man.<ref>Estienne, 52-54</ref>  \n\n<gallery widths=\"170px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Collections du Mus\u00e9e national de c\u00e9ramique de S\u00e8vres 17 (cropped).jpg|Rare Nevers \"Rustic ware\" dish, in the style of [[Bernard Palissy]], 1599, by Agostino Conrade\nFile:Mus\u00e9e national de C\u00e9ramique, saint S\u00e9bastien, Nevers 01 (cropped).jpg|Rare statue of [[Saint Sebastian]], about half life-size, c. 1630\nFile:Faience grand feu de Nevers 06859.jpg|Figure [[sconce]] (candleholder)\nFile:Vase - mus\u00e9e HCL - Charit\u00e9 (2) (cropped).jpg|Vase, 1650-1700\nFile:Plate MET ES633 (cropped).jpg|Characters from ''[[L'Astr\u00e9e]]'' in the \"Persian\" white on blue, c. 1675\nFile:Plate MET SF17 190 1779 img1 (cropped).jpg|Armorial dish, with characters from ''[[L'Astr\u00e9e]]'', 1650\u201375 \nFile:Nevers Vase with decoration \u00e0 la bougie.jpg|\"Candle\" style (''decoration \u00e0 la bougie''), imitating splashes of candle wax,<ref>McNab, 38 no. 12; Estienne, 60</ref> late 17th century\nFile:Nevers Factory - Large Plate - 1966.221 - Cleveland Museum of Art (cropped).tif|Astrological plate, 44 cm, perhaps with birthchart for \"Moderata Durant\", late 17th century.<ref>Estienne, 56</ref> \nFile:Gourde - mus\u00e9e HCL - c\u00e9ramique civile - 2007.0.3069.M (cropped).jpg|decorative pilgrim flask, 1700-1725\nFile:Bouteille - mus\u00e9e HCL - c\u00e9ramique civile - 2007.0.3074.M (cropped).jpg|Bottle, c. 1809\n</gallery>\n\n===''faiences parlantes''===\nThe ''faiences patriotiques'' of the Revolutionary period typically have one or two figures in the central section, rather crudely painted in a few colours, with a pro-revolutionary slogan or comment below in black cursive script. The earliest examples included pro-monarchist pieces.<ref>Chaffers, 149\u2013150 gives a number of examples; Britannica, F; [[:File:Carnavalet - pichet coeur ardent.jpg|Monarchist jug, c. 1789]]</ref>  The same style had been in use before the Revolution, and continued after it, the wider grouping being called ''faiences parlantes'' (\"talking faience\").  These were more comic or satirical than political.<ref>Britannica, N, F</ref>  Another type of pieces in this popular style, called ''faience patronymique'', showed the patron saint of the recipient, and were common as christening or birthday gifts.  These types were made in other centres, but Nevers was the leading producer.<ref>Britannica, F</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Bastilleteller.jpg|''[[Storming the Bastille]]'', c 1789\nFile:Serment clerg\u00e9 assiette.jpg|A priest swears \"with all my power\" to maintain the Constitution; the clergy were made to so swear (\"je jure de maintenir de tout mon pouvoir la constitution\") in November 1790 \nFile:Droits de l'homme assiette.jpg|\"Rights of Man\", c 1790\nFile:Plat au motif du train de bateaux (cropped).jpg|The Loire, with boats and the Nevers bridge, 1800\nFile:Arbre d'amour assiette.jpg|''Tree of Love'', a complex comic subject, 1803; the men are trying to hide from the women, a popular 18th century subject \n</gallery>\n\n==Collections==\nEstienne's group of 17th-century pieces included 227 in the Nevers museum, 179 at [[S\u00e8vres \u2013 Cit\u00e9 de la c\u00e9ramique|S\u00e8vres]], and 116 in the [[Chateau de Saumur]]. The [[Louvre]] had 49 pieces, but of the highest quality.<ref>Estienne, 47 note 6. At least today, many pieces at Nevers are loans from the Louvre.</ref>  [[J. P. Morgan]] collected Nevers wares, and left many to the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York (accessioned in 1917), including a number illustrated here.<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/194289 including the mustard ewer at the start of the article]</ref>  Most other major ceramic collections have examples, for example the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London has over 60.<ref>[http://collections.vam.ac.uk/search/?offset=0&limit=45&narrow=1&extrasearch=&q=Nevers+Tin-glazed+earthenware&commit=Search&quality=0&objectnamesearch=&placesearch=&after=&before=&namesearch=&materialsearch=&mnsearch=&locationsearch= a search on \"Nevers Tin-glazed earthenware\"] returns 80 results, but some are imitations, old attributions, photos etc.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat|Faience of Nevers}}\n\n* [[Orientalism in early modern France]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Badillet, Guy, ''Fa\u00efences de Nevers et Marine de Loire'' (in French), Chapter 3, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ptug6b11XrgC&pg=PP13 google books]\n*\"Britannica N\", [https://www.britannica.com/art/Nevers-faience \"Nevers faience\"], [[Encyclopedia Britannica]] online\n*\"Britannica F\", [https://www.britannica.com/art/faience-parlante#ref273139 \"Faience parlante\"], [[Encyclopedia Britannica]] online\n*[[William Chaffers|Chaffers, William]], ''Marks and Monograms on Pottery and Porcelain'', 1863, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-ikGAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA147 google books]\n*Coutts, Howard, ''The Art of Ceramics: European Ceramic Design, 1500\u20131830'', 2001, Yale University Press, {{ISBN|0300083874}}, 9780300083873, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fRfIfV3Eq_sC&pg=PA28 google books]\n*Estienne, Fran\u00e7oise, \"\u00c0 propos d'une \u00e9tude sur un centre de production de fa\u00efence en France: Nevers\", ''Histoire, \u00e9conomie & soci\u00e9t\u00e9'', 1989 8-1 pp. 45-60, [https://www.persee.fr/doc/hes_0752-5702_1989_num_8_1_1545 online] (in French, abstract in English)\n*Garnier, \u00c9douard, ''Histoire de la c\u00e9ramique, poteries, fa\u00efences et porcelaines chez tous les peuples depuis les temps anciens jusqu'\u00e0 nos jours'', 1882 reprinted 2012, Editorial MAXTOR, {{ISBN|9791020800183}}, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7nELBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA269 google books]\n*McNab, Jessie, ''Seventeenth-Century French Ceramic Art'', 1987, Metropolitan Museum of Art, {{ISBN|0870994905}}, 9780870994906, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tAnKFvwSmhwC&pg=PA12 google books]\n*\"Mont\": [http://faiencedenevers.fr/au-xixieme-et-xxieme-siecle/faiencerie-montagnon/ \"Faiencerie Montagnon\"], faiencedenevers.fr\n*Moon, Iris, \"French Faience\", in Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History, 2016, New York: The [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], [http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/ffai/hd_ffai.htm online]\n*Osborne, Harold (ed), ''The Oxford Companion to the Decorative Arts'', 1975, OUP, {{ISBN|0198661134}}\n*Wilson, Timothy, ''Maiolica: Italian Renaissance Ceramics in the Metropolitan Museum of Art'', 2016, Metropolitan Museum of Art, {{ISBN|1588395618}}, 9781588395610, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2i_ADAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover google books]\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Champfleury]] (pseudonym of Jules Fran\u00e7ois Felix Fleury-Husson), ''Histoire des fa\u00efences patriotiques sous la r\u00e9volution'', 1875 (3rd edn), E. Dentu, Paris, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=v6oNAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover fully online] (in French)\n*Reginster-Le Clanche, Fran\u00e7oise, ''Fa\u00efences de Nevers'', 2003, (in French)\n*Rosen, Jean, ''Faience de Nevers, 1585\u20131900'', 4 volumes, (in French)\n\n[[Category:Ceramics manufacturers of France|Nevers]]\n[[Category:1588 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Nevers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bourgogne-Franche-Comt\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Faience of France]]\n", "name_user": "Johnbod", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:sconce\u2192sconce (light fixture)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nevers_faience"}
{"title_page": "Ambivalent sexism", "text_new": "'''Ambivalent sexism''' is a theoretical (fictitious) framework which posits that [[sexism]] has two sub-components: \"hostile sexism\" and \"benevolent sexism\". Hostile sexism reflects overtly negative evaluations and [[stereotype]]s about a [[gender]] (e.g., the ideas that women are incompetent and inferior to men). Benevolent sexism represents evaluations of gender that may appear subjectively positive (subjective to the person who is evaluating), but are actually damaging to people and [[gender equality]] more broadly (e.g., the ideas that women need to be protected by men). For the most part, [[Psychology|psychologists]] have studied hostile forms of sexism. However, theorists using the theoretical framework of ambivalent sexism have found extensive [[empirical evidence]] for both varieties. The theory has largely been developed by [[Social psychology|social psychologists]] Peter Glick and [[Susan Fiske]].\n\n==General overview==\nSexism, like other forms of [[prejudice]], is a type of [[bias]] about a group of people. Sexism is founded in conceptualizations of one gender as being superior or having higher status than the other gender in a particular domain, which can lead to [[discrimination]]. Research has indicated that stereotypes about socially appropriate [[gender role]]s for women and men are a driving factor in the endorsement of sexism.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1471-6402.1997.tb00104.x |title=Hostile and Benevolent Sexism |year=1997 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=21 |pages=119\u201335}}</ref> [[Patriarchy]], defined as men's power and \"structural control over political, legal, economic, and religious institutions\",<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/> is a feature of sexism and is related to hostile attitudes toward women. [[Anthropology|Anthropological]] research suggests that patriarchy is pervasive among the majority of human societies, such that women have been systematically discriminated against, [[Oppression|oppressed]], and [[Marginalization|marginalized]] by men throughout history.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/> Sexism maintains patriarchal [[social structure]]s and reinforces prescribed gender roles.\n\nTypically, sexism is thought of as hostility toward women, perpetrated by men. However, both women and men can (and often do) endorse sexist beliefs about each other and themselves. In other words, men can express sexist attitudes about women or men, and women can express sexist attitudes about men or women. While sexism has historically disadvantaged women, there are negative consequences of sexism for both men and women.<ref name=\"Roets, A. 2012\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/per.843 |title=Is Sexism a Gender Issue? A Motivated Social Cognition Perspective on Men's and Women's Sexist Attitudes Toward Own and Other Gender |year=2012 |last1=Roets |first1=Arne |last2=Van Hiel |first2=Alain |last3=Dhont |first3=Kristof |journal=European Journal of Personality |volume=26 |issue=3 |pages=350\u20139|url=https://biblio.ugent.be/publication/2109456 |hdl=1854/LU-2109456 }}</ref> Rigid gender roles can be damaging to women and men alike, restricting opportunities and promoting gender-based prejudice. For the purposes of this article, sexism toward women will be the focus, as it is most relevant to the definition and study of ambivalent sexism.\n\nAmbivalent sexism offers a multidimensional reconceptualization of the traditional view of sexism to include both subjectively benevolent and hostile attitudes toward women.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.70.3.491 |title=The Ambivalent Sexism Inventory: Differentiating hostile and benevolent sexism |year=1996 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=70 |issue=3 |pages=491\u2013512|citeseerx=10.1.1.470.9865 }}</ref> The word \"ambivalent\" is used to describe the construal of sexism because this type of bias includes both negative and positive evaluations of women. The addition of a benevolent feature to definitions of gender-based prejudice was a major contribution to the study of sexism and field of psychology. Traditional conceptualizations of sexism focused almost entirely on overt hostility toward women. While historians, anthropologists, [[Feminist theory|feminist scholars]], and psychologists had previously suggested that sexism involves positive and negative evaluations of women, the majority of empirical research at the time evaluated only hostile expressions of sexism.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/><ref name=\"Glick, P. 2001\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0003-066X.56.2.109 |title=An ambivalent alliance: Hostile and benevolent sexism as complementary justifications for gender inequality |year=2001 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |journal=American Psychologist |volume=56 |issue=2 |pages=109\u201318 |pmid=11279804|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/e5c393e0f54f75edbdfbe8a507d6de755dd13bbb }}</ref> The introduction of the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory (ASI)\u2014a scale which was developed by Glick and Fiske in 1996, and which assesses ambivalently sexist attitudes\u2014marks a shift in how sexism is construed and scientifically measured. Glick and Fiske created the ASI to address a proposed deficiency in the measurement of sexism at the time.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> They argue that previous scales assessing sexism do not adequately capture the ambivalent nature of gender-based prejudice toward women.\n\n==Theoretical framework==\n\nGlick and Fiske assert that hostile and benevolent sexism complement each other in reinforcing [[tradition]]al gender roles and preserving patriarchal social structures of women as subordinate to men. Both forms of sexism share the assumption that women are inferior and restrict women to a lower [[social status]]. Hostile sexism reflects [[misogyny]] (i.e., the hatred of women by men) and is expressed through blatant negative evaluations of women.<ref name=\"Glick, P., Diebold, J., Bailey-Werner, B., & Zhu, L., 1997\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/01461672972312009 |title=The Two Faces of Adam: Ambivalent Sexism and Polarized Attitudes Toward Women |year=1997 |last1=Glick |first1=P. |last2=Diebold |first2=J. |last3=Bailey-Werner |first3=B. |last4=Zhu |first4=L. |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin |volume=23 |issue=12 |pages=1323\u201334}}</ref> Examples of hostile sexism include beliefs about women as incompetent, unintelligent, overly emotional, and sexually manipulative. Benevolent sexism reflects evaluations of women that are seemingly positive. Examples of benevolently sexist attitudes include the reverence of women in wife, mother, and child caretaker roles, the romanticizing of women as objects of [[Heterosexuality|heterosexual]] affection, and the belief that men have a duty to protect women.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> While benevolent sexism may not appear to be harmful to women on the surface, these beliefs are extremely caustic to gender equity and restrict women's personal, professional, political, and social opportunities. This is because these seemingly positive evaluations imply that (a) women are weak and need to be protected, (b) women should not deviate from traditional gender roles as mothers and caretakers, and (c) women should be idolized by men for their [[sexual purity]] and availability.\n\nBecause benevolently sexist attitudes appear positive, people often do not identify these beliefs as a form of gender-based prejudice. Furthermore, benevolent sexism may be seen by both men and women as reinforcing of the status quo, which some individuals may find comforting.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684312456369 |title=Why is Benevolent Sexism Appealing?: Associations with System Justification and Life Satisfaction |year=2012 |last1=Connelly |first1=K. |last2=Heesacker |first2=M. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=432\u201343}}</ref> Social and cultural [[norm (social)|norm]]s may encourage benevolently sexist beliefs among women and men. A classic illustration of this is the endorsement of [[Chivalry#Modern manifestations and revivals|modern-day chivalry]] in interactions between women and men.<ref name=\"Herzog, S. & Oreg, S., 2008\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1540-5893.2008.00334.x |title=Chivalry and the Moderating Effect of Ambivalent Sexism: Individual Differences in Crime Seriousness Judgments |year=2008 |last1=Herzog |first1=Sergio |last2=Oreg |first2=Shaul |journal=Law & Society Review |volume=42 |pages=45\u201373}}</ref> It can be considered traditional and polite for a man to insist that he holds a door open or carries a heavy object for a woman. However, this tradition is founded in historical representations of women as weaker than men. In these types of circumstances, people may find it difficult to distinguish between kindness, tradition, and benevolent sexism. Men and women often disagree on whether or not a specific incident should be considered sexist.<ref name=\"Guteg, B. A., & O'Conner, M., 1995\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1995.tb01314.x |title=The Empirical Basis for the Reasonable Woman Standard |year=1995 |last1=Gutek |first1=Barbara A. |last2=O'Connor |first2=Maureen |journal=Journal of Social Issues |volume=51 |pages=151\u201366}}</ref> In general, women and men tend to show more agreement in classifying extreme and overt expressions of sexism.<ref name=\"Guteg, B. A., & O'Conner, M., 1995\"/> Hostile sexism is typically easier for people to identify as an expression of prejudice.<ref name=\"Chisango, T. & Javangwe, G., 2012\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-012-0146-2 |title=Are People Better at Recognizing Ambivalent Sexism on the Basis of the Non-standard Profiles than the Standard ASI Ones? |year=2012 |last1=Chisango |first1=Tadios |last2=Javangwe |first2=Gwatirera |journal=Sex Roles |volume=67 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=69\u201382}}</ref>\n\nOverall, women are rarely perceived by others in an entirely hostile or benevolent manner. In fact, people frequently report high levels of both benevolent and hostile sexism.<ref name=\"Glick et al., 2000\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.79.5.763 |title=Beyond prejudice as simple antipathy: Hostile and benevolent sexism across cultures |year=2000 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |last3=Mladinic |first3=Antonio |last4=Saiz |first4=Jos\u00e9 L. |last5=Abrams |first5=Dominic |last6=Masser |first6=Barbara |last7=Adetoun |first7=Bolanle |last8=Osagie |first8=Johnstone E. |last9=Akande |first9=Adebowale |last10=Alao |first10=Amos |last11=Brunner |first11=Barbara |last12=Willemsen |first12=Tineke M. |last13=Chipeta |first13=Kettie |last14=Dardenne |first14=Benoit |last15=Dijksterhuis |first15=Ap |last16=Wigboldus |first16=Daniel |last17=Eckes |first17=Thomas |last18=Six-Materna |first18=Iris |last19=Exp\u00f3sito |first19=Francisca |last20=Moya |first20=Miguel |last21=Foddy |first21=Margaret |last22=Kim |first22=Hyun-Jeong |last23=Lameiras |first23=Maria |last24=Sotelo |first24=Maria Jos\u00e9 |last25=Mucchi-Faina |first25=Angelica |last26=Romani |first26=Myrna |last27=Sakalli |first27=Nuray |last28=Udegbe |first28=Bola |last29=Yamamoto |first29=Mariko |last30=Ui |first30=Miyoko  |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=79 |issue=5 |pages=763\u201375 |pmid=11079240|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/23eb7b57f821ec3b579605540b494d7c079a8467 }}</ref> There are individual differences in people's levels of benevolent and hostile sexism, such that a person can be rated highly on both, one, or neither dimension of the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory. In addition, women are not immune from endorsing sexist beliefs about women. Extensive research supports the idea that it is common for women and men to support ambivalently sexist attitudes about women.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2011\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684311414832 |pmid=24453402 |title=Ambivalent Sexism Revisited |year=2011 |last1=Glick |first1=P. |last2=Fiske |first2=S. T. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages=530\u20135|pmc=3896071 }}</ref> Despite this, people find it difficult to believe that others can endorse both benevolent and hostile sexism.<ref name=\"Chisango, T. & Javangwe, G., 2012\"/> Research suggests that, when individuals are shown profiles of a benevolently sexist man and a man who endorses hostile sexism, they feel that it is very unlikely that one person can embody both forms of bias.<ref name=\"Kilianski, S. E., & Rudman, L. A., 1998\">{{cite journal |title=Wanting It Both Ways: Do Women Approve of Benevolent Sexism?|doi=10.1023/A:1018814924402 |year=1998 |last1=Kilianski |first1=Stephen E. |last2=Rudman |first2=Laurie A. |journal=Sex Roles |volume=39 |issue=5/6 |pages=333\u201352}}</ref>\n\n==Sub-components and dimensions==\n\nSocial psychologists have suggested that sexism may be inherently different from other forms of ambivalent prejudice, in that there is interdependency between women and men in social structures.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2011\"/> A central argument to the theory of ambivalent sexism is the idea that there is a complicated balance of power between men and women, such that men have structural power and women have dyadic power (stemming from dependence between two people). Dyadic power reflects the notion that men depend on women to fulfill certain goals, such as heterosexual [[intimacy]] and childbearing. Glick and Fiske assert that men's dependence on women is what fuels benevolently sexist attitudes, leading to idolization and the placing of women on a pedestal.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> In other words, power relationships between men and women foster an ambivalent form of bias towards women.\n\nTheoretically, each form of sexism is composed of three subcomponents: [[paternalism]], gender differentiation, and heterosexuality.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/> Paternalism reflects views of women as underdeveloped adults, providing justification for men to be authoritative and monitor, protect, and make decisions on women's behalf. Gender differentiation promotes the assumption that biological differences between males and females justify the strict adherence to socially prescribed gender roles. Heterosexuality\u2014described as the most prominent cause of men's ambivalence toward women\u2014reflects a tension between genuine desires for closeness and intimacy and a fear of women attaining power over men through sexual attraction.\n\nWithin hostile sexism (HS) and benevolent sexism (BS), the three subcomponents serve distinct functions. Dominative paternalism (HS) suggests that men should control women, while protective paternalism (BS) implies that men should protect and care for women. Competitive gender differentiation (HS) bolsters men's self-confidence (e.g., men are superior to women). Complementary gender differentiation (BS) places importance on traditional gender roles for women (e.g., mother & wife) and assumes that men depend on women to fulfill these roles. Lastly, heterosexual hostility (HS) views women as [[Sexual objectification|sexual objects]] for men's pleasure and promotes the fear of women's capacity to manipulate men by engaging in or withholding sexual activity. Intimate heterosexuality (BS) romanticizes women as having sexual purity and views romantic intimacy as necessary to complete a man.\n\n==Ambivalent Sexism Inventory==\n\nResearchers typically measure ambivalent sexism at the individual level. The primary method used to measure an individual's endorsement of ambivalent sexism is the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory (ASI), created by Glick and Fiske in 1996. The ASI is a 22-item [[Self-report inventory|self-report measure]] of sexism on which respondents indicate their level of agreement with various statements, which are placed on a 6-point [[Likert scale]].<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> It is composed of two sub-scales that may be independently calculated for sub-scale scores or may be averaged for an overall composite sexism score. The first sub-scale is the hostile sexism scale, which is composed of 11 items designed to assess an individual's position on the dimensions of dominative paternalism, competitive gender differentiation, and heterosexual hostility, as previously defined. A sample item from the hostile sexism sub-scale is \"Women are too easily offended.\" The second sub-scale is the benevolent sexism scale, which is composed of 11 items that aim to assess an individual's position on the dimensions of protective paternalism, complementary gender differentiation, and heterosexual intimacy, as previously defined. A sample item from the benevolent sexism sub-scale is \"Women should be cherished and protected by men.\"\n\nOver fifteen years of additional research and replications support that this inventory possesses [[psychometric]] characteristics indicating that the measure is both empirically reliable and valid. Standard criteria in psychological research can be utilized to evaluate a scale.<ref name=\"McHugh, M. C., & Frieze, I. H., 1997\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1471-6402.1997.tb00097.x |title=The Measurement of Gender-Role Attitudes A Review and Commentary |year=1997 |last1=McHugh |first1=Maureen C. |last2=Frieze |first2=Irene Hanson |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=21 |pages=1\u201316}}</ref> Using statistics, a [[Cronbach's alpha]] coefficient can be calculated to indicate whether items on a scale seem to be measuring the same psychological construct or dimension (demonstrating the retestability of a scale). Generally, researchers agree that a Cronbach's alpha coefficient above 0.80 suggests strong reliability in a scale. The ASI has consistently demonstrated this empirical reliability over time.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2011\"/> In addition, empirical evaluations of the ASI provide support for the validity of the scale, such that the inventory seems to effectively measure what it proposes to assess: a polarized attitude towards women, where both dimensions can be activated simultaneously.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2011\"/>\n\nThe utility of the ASI is not limited to English speakers.<ref name=\"Dardenne, 2006\">{{cite journal |doi=10.4074/S0003503306002041 |title=Structure latente et validation de la version fran\u00e7aise de l'Ambivalent Sexism Inventory : l'\u00e9chelle de sexisme ambivalent |trans-title=Latent Structure of the French Validation of the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory : \u00c9chelle de Sexisme Ambivalent |language=French |year=2009 |last1=Dardenne |first1=Benoit |last2=Delacollette |first2=Nathalie |last3=Gr\u00e9goire |first3=Christine |last4=Lecocq |first4=Delphine |journal=L'Ann\u00e9e Psychologique |volume=106 |issue=2 |pages=235\u201363|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/64d860dac8f802539ae02cf30aeb925a8f5669b5 }}</ref> There is extensive support for the cross-cultural validity of the ASI. A cross-cultural study examining the theory of ambivalent sexism in 19 countries found that hostile and benevolent components of sexism are not culturally specific.<ref name=\"Glick et al., 2000\"/> Furthermore, research suggests that ambivalently sexist attitudes towards men exist, such that hostile and benevolent attitudes toward men are found cross-culturally.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2004\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.86.5.713 |title=Bad but Bold: Ambivalent Attitudes Toward Men Predict Gender Inequality in 16 Nations |year=2004 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Lameiras |first2=Maria |last3=Fiske |first3=Susan T. |last4=Eckes |first4=Thomas |last5=Masser |first5=Barbara |last6=Volpato |first6=Chiara |last7=Manganelli |first7=Anna Maria |last8=Pek |first8=Jolynn C. X. |last9=Huang |first9=Li-li |last10=Sakalli-Ugurlu |first10=Nuray |last11=Rodr\u00edguez Castro |first11=Yolanda Rodriguez |last12=Pereira |first12=Maria Luiza |last13=Willemsen |first13=Tineke M. |last14=Brunner |first14=Annetje |last15=Six-Materna |first15=Iris |last16=Wells |first16=Robin |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=86 |issue=5 |pages=713\u201328 |pmid=15161396 |last17=Glick |first17=P}}</ref> These studies provide additional empirical evidence that support the framework of ambivalent sexism.\n\n===Critiques===\n\nWhile the ASI is widely used and accepted among researchers,<ref name=\"Kilianski, S. E., & Rudman, L. A., 1998\"/> one limitation of the ASI is that it is a self-reported measure.<ref name=\"Sakalli-Ugurlu, 2002\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00223980209604825 |title=Turkish College Students' Attitudes Toward Women Managers: The Effects of Patriarchy, Sexism, and Gender Differences |year=2002 |last1=Sakalli-Ugurlu |first1=Nuray |last2=Beydogan |first2=Basak |journal=The Journal of Psychology |volume=136 |issue=6 |pages=647\u201356 |pmid=12523452}}</ref> [[Social desirability]] is a common limitation of self-report measures in survey research; when participants in a research study complete a written self-report questionnaire, respondents are vulnerable to answering the items in a socially desirable manner. For this reason, some researchers employ variations of the ASI in their study designs that do not require self-reports. For example, Dardeene, Dumont, and Bollier (2007) transformed some items from the ASI into scenarios, presenting them to participants to induce conditions of both hostile and benevolent sexism.<ref name=\"Dardenne, 2006\"/> Hebl, King, Glick, Singletary, and Kazama (2007) designed a field study in which they observed the sexist behaviors of others; they used the theory of ambivalent sexism and the ASI to generate items for their own measure to assess these observed behaviors.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0021-9010.92.6.1499 |title=Hostile and benevolent reactions toward pregnant women: Complementary interpersonal punishments and rewards that maintain traditional roles |year=2007 |last1=Hebl |first1=Michelle R. |last2=King |first2=Eden B. |last3=Glick |first3=Peter |last4=Singletary |first4=Sarah L. |last5=Kazama |first5=Stephanie |journal=Journal of Applied Psychology |volume=92 |issue=6 |pages=1499\u2013511 |pmid=18020792|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/24461ffb925a31d3333b85920851786688ac8c51 }}</ref>\n\nAnother criticism of the ASI is that the labels of the two sub-constructs, \"benevolent\" and \"hostile\", are too abstract, do not generalize to certain languages, and may not be relevant to some cultures.<ref name=\"Chisango, T. & Javangwe, G., 2012\"/>\n\nLastly, findings from the Conn, Hanges, Sipe, and Salvaggio (1999) study suggest that other sexism scales may measure ambivalent attitudes towards women.<ref name=\"Conn, A., Paul, H., Sipe, W., & Salvaggio, A., 1999\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/00131649921970242 |title=The Search for Ambivalent Sexism: A Comparison of Two Measures |year=1999 |last1=Conn |first1=A. B. |last2=Hanges |first2=P. J. |last3=Sipe |first3=W. P. |last4=Salvaggio |first4=A. N. |journal=Educational and Psychological Measurement |volume=59 |issue=6 |pages=898\u2013909}}</ref> Glick and Fiske originally proposed the theoretical framework of ambivalent sexism as filling a gap in the psychological literature and providing a novel tool for assessing a new dimension of sexism: benevolent sexism.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> However, Conn and colleagues (1999), using [[confirmatory factor analysis]], showed that the Modern Sexism Scale (Swim, Aikin, Hall, and Hunter, 1995) captures ambivalent sentiments toward women, such that it identifies individuals that appear nonsexist but actually endorse sexist attitudes.<ref name=\"Conn, A., Paul, H., Sipe, W., & Salvaggio, A., 1999\"/> Results from this study suggest that, while both the Modern Sexism Scale and the ASI assess ambivalence toward women, the ASI is unique in its capabilities for separately measuring both hostile and benevolent attitudes. In addition, the ASI captures heterosexual intimacy and benevolent paternalism, whereas the Modern Sexism Scale does not.\n\n==Empirical support==\n\nWhile many individuals{{specify|date=July 2018}} endorse both benevolent and hostile sexism simultaneously, research{{by whom|date=July 2018}} suggests that people rated significantly higher in one of the two sub-components have distinct constellations of beliefs and patterns of behavior. In other words, someone who is high in benevolent sexism tends to show a different profile of attitudes than someone who is high in hostile sexism. The independence of these types of sexism in predicting human behavior indicates that the two are, in fact, discrete forms of bias on separate but related axes. Examples of research findings identifying disparate outcomes between benevolent sexism and hostile sexism are described below. In addition, the relationships between ambivalent sexism and a range of other related attitudes and behaviors are discussed.\n\n===Attitudes toward sexual harassment, intimate partner violence, and rape===\n\nMen who are ambivalently sexist (i.e., high in both benevolent and hostile sexism simultaneously) and men who are high in hostile sexism are more likely to tolerate the [[sexual harassment]] of women than men who are benevolently sexist.<ref name=\"Russell, B. L., & Trigg, K., 2004\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1023/B:SERS.0000023075.32252.fd |title=Tolerance of Sexual Harassment: An Examination of Gender Differences, Ambivalent Sexism, Social Dominance, and Gender Roles |year=2004 |last1=Russell |first1=Brenda L. |last2=Trigg |first2=Kristin Y. |journal=Sex Roles |volume=50 |issue=7/8 |pages=565\u201373}}</ref> Overall, hostile sexism is associated with acceptance of sexual harassment.<ref name=\"Begany, J., & Milburn, M., 2002\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/1524-9220.3.2.119 |title=Psychological predictors of sexual harassment: Authoritarianism, hostile sexism, and rape myths |year=2002 |last1=Begany |first1=Joseph J. |last2=Milburn |first2=Michael A. |journal=Psychology of Men & Masculinity |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=119\u201326}}</ref> In addition, the endorsement of hostile sexism is related to attitudes about [[intimate partner violence]] perpetrated by men towards women, such that people that are high in hostile sexism are more tolerant of intimate partner violence.<ref name=\"Glick, P., Sakalli-Ugurlu, N., Ferreira, M., & de Souza, M. 2002\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/1471-6402.t01-1-00068 |title=Ambivalent Sexism and Attitudes Toward Wife Abuse in Turkey and Brazil |year=2002 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Sakalli-Ugurlu |first2=Nuray |last3=Ferreira |first3=Maria Cristina |last4=Aguiar De Souza |first4=Marcos |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=292\u20137}}</ref> Benevolently sexist attitudes were not found to be a significant predictor of the tolerance of intimate partner violence. However, the endorsement of benevolent sexism was not a protective factor either. Lastly, men high in hostile sexism are more likely to rape women, whereas men that are high in benevolent sexism are more likely to [[Victim-blaming|blame a victim]] of rape for the attack.<ref name=\"Viki & Abrams, 2002\">{{cite journal |title=But She Was Unfaithful: Benevolent Sexism and Reactions to Rape Victims Who Violate Traditional Gender Role Expectations|doi=10.1023/A:1021342912248 |year=2002 |last1=Viki |first1=G. Tendayi |last2=Abrams |first2=Dominic |journal=Sex Roles |volume=47 |issue=5/6 |pages=289\u201393}}</ref>\n\n===Close relationships and attraction===\n\nResearch has shown that sexist attitudes relate to preferences for certain characteristics in romantic partners.<ref name=\"Sibley & Overall, 2011\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684311401838 |title=A Dual Process Motivational Model of Ambivalent Sexism and Gender Differences in Romantic Partner Preferences |year=2011 |last1=Sibley |first1=C. G. |last2=Overall |first2=N. C. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=303\u201317}}</ref> Evidence suggests that women with higher levels of benevolent sexism have more stereotypical preferences in men as romantic partners, such as financial security and resources. Men with higher levels of hostile sexism are more likely to value physical attractiveness in women as romantic partners. In addition, benevolent sexism tends to predict mate selection, whereas hostile sexism tend to predict subsequent marriage norms after pairing.<ref name=\"Chen, Fiske, & Lee, 2009\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-009-9585-9 |title=Ambivalent Sexism and Power-Related Gender-role Ideology in Marriage |year=2009 |last1=Chen |first1=Zhixia |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |last3=Lee |first3=Tiane L. |journal=Sex Roles |volume=60 |issue=11\u201312 |pages=765\u2013778 |pmid=24058258 |pmc=3777654}}</ref> Women find men high in benevolent sexism attractive, and rate men high in ambivalent sexism as less attractive.<ref name=\"Bohner, Ahlborn, & Steiner, 2010\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-009-9665-x |title=How Sexy are Sexist Men? Women's Perception of Male Response Profiles in the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory |year=2009 |last1=Bohner |first1=Gerd |last2=Ahlborn |first2=Katrin |last3=Steiner |first3=Regine |journal=Sex Roles |volume=62 |issue=7\u20138 |pages=568\u201382}}</ref> Furthermore, in a recent research study on a particular aspect of benevolent sexism, protective paternalistic beliefs, women endorsed more protective paternalistic beliefs for men (toward women) in romantic versus work contexts. The endorsement of these beliefs in romantic contexts is thought to serve to reinforce and maintain such benevolent sexist behaviors.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684312454842 |title=Prescription of Protective Paternalism for Men in Romantic and Work Contexts |year=2012 |last1=Sarlet |first1=M. |last2=Dumont |first2=M. |last3=Delacollette |first3=N. |last4=Dardenne |first4=B. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=444\u201357|url=http://orbi.ulg.ac.be/handle/2268/129459 }}</ref> Overall, benevolent sexism and hostile sexism are associated with beliefs that [[premarital sex]] is unacceptable for women.<ref name=\"Sakalli-Ugurlu & Glick, 2003\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00224490309552194 |title=Ambivalent sexism and attitudes toward women who engage in premarital sex in Turkey |year=2003 |last1=Sakalh\u2010U\u011furlu |first1=Nuray |last2=Glick |first2=Peter |journal=Journal of Sex Research |volume=40 |issue=3 |pages=296\u2013302 |pmid=14533024}}</ref>\n\n===Women in the workplace===\n\nWhile the consequences of hostile sexism in the workplace are more widely known and accepted, research has shown that benevolent sexism may have a more severe impact on a women's cognitive performance.<ref name=\"Dardenne, 2006\"/> Dardenne, et al.(2006) suggested that hostile sexism can elicit anger or frustration in the target, which may increase her motivation to succeed or perform. Benevolent sexism, because of its seemingly positive evaluations and implicit attributions, is likely to hinder a woman's confidence and performance. The researchers showed that, in a typical team working environment, hostile sexism as well as benevolent sexism had consequences for the participant's performance. Masser and Abrams (2004) highlighted the fact that previous research has shown that benevolent sexism can have detrimental effects on a woman's performance evaluation if that woman violates social norms associated with certain sexist attitudes.<ref name=\"Masser, B. M.& Abrams, D., 2004\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-004-5470-8 |title=Reinforcing the Glass Ceiling: The Consequences of Hostile Sexism for Female Managerial Candidates |year=2004 |last1=Masser |first1=Barbara M. |last2=Abrams |first2=Dominic |journal=Sex Roles |volume=51 |issue=9\u201310 |pages=609\u201316|url=http://kar.kent.ac.uk/4384/1/abrams_reinforcing_glass.pdf }}</ref> Their study showed that hostile sexism, but not benevolent sexism, hurt women's evaluations and recommendations for promotion.\n\nAdditionally, studies have shown that benevolent sexist attitudes lead to lower professional evaluations from men and women.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/><ref name=\"Masser, B. M.& Abrams, D., 2004\"/> Using an experimental design, Masser and Abrams (2004) found that individuals with hostile sexist attitudes rated women lower when applying for a male-dominant position. Additionally, high hostile sexist individuals recommend men to fill the available position more often than women. The authors argue that this is one of the main contributors to the [[glass ceiling]] effect.\n\n===Help-seeking===\n\nIn a recent experimental study on the effects of benevolent sexism on [[help-seeking]] behaviors, researchers found that, when stereotypes of women as dependent were made salient, female college students were less willing to seek help. In addition, the more that help was sought, the worse women felt.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684312457659 |title=Thanks, but No Thanks: Women's Avoidance of Help-Seeking in the Context of a Dependency-Related Stereotype |year=2012 |last1=Wakefield |first1=J. R. H. |last2=Hopkins |first2=N. |last3=Greenwood |first3=R. M. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=423\u201331|url=http://irep.ntu.ac.uk/id/eprint/20119/1/220483_2565.pdf }}</ref> Therefore, benevolent sexism appears to hold consequences towards women's help-seeking when certain benevolent sexist stereotypes are made salient.\n\n=== Voting Behaviour ===\nDuring the 2016 US Presidential Election, researchers connected ambivalent sexism to voting intentions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/usappblog/2016/10/10/a-basket-of-deplorables-a-new-study-finds-that-trump-supporters-are-more-likely-to-be-islamophobic-racist-transphobic-and-homophobic/|title=A 'basket of deplorables'? A new study finds that Trump supporters are more likely to be Islamophobic, racist, transphobic and homophobic.|date=2016-10-10|newspaper=USAPP|last1=Blair |first1= Karen L. |language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-13}}</ref> In a non-representative sample of US voters, predominantly male, ambivalent sexism was found to be the sole predictor of intending to vote for someone other than Hillary Clinton in the election. For every step up on the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory, participants were 3.3 times more likely to be voting for someone other than Hillary Clinton. Of those not voting for Clinton, they were not necessarily being pulled over to the Trump campaign, but rather, many were intending to vote Third Party or were still undecided. While higher Islamophobia predicted a vote for Trump, lower Islamophobia and ''higher'' ambivalent sexism predicted being undecided or voting for a Third Party.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nAmbivalent sexism may also be endorsed by the media in the presentation of electoral candidates, consequentially influencing voting behaviour. In the article ''The Psychology of Voting, Digested'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sts.uea.ac.uk/adfs/ls/?SAMLRequest=jZJRT4MwEMe%2FStP3UUBgsxksuMW4ZCrZmA%2B%2BdeW2EaFFrkz99tYhyXxZTPp29%2B%2Bv97tOZ591RU7QYqlVTD3HpQSU1EWpDjHd5vejCZ0lUxR11fC0M0e1hvcO0BCbU8jPhZh2reJaYIlciRqQG8k36eOK%2B47Lm1YbLXVFSYoIrbGguVbY1dBuoD2VErbrVUyPxjTIGav0oVSObkAJcwSFjgLDfjDMZ0IiJQtLL23x%2FOAhhQadDoQjpNO9MVHskVXIKFkuYgphEIYycGEc7YN9CLvIl4Ece0UQRmMhI9uF2MFSoRHKxNR3vduR59mTexPu%2BjwMnJsweKUk%2Bx3lrlS9oGtz7%2Fom5A95no2y501Oycsg2jbQXis%2Fw9sLn9evFYNEmvxHWQ1GFMKIETZTdsEbdvpkActFpqtSfpG0qvTHvAVhwP4FypI%2B8nfzyTc%3D&RelayState=%2Fsaml%2F2%2Fsso%2Fuea.ac.uk%2Fc%2Fukfed%3FSAMLRequest%3DfZLNboMwEIRfBfkeDASS1gpINDk0UtqiQHvopTJmCVbApqzpz9sXQqukl0i%252Bzey3OyOvkDd1y%252BLeVGoP7z2gsb6aWiE7CSHpO8U0R4lM8QaQGcHS%252BGHHPNthbaeNFromVowInZFarbXCvoEuhe5DCnje70JSGdMioxQrmee6BlPZkKPQlUZjC93Q9CwgajryPZo8pRmxNsNBUvERfQbV%252BiCVrVsYhAoU2goMHe%252BlHh0BPXCbC7s%252FUkH7YwkFsbabkLwtvEIE%252BbIoA7%252BEBYgg8OfgOKU3ny8dL%252FAHG2IPW4WGKxMSz3FvZ647vMy9YY7HAv%252BVWMlv6jupCqkO1yvKJxOy%252ByxLZlOmF%252BjwlGcwkGg1Hs5Oi7uL6q9j%252BV%252FfJBpLuVLuil7wp2UtexyA202iaym%252Brbiu9ee6A24gJC6h0TTy%252F1NEPw%253D%253D%26RelayState%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fshibboleth.ebscohost.com%252FShibAgent.aspx%253Fshib_returl%253Dhttps%25253a%25252f%25252fsearch.ebscohost.com%25252flogin.aspx%25253fdirect%25253dtrue%252526db%25253da9h%252526AN%25253d102236392%252526authtype%25253dsso%252526custid%25253ds8993828%252526site%25253deds-live%252526scope%25253dsite%2526IdpId%253D|title=Sign In|website=sts.uea.ac.uk|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> a study is noted which revealed that 'obesity is a disadvantage for female candidates, but may help male candidates'. This is one example of how media coverage of female electoral candidates can prioritise appearance over capability, often using the former to shed a negative light over the latter.\n\nIt's also important to acknowledge that ambivalent sexism has a disproportionate effect on women of colour, and groups of women who may be more so marginalised because of the physical geography of where, or socio-political condition in which they live. The cost of voting participation may be too high for women; as put in an economic journal on female voting behaviour in Pakistan <ref>''Gine, X., & Mansuri, G. (2018). Together We Will: Experimental Evidence on Female Voting Behavior in Pakistan. American Economic Journal: Applied Economics, 10(1), 207\u2013235. <nowiki>https://doi.org/http://www.aeaweb.org/aej-applied/</nowiki>''</ref> , this might be because of 'cultural stereotypes that discourage the exercise of own preferences'. That is to say in an election, for example, the outcome may be a relatively low count of female voters when women are unable to choose to be active political agents alongside other socio-cultural responsibilities. \n\n<br />\n\n=== Plan A vs. Plan B ===\nBenevolent sexism is sometimes also referred to as Plan A. It can be used to have women act as a subordinate because it aims for the remarks to be perceived as \u2018good\u2019 or \u2018positive\u2019.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Gender: Ideas, Interactions, and Institutions 2nd Edition|last=Lisa Wade|first=Myra Marx Ferree|year=2019|isbn=978-0-393-66796-7|location=|pages=}}</ref> This targets a woman\u2019s sensitivity and need to be protected by a male, which may not seem so bad to some women. Plan B or hostile sexism is used as a more aggressive approach as it includes more harsh remarks, and can tend to anger the women more. Studies show that women are more likely to be defensive and inspired to protest against sexism when exposed to hostile sexist statements. When exposed to benevolently sexist remarks, they\u2019re less likely rally and protest. They take on a more subordinate and passive role. This is why benevolent sexism is Plan A when trying to get women to be subordinate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/psysociety/benevolent-sexism/|title=The Problem When Sexism Just Sounds So Darn Friendly...|last=Tannenbaum|first=Melanie|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Women's endorsement of ambivalent sexism==\n\nBoth benevolent and hostile sexism are considered legitimizing ideologies, in that these attitudes provide the justification for social inequalities between men and women.<ref name=\"Sidanius, Pratto, & Bobo, 1994\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.67.6.998 |title=Social dominance orientation and the political psychology of gender: A case of invariance? |year=1994 |last1=Sidanius |first1=Jim |last2=Pratto |first2=Felicia |last3=Bobo |first3=Lawrence |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=67 |issue=6 |pages=998\u20131011}}</ref> [[Social dominance orientation]] (SDO; Sidanius & Pratto, 1999) asserts that group-based inequalities are systematically reinforced by the disadvantaged group's adoption of the dominant group's ideology and social stratification.<ref name=\"Sidanius & Pratto 1999\">{{cite book |last1=Sidanius |first1=Jim |last2=Pratto |first2=Felicia |year=1999 |title=Social Dominance: An Intergroup Theory of Social Hierarchy and Oppression |location=New York |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-62290-5|doi=10.1017/CBO9781139175043}}{{page needed|date=November 2013}}</ref> Empirical research has consistently supported the validity of Social Dominance Theory,<ref name=\"Gaucher, Frieser, & Kay, 2011\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/a0022530 |title=Evidence that gendered wording in job advertisements exists and sustains gender inequality |year=2011 |last1=Gaucher |first1=Danielle |last2=Friesen |first2=Justin |last3=Kay |first3=Aaron C. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=101 |pages=109\u201328 |pmid=21381851 |issue=1}}</ref> and the SDO model of structural oppression may be particularly apt to describe how patriarchy is perpetuated.<ref name=\"Sibley et al, 2009\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-008-9554-8 |title=Your Sexism Predicts My Sexism: Perceptions of Men's (but not Women's) Sexism Affects One's Own Sexism over Time |year=2008 |last1=Sibley |first1=Chris G. |last2=Overall |first2=Nickola C. |last3=Duckitt |first3=John |last4=Perry |first4=Ryan |last5=Milfont |first5=Taciano L. |last6=Khan |first6=Sammyh S. |last7=Fischer |first7=Ronald |last8=Robertson |first8=Andrew |journal=Sex Roles |volume=60 |issue=9\u201310 |pages=682\u201393}}</ref>\n\nResearchers have explored reasons for why women might [[Internalisation (sociology)|internalize]] ambivalently sexist attitudes towards women. Fischer (2006) found that women may develop benevolently sexist attitudes as a response to experiencing sexism themselves.<ref name=\"Fischer, 2006\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1471-6402.2006.00316.x |title=Women's Benevolent Sexism As Reaction to Hostility |year=2006 |last1=Fischer |first1=Ann R. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=30 |issue=4 |pages=410\u20136}}</ref> Cross-cultural research suggests that women's endorsement of benevolent sexism often reflects a culture of extreme hostile sexism among men in a given community.<ref name=\"Glick et al., 2000\"/> Some researchers argue that, in cultures that are particularly hostile, women may internalize benevolent sexism as a protective mechanism.\n\nSome research indicates that women perceived men high in benevolent sexism to possess positive attitudes towards women, while by contrast men low in benevolent sexism were perceived to be misogynistic and possessing high levels of hostile sexism, when in reality men who reject benevolent sexism also tend to reject hostile sexism. If the man stated that his rejection of benevolent sexism was motivated by egalitarian values then the perception that he was a hostile sexist was somewhat mitigated, though not entirely.<ref>Yeung, Amy. [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/45b2/607b3f62fe4d0029ee602103d1a0811f11f1.pdf \"Chivalry is far from dead: Misperceiving the link between men's benevolent and hostile sexism.\"] (2018).</ref><ref>Yeung, Amy. \"Lay misperceptions of the relationship between men\u2019s benevolent and hostile sexism.\" Master's thesis, University of Waterloo, 2012.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ambivalent prejudice]]\n* [[Women are wonderful]]\n* [[Aversive racism]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last1=Good |first1=Jessica J. |editor1-last=Nadal |editor1-first=K.L. |title=The SAGE Encyclopedia of Psychology and Gender|date=2017 |publisher=SAGE Publications |location=Thousand Oaks, Calif. |isbn=978-1-48-338427-6 |pages=136\u20137 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=lVYoDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 |language=en |chapter=Benevolent Sexism}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sexism]]\n[[Category:Gender theories]]\n\n[[fr:Sexisme ambivalent]]\n", "text_old": "'''Ambivalent sexism''' is a theoretical framework which posits that [[sexism]] has two sub-components: \"hostile sexism\" and \"benevolent sexism\". Hostile sexism reflects overtly negative evaluations and [[stereotype]]s about a [[gender]] (e.g., the ideas that women are incompetent and inferior to men). Benevolent sexism represents evaluations of gender that may appear subjectively positive (subjective to the person who is evaluating), but are actually damaging to people and [[gender equality]] more broadly (e.g., the ideas that women need to be protected by men). For the most part, [[Psychology|psychologists]] have studied hostile forms of sexism. However, theorists using the theoretical framework of ambivalent sexism have found extensive [[empirical evidence]] for both varieties. The theory has largely been developed by [[Social psychology|social psychologists]] Peter Glick and [[Susan Fiske]].\n\n==General overview==\nSexism, like other forms of [[prejudice]], is a type of [[bias]] about a group of people. Sexism is founded in conceptualizations of one gender as being superior or having higher status than the other gender in a particular domain, which can lead to [[discrimination]]. Research has indicated that stereotypes about socially appropriate [[gender role]]s for women and men are a driving factor in the endorsement of sexism.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1471-6402.1997.tb00104.x |title=Hostile and Benevolent Sexism |year=1997 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=21 |pages=119\u201335}}</ref> [[Patriarchy]], defined as men's power and \"structural control over political, legal, economic, and religious institutions\",<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/> is a feature of sexism and is related to hostile attitudes toward women. [[Anthropology|Anthropological]] research suggests that patriarchy is pervasive among the majority of human societies, such that women have been systematically discriminated against, [[Oppression|oppressed]], and [[Marginalization|marginalized]] by men throughout history.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/> Sexism maintains patriarchal [[social structure]]s and reinforces prescribed gender roles.\n\nTypically, sexism is thought of as hostility toward women, perpetrated by men. However, both women and men can (and often do) endorse sexist beliefs about each other and themselves. In other words, men can express sexist attitudes about women or men, and women can express sexist attitudes about men or women. While sexism has historically disadvantaged women, there are negative consequences of sexism for both men and women.<ref name=\"Roets, A. 2012\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/per.843 |title=Is Sexism a Gender Issue? A Motivated Social Cognition Perspective on Men's and Women's Sexist Attitudes Toward Own and Other Gender |year=2012 |last1=Roets |first1=Arne |last2=Van Hiel |first2=Alain |last3=Dhont |first3=Kristof |journal=European Journal of Personality |volume=26 |issue=3 |pages=350\u20139|url=https://biblio.ugent.be/publication/2109456 |hdl=1854/LU-2109456 }}</ref> Rigid gender roles can be damaging to women and men alike, restricting opportunities and promoting gender-based prejudice. For the purposes of this article, sexism toward women will be the focus, as it is most relevant to the definition and study of ambivalent sexism.\n\nAmbivalent sexism offers a multidimensional reconceptualization of the traditional view of sexism to include both subjectively benevolent and hostile attitudes toward women.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.70.3.491 |title=The Ambivalent Sexism Inventory: Differentiating hostile and benevolent sexism |year=1996 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=70 |issue=3 |pages=491\u2013512|citeseerx=10.1.1.470.9865 }}</ref> The word \"ambivalent\" is used to describe the construal of sexism because this type of bias includes both negative and positive evaluations of women. The addition of a benevolent feature to definitions of gender-based prejudice was a major contribution to the study of sexism and field of psychology. Traditional conceptualizations of sexism focused almost entirely on overt hostility toward women. While historians, anthropologists, [[Feminist theory|feminist scholars]], and psychologists had previously suggested that sexism involves positive and negative evaluations of women, the majority of empirical research at the time evaluated only hostile expressions of sexism.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/><ref name=\"Glick, P. 2001\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0003-066X.56.2.109 |title=An ambivalent alliance: Hostile and benevolent sexism as complementary justifications for gender inequality |year=2001 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |journal=American Psychologist |volume=56 |issue=2 |pages=109\u201318 |pmid=11279804|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/e5c393e0f54f75edbdfbe8a507d6de755dd13bbb }}</ref> The introduction of the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory (ASI)\u2014a scale which was developed by Glick and Fiske in 1996, and which assesses ambivalently sexist attitudes\u2014marks a shift in how sexism is construed and scientifically measured. Glick and Fiske created the ASI to address a proposed deficiency in the measurement of sexism at the time.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> They argue that previous scales assessing sexism do not adequately capture the ambivalent nature of gender-based prejudice toward women.\n\n==Theoretical framework==\n\nGlick and Fiske assert that hostile and benevolent sexism complement each other in reinforcing [[tradition]]al gender roles and preserving patriarchal social structures of women as subordinate to men. Both forms of sexism share the assumption that women are inferior and restrict women to a lower [[social status]]. Hostile sexism reflects [[misogyny]] (i.e., the hatred of women by men) and is expressed through blatant negative evaluations of women.<ref name=\"Glick, P., Diebold, J., Bailey-Werner, B., & Zhu, L., 1997\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/01461672972312009 |title=The Two Faces of Adam: Ambivalent Sexism and Polarized Attitudes Toward Women |year=1997 |last1=Glick |first1=P. |last2=Diebold |first2=J. |last3=Bailey-Werner |first3=B. |last4=Zhu |first4=L. |journal=Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin |volume=23 |issue=12 |pages=1323\u201334}}</ref> Examples of hostile sexism include beliefs about women as incompetent, unintelligent, overly emotional, and sexually manipulative. Benevolent sexism reflects evaluations of women that are seemingly positive. Examples of benevolently sexist attitudes include the reverence of women in wife, mother, and child caretaker roles, the romanticizing of women as objects of [[Heterosexuality|heterosexual]] affection, and the belief that men have a duty to protect women.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> While benevolent sexism may not appear to be harmful to women on the surface, these beliefs are extremely caustic to gender equity and restrict women's personal, professional, political, and social opportunities. This is because these seemingly positive evaluations imply that (a) women are weak and need to be protected, (b) women should not deviate from traditional gender roles as mothers and caretakers, and (c) women should be idolized by men for their [[sexual purity]] and availability.\n\nBecause benevolently sexist attitudes appear positive, people often do not identify these beliefs as a form of gender-based prejudice. Furthermore, benevolent sexism may be seen by both men and women as reinforcing of the status quo, which some individuals may find comforting.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684312456369 |title=Why is Benevolent Sexism Appealing?: Associations with System Justification and Life Satisfaction |year=2012 |last1=Connelly |first1=K. |last2=Heesacker |first2=M. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=432\u201343}}</ref> Social and cultural [[norm (social)|norm]]s may encourage benevolently sexist beliefs among women and men. A classic illustration of this is the endorsement of [[Chivalry#Modern manifestations and revivals|modern-day chivalry]] in interactions between women and men.<ref name=\"Herzog, S. & Oreg, S., 2008\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1540-5893.2008.00334.x |title=Chivalry and the Moderating Effect of Ambivalent Sexism: Individual Differences in Crime Seriousness Judgments |year=2008 |last1=Herzog |first1=Sergio |last2=Oreg |first2=Shaul |journal=Law & Society Review |volume=42 |pages=45\u201373}}</ref> It can be considered traditional and polite for a man to insist that he holds a door open or carries a heavy object for a woman. However, this tradition is founded in historical representations of women as weaker than men. In these types of circumstances, people may find it difficult to distinguish between kindness, tradition, and benevolent sexism. Men and women often disagree on whether or not a specific incident should be considered sexist.<ref name=\"Guteg, B. A., & O'Conner, M., 1995\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1540-4560.1995.tb01314.x |title=The Empirical Basis for the Reasonable Woman Standard |year=1995 |last1=Gutek |first1=Barbara A. |last2=O'Connor |first2=Maureen |journal=Journal of Social Issues |volume=51 |pages=151\u201366}}</ref> In general, women and men tend to show more agreement in classifying extreme and overt expressions of sexism.<ref name=\"Guteg, B. A., & O'Conner, M., 1995\"/> Hostile sexism is typically easier for people to identify as an expression of prejudice.<ref name=\"Chisango, T. & Javangwe, G., 2012\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-012-0146-2 |title=Are People Better at Recognizing Ambivalent Sexism on the Basis of the Non-standard Profiles than the Standard ASI Ones? |year=2012 |last1=Chisango |first1=Tadios |last2=Javangwe |first2=Gwatirera |journal=Sex Roles |volume=67 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=69\u201382}}</ref>\n\nOverall, women are rarely perceived by others in an entirely hostile or benevolent manner. In fact, people frequently report high levels of both benevolent and hostile sexism.<ref name=\"Glick et al., 2000\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.79.5.763 |title=Beyond prejudice as simple antipathy: Hostile and benevolent sexism across cultures |year=2000 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |last3=Mladinic |first3=Antonio |last4=Saiz |first4=Jos\u00e9 L. |last5=Abrams |first5=Dominic |last6=Masser |first6=Barbara |last7=Adetoun |first7=Bolanle |last8=Osagie |first8=Johnstone E. |last9=Akande |first9=Adebowale |last10=Alao |first10=Amos |last11=Brunner |first11=Barbara |last12=Willemsen |first12=Tineke M. |last13=Chipeta |first13=Kettie |last14=Dardenne |first14=Benoit |last15=Dijksterhuis |first15=Ap |last16=Wigboldus |first16=Daniel |last17=Eckes |first17=Thomas |last18=Six-Materna |first18=Iris |last19=Exp\u00f3sito |first19=Francisca |last20=Moya |first20=Miguel |last21=Foddy |first21=Margaret |last22=Kim |first22=Hyun-Jeong |last23=Lameiras |first23=Maria |last24=Sotelo |first24=Maria Jos\u00e9 |last25=Mucchi-Faina |first25=Angelica |last26=Romani |first26=Myrna |last27=Sakalli |first27=Nuray |last28=Udegbe |first28=Bola |last29=Yamamoto |first29=Mariko |last30=Ui |first30=Miyoko  |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=79 |issue=5 |pages=763\u201375 |pmid=11079240|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/23eb7b57f821ec3b579605540b494d7c079a8467 }}</ref> There are individual differences in people's levels of benevolent and hostile sexism, such that a person can be rated highly on both, one, or neither dimension of the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory. In addition, women are not immune from endorsing sexist beliefs about women. Extensive research supports the idea that it is common for women and men to support ambivalently sexist attitudes about women.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2011\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684311414832 |pmid=24453402 |title=Ambivalent Sexism Revisited |year=2011 |last1=Glick |first1=P. |last2=Fiske |first2=S. T. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages=530\u20135|pmc=3896071 }}</ref> Despite this, people find it difficult to believe that others can endorse both benevolent and hostile sexism.<ref name=\"Chisango, T. & Javangwe, G., 2012\"/> Research suggests that, when individuals are shown profiles of a benevolently sexist man and a man who endorses hostile sexism, they feel that it is very unlikely that one person can embody both forms of bias.<ref name=\"Kilianski, S. E., & Rudman, L. A., 1998\">{{cite journal |title=Wanting It Both Ways: Do Women Approve of Benevolent Sexism?|doi=10.1023/A:1018814924402 |year=1998 |last1=Kilianski |first1=Stephen E. |last2=Rudman |first2=Laurie A. |journal=Sex Roles |volume=39 |issue=5/6 |pages=333\u201352}}</ref>\n\n==Sub-components and dimensions==\n\nSocial psychologists have suggested that sexism may be inherently different from other forms of ambivalent prejudice, in that there is interdependency between women and men in social structures.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2011\"/> A central argument to the theory of ambivalent sexism is the idea that there is a complicated balance of power between men and women, such that men have structural power and women have dyadic power (stemming from dependence between two people). Dyadic power reflects the notion that men depend on women to fulfill certain goals, such as heterosexual [[intimacy]] and childbearing. Glick and Fiske assert that men's dependence on women is what fuels benevolently sexist attitudes, leading to idolization and the placing of women on a pedestal.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> In other words, power relationships between men and women foster an ambivalent form of bias towards women.\n\nTheoretically, each form of sexism is composed of three subcomponents: [[paternalism]], gender differentiation, and heterosexuality.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/> Paternalism reflects views of women as underdeveloped adults, providing justification for men to be authoritative and monitor, protect, and make decisions on women's behalf. Gender differentiation promotes the assumption that biological differences between males and females justify the strict adherence to socially prescribed gender roles. Heterosexuality\u2014described as the most prominent cause of men's ambivalence toward women\u2014reflects a tension between genuine desires for closeness and intimacy and a fear of women attaining power over men through sexual attraction.\n\nWithin hostile sexism (HS) and benevolent sexism (BS), the three subcomponents serve distinct functions. Dominative paternalism (HS) suggests that men should control women, while protective paternalism (BS) implies that men should protect and care for women. Competitive gender differentiation (HS) bolsters men's self-confidence (e.g., men are superior to women). Complementary gender differentiation (BS) places importance on traditional gender roles for women (e.g., mother & wife) and assumes that men depend on women to fulfill these roles. Lastly, heterosexual hostility (HS) views women as [[Sexual objectification|sexual objects]] for men's pleasure and promotes the fear of women's capacity to manipulate men by engaging in or withholding sexual activity. Intimate heterosexuality (BS) romanticizes women as having sexual purity and views romantic intimacy as necessary to complete a man.\n\n==Ambivalent Sexism Inventory==\n\nResearchers typically measure ambivalent sexism at the individual level. The primary method used to measure an individual's endorsement of ambivalent sexism is the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory (ASI), created by Glick and Fiske in 1996. The ASI is a 22-item [[Self-report inventory|self-report measure]] of sexism on which respondents indicate their level of agreement with various statements, which are placed on a 6-point [[Likert scale]].<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> It is composed of two sub-scales that may be independently calculated for sub-scale scores or may be averaged for an overall composite sexism score. The first sub-scale is the hostile sexism scale, which is composed of 11 items designed to assess an individual's position on the dimensions of dominative paternalism, competitive gender differentiation, and heterosexual hostility, as previously defined. A sample item from the hostile sexism sub-scale is \"Women are too easily offended.\" The second sub-scale is the benevolent sexism scale, which is composed of 11 items that aim to assess an individual's position on the dimensions of protective paternalism, complementary gender differentiation, and heterosexual intimacy, as previously defined. A sample item from the benevolent sexism sub-scale is \"Women should be cherished and protected by men.\"\n\nOver fifteen years of additional research and replications support that this inventory possesses [[psychometric]] characteristics indicating that the measure is both empirically reliable and valid. Standard criteria in psychological research can be utilized to evaluate a scale.<ref name=\"McHugh, M. C., & Frieze, I. H., 1997\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1471-6402.1997.tb00097.x |title=The Measurement of Gender-Role Attitudes A Review and Commentary |year=1997 |last1=McHugh |first1=Maureen C. |last2=Frieze |first2=Irene Hanson |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=21 |pages=1\u201316}}</ref> Using statistics, a [[Cronbach's alpha]] coefficient can be calculated to indicate whether items on a scale seem to be measuring the same psychological construct or dimension (demonstrating the retestability of a scale). Generally, researchers agree that a Cronbach's alpha coefficient above 0.80 suggests strong reliability in a scale. The ASI has consistently demonstrated this empirical reliability over time.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2011\"/> In addition, empirical evaluations of the ASI provide support for the validity of the scale, such that the inventory seems to effectively measure what it proposes to assess: a polarized attitude towards women, where both dimensions can be activated simultaneously.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2011\"/>\n\nThe utility of the ASI is not limited to English speakers.<ref name=\"Dardenne, 2006\">{{cite journal |doi=10.4074/S0003503306002041 |title=Structure latente et validation de la version fran\u00e7aise de l'Ambivalent Sexism Inventory : l'\u00e9chelle de sexisme ambivalent |trans-title=Latent Structure of the French Validation of the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory : \u00c9chelle de Sexisme Ambivalent |language=French |year=2009 |last1=Dardenne |first1=Benoit |last2=Delacollette |first2=Nathalie |last3=Gr\u00e9goire |first3=Christine |last4=Lecocq |first4=Delphine |journal=L'Ann\u00e9e Psychologique |volume=106 |issue=2 |pages=235\u201363|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/64d860dac8f802539ae02cf30aeb925a8f5669b5 }}</ref> There is extensive support for the cross-cultural validity of the ASI. A cross-cultural study examining the theory of ambivalent sexism in 19 countries found that hostile and benevolent components of sexism are not culturally specific.<ref name=\"Glick et al., 2000\"/> Furthermore, research suggests that ambivalently sexist attitudes towards men exist, such that hostile and benevolent attitudes toward men are found cross-culturally.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 2004\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.86.5.713 |title=Bad but Bold: Ambivalent Attitudes Toward Men Predict Gender Inequality in 16 Nations |year=2004 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Lameiras |first2=Maria |last3=Fiske |first3=Susan T. |last4=Eckes |first4=Thomas |last5=Masser |first5=Barbara |last6=Volpato |first6=Chiara |last7=Manganelli |first7=Anna Maria |last8=Pek |first8=Jolynn C. X. |last9=Huang |first9=Li-li |last10=Sakalli-Ugurlu |first10=Nuray |last11=Rodr\u00edguez Castro |first11=Yolanda Rodriguez |last12=Pereira |first12=Maria Luiza |last13=Willemsen |first13=Tineke M. |last14=Brunner |first14=Annetje |last15=Six-Materna |first15=Iris |last16=Wells |first16=Robin |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=86 |issue=5 |pages=713\u201328 |pmid=15161396 |last17=Glick |first17=P}}</ref> These studies provide additional empirical evidence that support the framework of ambivalent sexism.\n\n===Critiques===\n\nWhile the ASI is widely used and accepted among researchers,<ref name=\"Kilianski, S. E., & Rudman, L. A., 1998\"/> one limitation of the ASI is that it is a self-reported measure.<ref name=\"Sakalli-Ugurlu, 2002\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00223980209604825 |title=Turkish College Students' Attitudes Toward Women Managers: The Effects of Patriarchy, Sexism, and Gender Differences |year=2002 |last1=Sakalli-Ugurlu |first1=Nuray |last2=Beydogan |first2=Basak |journal=The Journal of Psychology |volume=136 |issue=6 |pages=647\u201356 |pmid=12523452}}</ref> [[Social desirability]] is a common limitation of self-report measures in survey research; when participants in a research study complete a written self-report questionnaire, respondents are vulnerable to answering the items in a socially desirable manner. For this reason, some researchers employ variations of the ASI in their study designs that do not require self-reports. For example, Dardeene, Dumont, and Bollier (2007) transformed some items from the ASI into scenarios, presenting them to participants to induce conditions of both hostile and benevolent sexism.<ref name=\"Dardenne, 2006\"/> Hebl, King, Glick, Singletary, and Kazama (2007) designed a field study in which they observed the sexist behaviors of others; they used the theory of ambivalent sexism and the ASI to generate items for their own measure to assess these observed behaviors.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0021-9010.92.6.1499 |title=Hostile and benevolent reactions toward pregnant women: Complementary interpersonal punishments and rewards that maintain traditional roles |year=2007 |last1=Hebl |first1=Michelle R. |last2=King |first2=Eden B. |last3=Glick |first3=Peter |last4=Singletary |first4=Sarah L. |last5=Kazama |first5=Stephanie |journal=Journal of Applied Psychology |volume=92 |issue=6 |pages=1499\u2013511 |pmid=18020792|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/24461ffb925a31d3333b85920851786688ac8c51 }}</ref>\n\nAnother criticism of the ASI is that the labels of the two sub-constructs, \"benevolent\" and \"hostile\", are too abstract, do not generalize to certain languages, and may not be relevant to some cultures.<ref name=\"Chisango, T. & Javangwe, G., 2012\"/>\n\nLastly, findings from the Conn, Hanges, Sipe, and Salvaggio (1999) study suggest that other sexism scales may measure ambivalent attitudes towards women.<ref name=\"Conn, A., Paul, H., Sipe, W., & Salvaggio, A., 1999\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/00131649921970242 |title=The Search for Ambivalent Sexism: A Comparison of Two Measures |year=1999 |last1=Conn |first1=A. B. |last2=Hanges |first2=P. J. |last3=Sipe |first3=W. P. |last4=Salvaggio |first4=A. N. |journal=Educational and Psychological Measurement |volume=59 |issue=6 |pages=898\u2013909}}</ref> Glick and Fiske originally proposed the theoretical framework of ambivalent sexism as filling a gap in the psychological literature and providing a novel tool for assessing a new dimension of sexism: benevolent sexism.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1996\"/> However, Conn and colleagues (1999), using [[confirmatory factor analysis]], showed that the Modern Sexism Scale (Swim, Aikin, Hall, and Hunter, 1995) captures ambivalent sentiments toward women, such that it identifies individuals that appear nonsexist but actually endorse sexist attitudes.<ref name=\"Conn, A., Paul, H., Sipe, W., & Salvaggio, A., 1999\"/> Results from this study suggest that, while both the Modern Sexism Scale and the ASI assess ambivalence toward women, the ASI is unique in its capabilities for separately measuring both hostile and benevolent attitudes. In addition, the ASI captures heterosexual intimacy and benevolent paternalism, whereas the Modern Sexism Scale does not.\n\n==Empirical support==\n\nWhile many individuals{{specify|date=July 2018}} endorse both benevolent and hostile sexism simultaneously, research{{by whom|date=July 2018}} suggests that people rated significantly higher in one of the two sub-components have distinct constellations of beliefs and patterns of behavior. In other words, someone who is high in benevolent sexism tends to show a different profile of attitudes than someone who is high in hostile sexism. The independence of these types of sexism in predicting human behavior indicates that the two are, in fact, discrete forms of bias on separate but related axes. Examples of research findings identifying disparate outcomes between benevolent sexism and hostile sexism are described below. In addition, the relationships between ambivalent sexism and a range of other related attitudes and behaviors are discussed.\n\n===Attitudes toward sexual harassment, intimate partner violence, and rape===\n\nMen who are ambivalently sexist (i.e., high in both benevolent and hostile sexism simultaneously) and men who are high in hostile sexism are more likely to tolerate the [[sexual harassment]] of women than men who are benevolently sexist.<ref name=\"Russell, B. L., & Trigg, K., 2004\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1023/B:SERS.0000023075.32252.fd |title=Tolerance of Sexual Harassment: An Examination of Gender Differences, Ambivalent Sexism, Social Dominance, and Gender Roles |year=2004 |last1=Russell |first1=Brenda L. |last2=Trigg |first2=Kristin Y. |journal=Sex Roles |volume=50 |issue=7/8 |pages=565\u201373}}</ref> Overall, hostile sexism is associated with acceptance of sexual harassment.<ref name=\"Begany, J., & Milburn, M., 2002\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/1524-9220.3.2.119 |title=Psychological predictors of sexual harassment: Authoritarianism, hostile sexism, and rape myths |year=2002 |last1=Begany |first1=Joseph J. |last2=Milburn |first2=Michael A. |journal=Psychology of Men & Masculinity |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=119\u201326}}</ref> In addition, the endorsement of hostile sexism is related to attitudes about [[intimate partner violence]] perpetrated by men towards women, such that people that are high in hostile sexism are more tolerant of intimate partner violence.<ref name=\"Glick, P., Sakalli-Ugurlu, N., Ferreira, M., & de Souza, M. 2002\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/1471-6402.t01-1-00068 |title=Ambivalent Sexism and Attitudes Toward Wife Abuse in Turkey and Brazil |year=2002 |last1=Glick |first1=Peter |last2=Sakalli-Ugurlu |first2=Nuray |last3=Ferreira |first3=Maria Cristina |last4=Aguiar De Souza |first4=Marcos |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=292\u20137}}</ref> Benevolently sexist attitudes were not found to be a significant predictor of the tolerance of intimate partner violence. However, the endorsement of benevolent sexism was not a protective factor either. Lastly, men high in hostile sexism are more likely to rape women, whereas men that are high in benevolent sexism are more likely to [[Victim-blaming|blame a victim]] of rape for the attack.<ref name=\"Viki & Abrams, 2002\">{{cite journal |title=But She Was Unfaithful: Benevolent Sexism and Reactions to Rape Victims Who Violate Traditional Gender Role Expectations|doi=10.1023/A:1021342912248 |year=2002 |last1=Viki |first1=G. Tendayi |last2=Abrams |first2=Dominic |journal=Sex Roles |volume=47 |issue=5/6 |pages=289\u201393}}</ref>\n\n===Close relationships and attraction===\n\nResearch has shown that sexist attitudes relate to preferences for certain characteristics in romantic partners.<ref name=\"Sibley & Overall, 2011\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684311401838 |title=A Dual Process Motivational Model of Ambivalent Sexism and Gender Differences in Romantic Partner Preferences |year=2011 |last1=Sibley |first1=C. G. |last2=Overall |first2=N. C. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=303\u201317}}</ref> Evidence suggests that women with higher levels of benevolent sexism have more stereotypical preferences in men as romantic partners, such as financial security and resources. Men with higher levels of hostile sexism are more likely to value physical attractiveness in women as romantic partners. In addition, benevolent sexism tends to predict mate selection, whereas hostile sexism tend to predict subsequent marriage norms after pairing.<ref name=\"Chen, Fiske, & Lee, 2009\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-009-9585-9 |title=Ambivalent Sexism and Power-Related Gender-role Ideology in Marriage |year=2009 |last1=Chen |first1=Zhixia |last2=Fiske |first2=Susan T. |last3=Lee |first3=Tiane L. |journal=Sex Roles |volume=60 |issue=11\u201312 |pages=765\u2013778 |pmid=24058258 |pmc=3777654}}</ref> Women find men high in benevolent sexism attractive, and rate men high in ambivalent sexism as less attractive.<ref name=\"Bohner, Ahlborn, & Steiner, 2010\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-009-9665-x |title=How Sexy are Sexist Men? Women's Perception of Male Response Profiles in the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory |year=2009 |last1=Bohner |first1=Gerd |last2=Ahlborn |first2=Katrin |last3=Steiner |first3=Regine |journal=Sex Roles |volume=62 |issue=7\u20138 |pages=568\u201382}}</ref> Furthermore, in a recent research study on a particular aspect of benevolent sexism, protective paternalistic beliefs, women endorsed more protective paternalistic beliefs for men (toward women) in romantic versus work contexts. The endorsement of these beliefs in romantic contexts is thought to serve to reinforce and maintain such benevolent sexist behaviors.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684312454842 |title=Prescription of Protective Paternalism for Men in Romantic and Work Contexts |year=2012 |last1=Sarlet |first1=M. |last2=Dumont |first2=M. |last3=Delacollette |first3=N. |last4=Dardenne |first4=B. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=444\u201357|url=http://orbi.ulg.ac.be/handle/2268/129459 }}</ref> Overall, benevolent sexism and hostile sexism are associated with beliefs that [[premarital sex]] is unacceptable for women.<ref name=\"Sakalli-Ugurlu & Glick, 2003\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00224490309552194 |title=Ambivalent sexism and attitudes toward women who engage in premarital sex in Turkey |year=2003 |last1=Sakalh\u2010U\u011furlu |first1=Nuray |last2=Glick |first2=Peter |journal=Journal of Sex Research |volume=40 |issue=3 |pages=296\u2013302 |pmid=14533024}}</ref>\n\n===Women in the workplace===\n\nWhile the consequences of hostile sexism in the workplace are more widely known and accepted, research has shown that benevolent sexism may have a more severe impact on a women's cognitive performance.<ref name=\"Dardenne, 2006\"/> Dardenne, et al.(2006) suggested that hostile sexism can elicit anger or frustration in the target, which may increase her motivation to succeed or perform. Benevolent sexism, because of its seemingly positive evaluations and implicit attributions, is likely to hinder a woman's confidence and performance. The researchers showed that, in a typical team working environment, hostile sexism as well as benevolent sexism had consequences for the participant's performance. Masser and Abrams (2004) highlighted the fact that previous research has shown that benevolent sexism can have detrimental effects on a woman's performance evaluation if that woman violates social norms associated with certain sexist attitudes.<ref name=\"Masser, B. M.& Abrams, D., 2004\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-004-5470-8 |title=Reinforcing the Glass Ceiling: The Consequences of Hostile Sexism for Female Managerial Candidates |year=2004 |last1=Masser |first1=Barbara M. |last2=Abrams |first2=Dominic |journal=Sex Roles |volume=51 |issue=9\u201310 |pages=609\u201316|url=http://kar.kent.ac.uk/4384/1/abrams_reinforcing_glass.pdf }}</ref> Their study showed that hostile sexism, but not benevolent sexism, hurt women's evaluations and recommendations for promotion.\n\nAdditionally, studies have shown that benevolent sexist attitudes lead to lower professional evaluations from men and women.<ref name=\"Glick, P. 1997\"/><ref name=\"Masser, B. M.& Abrams, D., 2004\"/> Using an experimental design, Masser and Abrams (2004) found that individuals with hostile sexist attitudes rated women lower when applying for a male-dominant position. Additionally, high hostile sexist individuals recommend men to fill the available position more often than women. The authors argue that this is one of the main contributors to the [[glass ceiling]] effect.\n\n===Help-seeking===\n\nIn a recent experimental study on the effects of benevolent sexism on [[help-seeking]] behaviors, researchers found that, when stereotypes of women as dependent were made salient, female college students were less willing to seek help. In addition, the more that help was sought, the worse women felt.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0361684312457659 |title=Thanks, but No Thanks: Women's Avoidance of Help-Seeking in the Context of a Dependency-Related Stereotype |year=2012 |last1=Wakefield |first1=J. R. H. |last2=Hopkins |first2=N. |last3=Greenwood |first3=R. M. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=423\u201331|url=http://irep.ntu.ac.uk/id/eprint/20119/1/220483_2565.pdf }}</ref> Therefore, benevolent sexism appears to hold consequences towards women's help-seeking when certain benevolent sexist stereotypes are made salient.\n\n=== Voting Behaviour ===\nDuring the 2016 US Presidential Election, researchers connected ambivalent sexism to voting intentions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/usappblog/2016/10/10/a-basket-of-deplorables-a-new-study-finds-that-trump-supporters-are-more-likely-to-be-islamophobic-racist-transphobic-and-homophobic/|title=A 'basket of deplorables'? A new study finds that Trump supporters are more likely to be Islamophobic, racist, transphobic and homophobic.|date=2016-10-10|newspaper=USAPP|last1=Blair |first1= Karen L. |language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-13}}</ref> In a non-representative sample of US voters, predominantly male, ambivalent sexism was found to be the sole predictor of intending to vote for someone other than Hillary Clinton in the election. For every step up on the Ambivalent Sexism Inventory, participants were 3.3 times more likely to be voting for someone other than Hillary Clinton. Of those not voting for Clinton, they were not necessarily being pulled over to the Trump campaign, but rather, many were intending to vote Third Party or were still undecided. While higher Islamophobia predicted a vote for Trump, lower Islamophobia and ''higher'' ambivalent sexism predicted being undecided or voting for a Third Party.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nAmbivalent sexism may also be endorsed by the media in the presentation of electoral candidates, consequentially influencing voting behaviour. In the article ''The Psychology of Voting, Digested'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sts.uea.ac.uk/adfs/ls/?SAMLRequest=jZJRT4MwEMe%2FStP3UUBgsxksuMW4ZCrZmA%2B%2BdeW2EaFFrkz99tYhyXxZTPp29%2B%2Bv97tOZ591RU7QYqlVTD3HpQSU1EWpDjHd5vejCZ0lUxR11fC0M0e1hvcO0BCbU8jPhZh2reJaYIlciRqQG8k36eOK%2B47Lm1YbLXVFSYoIrbGguVbY1dBuoD2VErbrVUyPxjTIGav0oVSObkAJcwSFjgLDfjDMZ0IiJQtLL23x%2FOAhhQadDoQjpNO9MVHskVXIKFkuYgphEIYycGEc7YN9CLvIl4Ece0UQRmMhI9uF2MFSoRHKxNR3vduR59mTexPu%2BjwMnJsweKUk%2Bx3lrlS9oGtz7%2Fom5A95no2y501Oycsg2jbQXis%2Fw9sLn9evFYNEmvxHWQ1GFMKIETZTdsEbdvpkActFpqtSfpG0qvTHvAVhwP4FypI%2B8nfzyTc%3D&RelayState=%2Fsaml%2F2%2Fsso%2Fuea.ac.uk%2Fc%2Fukfed%3FSAMLRequest%3DfZLNboMwEIRfBfkeDASS1gpINDk0UtqiQHvopTJmCVbApqzpz9sXQqukl0i%252Bzey3OyOvkDd1y%252BLeVGoP7z2gsb6aWiE7CSHpO8U0R4lM8QaQGcHS%252BGHHPNthbaeNFromVowInZFarbXCvoEuhe5DCnje70JSGdMioxQrmee6BlPZkKPQlUZjC93Q9CwgajryPZo8pRmxNsNBUvERfQbV%252BiCVrVsYhAoU2goMHe%252BlHh0BPXCbC7s%252FUkH7YwkFsbabkLwtvEIE%252BbIoA7%252BEBYgg8OfgOKU3ny8dL%252FAHG2IPW4WGKxMSz3FvZ647vMy9YY7HAv%252BVWMlv6jupCqkO1yvKJxOy%252ByxLZlOmF%252BjwlGcwkGg1Hs5Oi7uL6q9j%252BV%252FfJBpLuVLuil7wp2UtexyA202iaym%252Brbiu9ee6A24gJC6h0TTy%252F1NEPw%253D%253D%26RelayState%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fshibboleth.ebscohost.com%252FShibAgent.aspx%253Fshib_returl%253Dhttps%25253a%25252f%25252fsearch.ebscohost.com%25252flogin.aspx%25253fdirect%25253dtrue%252526db%25253da9h%252526AN%25253d102236392%252526authtype%25253dsso%252526custid%25253ds8993828%252526site%25253deds-live%252526scope%25253dsite%2526IdpId%253D|title=Sign In|website=sts.uea.ac.uk|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> a study is noted which revealed that 'obesity is a disadvantage for female candidates, but may help male candidates'. This is one example of how media coverage of female electoral candidates can prioritise appearance over capability, often using the former to shed a negative light over the latter.\n\nIt's also important to acknowledge that ambivalent sexism has a disproportionate effect on women of colour, and groups of women who may be more so marginalised because of the physical geography of where, or socio-political condition in which they live. The cost of voting participation may be too high for women; as put in an economic journal on female voting behaviour in Pakistan <ref>''Gine, X., & Mansuri, G. (2018). Together We Will: Experimental Evidence on Female Voting Behavior in Pakistan. American Economic Journal: Applied Economics, 10(1), 207\u2013235. <nowiki>https://doi.org/http://www.aeaweb.org/aej-applied/</nowiki>''</ref> , this might be because of 'cultural stereotypes that discourage the exercise of own preferences'. That is to say in an election, for example, the outcome may be a relatively low count of female voters when women are unable to choose to be active political agents alongside other socio-cultural responsibilities. \n\n<br />\n\n=== Plan A vs. Plan B ===\nBenevolent sexism is sometimes also referred to as Plan A. It can be used to have women act as a subordinate because it aims for the remarks to be perceived as \u2018good\u2019 or \u2018positive\u2019.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Gender: Ideas, Interactions, and Institutions 2nd Edition|last=Lisa Wade|first=Myra Marx Ferree|year=2019|isbn=978-0-393-66796-7|location=|pages=}}</ref> This targets a woman\u2019s sensitivity and need to be protected by a male, which may not seem so bad to some women. Plan B or hostile sexism is used as a more aggressive approach as it includes more harsh remarks, and can tend to anger the women more. Studies show that women are more likely to be defensive and inspired to protest against sexism when exposed to hostile sexist statements. When exposed to benevolently sexist remarks, they\u2019re less likely rally and protest. They take on a more subordinate and passive role. This is why benevolent sexism is Plan A when trying to get women to be subordinate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/psysociety/benevolent-sexism/|title=The Problem When Sexism Just Sounds So Darn Friendly...|last=Tannenbaum|first=Melanie|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Women's endorsement of ambivalent sexism==\n\nBoth benevolent and hostile sexism are considered legitimizing ideologies, in that these attitudes provide the justification for social inequalities between men and women.<ref name=\"Sidanius, Pratto, & Bobo, 1994\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.67.6.998 |title=Social dominance orientation and the political psychology of gender: A case of invariance? |year=1994 |last1=Sidanius |first1=Jim |last2=Pratto |first2=Felicia |last3=Bobo |first3=Lawrence |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=67 |issue=6 |pages=998\u20131011}}</ref> [[Social dominance orientation]] (SDO; Sidanius & Pratto, 1999) asserts that group-based inequalities are systematically reinforced by the disadvantaged group's adoption of the dominant group's ideology and social stratification.<ref name=\"Sidanius & Pratto 1999\">{{cite book |last1=Sidanius |first1=Jim |last2=Pratto |first2=Felicia |year=1999 |title=Social Dominance: An Intergroup Theory of Social Hierarchy and Oppression |location=New York |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-62290-5|doi=10.1017/CBO9781139175043}}{{page needed|date=November 2013}}</ref> Empirical research has consistently supported the validity of Social Dominance Theory,<ref name=\"Gaucher, Frieser, & Kay, 2011\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/a0022530 |title=Evidence that gendered wording in job advertisements exists and sustains gender inequality |year=2011 |last1=Gaucher |first1=Danielle |last2=Friesen |first2=Justin |last3=Kay |first3=Aaron C. |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |volume=101 |pages=109\u201328 |pmid=21381851 |issue=1}}</ref> and the SDO model of structural oppression may be particularly apt to describe how patriarchy is perpetuated.<ref name=\"Sibley et al, 2009\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s11199-008-9554-8 |title=Your Sexism Predicts My Sexism: Perceptions of Men's (but not Women's) Sexism Affects One's Own Sexism over Time |year=2008 |last1=Sibley |first1=Chris G. |last2=Overall |first2=Nickola C. |last3=Duckitt |first3=John |last4=Perry |first4=Ryan |last5=Milfont |first5=Taciano L. |last6=Khan |first6=Sammyh S. |last7=Fischer |first7=Ronald |last8=Robertson |first8=Andrew |journal=Sex Roles |volume=60 |issue=9\u201310 |pages=682\u201393}}</ref>\n\nResearchers have explored reasons for why women might [[Internalisation (sociology)|internalize]] ambivalently sexist attitudes towards women. Fischer (2006) found that women may develop benevolently sexist attitudes as a response to experiencing sexism themselves.<ref name=\"Fischer, 2006\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1471-6402.2006.00316.x |title=Women's Benevolent Sexism As Reaction to Hostility |year=2006 |last1=Fischer |first1=Ann R. |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=30 |issue=4 |pages=410\u20136}}</ref> Cross-cultural research suggests that women's endorsement of benevolent sexism often reflects a culture of extreme hostile sexism among men in a given community.<ref name=\"Glick et al., 2000\"/> Some researchers argue that, in cultures that are particularly hostile, women may internalize benevolent sexism as a protective mechanism.\n\nSome research indicates that women perceived men high in benevolent sexism to possess positive attitudes towards women, while by contrast men low in benevolent sexism were perceived to be misogynistic and possessing high levels of hostile sexism, when in reality men who reject benevolent sexism also tend to reject hostile sexism. If the man stated that his rejection of benevolent sexism was motivated by egalitarian values then the perception that he was a hostile sexist was somewhat mitigated, though not entirely.<ref>Yeung, Amy. [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/45b2/607b3f62fe4d0029ee602103d1a0811f11f1.pdf \"Chivalry is far from dead: Misperceiving the link between men's benevolent and hostile sexism.\"] (2018).</ref><ref>Yeung, Amy. \"Lay misperceptions of the relationship between men\u2019s benevolent and hostile sexism.\" Master's thesis, University of Waterloo, 2012.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ambivalent prejudice]]\n* [[Women are wonderful]]\n* [[Aversive racism]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last1=Good |first1=Jessica J. |editor1-last=Nadal |editor1-first=K.L. |title=The SAGE Encyclopedia of Psychology and Gender|date=2017 |publisher=SAGE Publications |location=Thousand Oaks, Calif. |isbn=978-1-48-338427-6 |pages=136\u20137 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=lVYoDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 |language=en |chapter=Benevolent Sexism}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sexism]]\n[[Category:Gender theories]]\n\n[[fr:Sexisme ambivalent]]\n", "name_user": "83.24.94.87", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ambivalent_sexism"}
